window.ACLS_DATA = {"manifest":{"id":"acls","title":"ACLS — Advanced Cardiovascular Life Support","subtitle":"The Ultimate Provider Course Reviewer","version":"1.0.0","edition":"Based on the AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC","description":"A comprehensive, self-contained study reviewer for Advanced Cardiovascular Life Support. Each chapter includes a concise summary, clinical pearls, red flags, common mistakes, memory aids, decision trees, high-yield flashcards, AHA-style quiz questions, realistic scenarios, structured algorithms, and drug/energy tables. Designed for paramedics, nurses, physicians, respiratory therapists, and medical/nursing students preparing for ACLS Provider certification.","icon":"heart-pulse","color":"#c8102e","accentColor":"#1f6feb","estimatedHours":16,"difficulty":"Intermediate to Advanced","certification":"AHA ACLS Provider","examLink":"https://cpr.heart.org/","audience":["Paramedic","Nurse","Physician","Respiratory Therapist","Medical Student","Nursing Student","Healthcare Provider"],"prerequisites":["BLS provider competency","Basic ECG rhythm recognition","Basic pharmacology"],"contentTypes":["summary","flashcards","quizzes","scenarios","algorithms","tables"],"chapters":[{"id":"c01","number":1,"title":"Systems of Care & the Chain of Survival","section":"Foundations","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c02","number":2,"title":"High-Quality BLS Inside ACLS & Team Dynamics","section":"Foundations","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c03","number":3,"title":"Airway Management & Waveform Capnography","section":"Airway","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c04","number":4,"title":"Rhythm Recognition for ACLS","section":"Rhythms","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c05","number":5,"title":"Defibrillation, Cardioversion & Pacing","section":"Electrical Therapy","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c06","number":6,"title":"Cardiac Arrest: VF / Pulseless VT","section":"Cardiac Arrest","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c07","number":7,"title":"Cardiac Arrest: Asystole / PEA","section":"Cardiac Arrest","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c08","number":8,"title":"Pharmacology of Cardiac Arrest","section":"Cardiac Arrest","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c09","number":9,"title":"Reversible Causes: H's & T's and Refractory Arrest","section":"Cardiac Arrest","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c10","number":10,"title":"Bradycardia With a Pulse","section":"Peri-Arrest","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c11","number":11,"title":"Tachycardia With a Pulse","section":"Peri-Arrest","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c12","number":12,"title":"Acute Coronary Syndromes","section":"Emergencies","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c13","number":13,"title":"Acute Stroke","section":"Emergencies","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c14","number":14,"title":"Post-Cardiac Arrest Care, ECPR & Recovery","section":"Post-Arrest","difficulty":"Advanced"}]},"chapters":{"c01":{"id":"c01","title":"Systems of Care & the Chain of Survival","shortTitle":"Systems of Care","estimatedStudyTime":30,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Describe how ACLS providers extend and strengthen every link of the 2025 AHA universal Chain of Survival.","Differentiate the systems-of-care emphasis for out-of-hospital cardiac arrest (OHCA) versus in-hospital cardiac arrest (IHCA).","Explain the rationale for regionalized cardiac arrest centers and post-arrest transfer.","Describe continuous quality improvement (CQI) and Utstein-style reporting as tools for system performance.","Explain why post-cardiac arrest care is a continuation of resuscitation rather than an afterthought.","Describe the multidisciplinary, team-based nature of an ACLS resuscitation.","Identify the role of early-warning scores and rapid-response teams in preventing in-hospital arrest."],"summary":[{"title":"From BLS to ACLS: Extending the Chain","content":"ACLS builds directly on BLS. The first links of the 2025 universal Chain of Survival — recognition, activation, high-quality CPR, and early defibrillation — remain the strongest predictors of survival, and ACLS providers must protect them even while adding advanced airway management, IV/IO access, rhythm-specific therapy, and drug administration. Advanced interventions never replace high-quality compressions and early defibrillation; they are layered on top of a BLS foundation that cannot be interrupted for long."},{"title":"The 2025 Universal Chain of Survival — the ACLS Provider's View","content":"The six-link universal chain (activation, high-quality CPR, defibrillation, advanced resuscitation interventions, post-cardiac arrest care, recovery) applies across all settings, with a separate Neonatal Chain of Care for newborns. ACLS providers are the primary owners of link 4 (advanced resuscitation interventions: airway, rhythm therapy, medications, treatment of reversible causes) and share ownership of link 5 (post-cardiac arrest care) with critical-care and cardiology teams. A weak link anywhere in the chain — including a delayed or interrupted advanced intervention — degrades the whole system's performance."},{"title":"Systems of Care: OHCA versus IHCA","content":"Out-of-hospital systems depend on bystander CPR, dispatcher-assisted instructions, public-access AEDs, and EMS response times; ACLS-level care begins when advanced providers arrive and continues through transport and hospital hand-off. In-hospital systems emphasize surveillance and prevention — continuous monitoring, early-warning scores, and rapid-response or medical emergency teams — so many arrests are recognized and treated before a full arrest occurs. Both systems converge on the same standard once ACLS-level care begins: high-quality CPR, minimal interruptions, and rhythm-appropriate therapy."},{"title":"Regionalized Cardiac Arrest Centers","content":"Evidence increasingly supports triaging resuscitated (or refractory) cardiac arrest patients to specialized cardiac arrest centers capable of 24/7 coronary angiography/PCI, targeted temperature management, multimodal neuroprognostication, and ECPR when indicated, analogous to trauma and stroke systems of care. Where such regionalized systems exist, protocols should route appropriate post-ROSC and refractory-arrest patients to these centers rather than the nearest facility alone."},{"title":"Continuous Quality Improvement & Utstein Reporting","content":"High-performing resuscitation systems measure what they do: chest compression fraction, time to first shock, time to epinephrine, ROSC rate, survival to discharge, and neurologic outcome, using standardized Utstein-style templates so performance can be compared across systems and over time. Debriefing after real events (and after simulation), combined with data-driven feedback, is how teams and systems improve — CQI is itself a component of the chain, not a separate add-on."},{"title":"Post-Cardiac Arrest Care as Continued Resuscitation","content":"The 2025 guidelines emphasize that post-cardiac arrest care is a direct continuation of resuscitation, not a separate phase that begins after ROSC. The same team mindset — anticipate deterioration, treat reversible causes, communicate in closed loops — carries forward into airway/ventilation management, hemodynamic support, temperature control, urgent coronary evaluation, and early planning for neuroprognostication and recovery."}],"clinicalPearls":["Advanced interventions are additive, not substitutive — they must never come at the cost of compression fraction or time to first shock.","In-hospital systems win by preventing arrest (surveillance, early-warning scores); out-of-hospital systems win by compressing the time from collapse to CPR and shock.","Consider regionalized cardiac arrest center transfer for post-ROSC and refractory-arrest patients where systems of care support it.","What isn't measured isn't improved — CQI metrics (CCF, time-to-shock, time-to-epinephrine) are core system components, not paperwork."],"redFlags":["Advanced procedures (intubation, IV/IO attempts) causing long pauses in chest compressions.","Treating ROSC as the end of the resuscitation rather than the start of the post-arrest phase.","No local process for identifying candidates for cardiac arrest center transfer or CQI review."],"commonMistakes":["Prioritizing advanced airway placement over compression quality and early defibrillation.","Assuming systems-of-care improvement is an administrative task unrelated to bedside providers.","Failing to debrief after an arrest, losing the chance to identify system gaps."],"memoryAids":["'BLS first, ACLS on top' — advanced care layers onto, never replaces, compressions and defibrillation.","OHCA = bystanders and speed; IHCA = surveillance and prevention.","Measure it to improve it — CCF, time-to-shock, time-to-epi, survival, neuro outcome."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"ACLS Provider's Place in the System of Care","content":"Cardiac arrest recognized (OHCA or IHCA)\n  → Link 1: Activation — call for help / activate resuscitation team\n  → Link 2: High-quality CPR — protect this throughout everything that follows\n  → Link 3: Defibrillation — shock a shockable rhythm ASAP, resume compressions immediately\n  → Link 4 (ACLS provider's primary role): advanced airway when indicated, IV/IO access, rhythm-specific drugs, treat H's & T's\n  → ROSC achieved\n     → Link 5: Post-cardiac arrest care — airway/ventilation, hemodynamics, 12-lead ECG, temperature control, consider cardiac arrest center transfer\n  → Link 6: Recovery — neuroprognostication timeline, rehabilitation, survivor and family support\n  → System feedback: CQI review / Utstein-style data feeds back into training and protocols"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Executive Summary and Systems of Care","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 11: Post-Cardiac Arrest Care"]},"c02":{"id":"c02","title":"High-Quality BLS Inside ACLS & Team Dynamics","shortTitle":"BLS Quality & Teams","estimatedStudyTime":30,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["State the compression rate, depth, and recoil targets that must be preserved throughout an ACLS resuscitation.","Explain chest compression fraction (CCF) and why it is a core team performance metric.","Describe the ventilation strategy once an advanced airway is placed (continuous compressions + 1 breath every 6 seconds).","List the core elements of effective resuscitation team dynamics.","Describe closed-loop communication and give an example.","Explain the concept of constructive intervention and when a team member should use it.","Describe the role of a dedicated CPR coach during a resuscitation."],"summary":[{"title":"Why BLS Quality Doesn't Stop When ACLS Starts","content":"Every ACLS intervention is built on top of high-quality BLS. Adding drugs, airways, and rhythm therapy does not lower the bar for compressions — it raises the stakes of protecting them. Teams that let compression quality slip while focusing on advanced tasks lose the single strongest driver of survival."},{"title":"Compression Quality Targets in ACLS","content":"Rate 100–120/min; depth at least 2 in (5 cm) and not more than 2.4 in (6 cm); full chest recoil between compressions; minimize interruptions and keep any pause under 10 seconds; switch the compressor roughly every 2 minutes (or sooner if fatigued) to prevent quality decay. Chest compression fraction (CCF) — the proportion of resuscitation time spent actually compressing — should be at least 60%, and ideally above 80%; it is one of the most important team performance metrics because every pause, no matter how well-intentioned, drops it."},{"title":"Ventilation Once an Advanced Airway Is Placed","content":"Before an advanced airway, compressions and breaths remain cycled 30:2. Once a supraglottic airway or endotracheal tube is in place, compressions become continuous (no more pausing for breaths) and a single breath is delivered every 6 seconds (about 10 breaths/min), timed independently of the compression cycle. Avoid excessive ventilation rate or volume — over-ventilation raises intrathoracic pressure, reduces venous return, and lowers cardiac output during CPR."},{"title":"Core Elements of Team Dynamics","content":"Effective resuscitation teams rely on: clearly defined roles known to everyone before the code; closed-loop communication (order given by name and content, receiver repeats it back, sender confirms); clear, concise messages instead of vague or shouted ones; knowing and communicating your own limitations before attempting a task; constructive intervention when an error is about to happen; frequent reevaluation of the patient and plan; and mutual respect maintained even under stress."},{"title":"Closed-Loop Communication in Practice","content":"The team leader assigns a task to a named person ('Sarah, push epinephrine 1 mg now'), the receiver acknowledges and states the action ('Giving epinephrine 1 mg now'), and confirms completion ('Epinephrine 1 mg given'). This loop prevents duplicated or missed interventions and keeps the whole team's mental model synchronized, especially in a loud, high-stress environment."},{"title":"Constructive Intervention and the CPR Coach","content":"Any team member who notices an error — a drug about to be given twice, a pulse check taking too long, compression depth trailing off — should speak up immediately and respectfully; a good leader invites this rather than punishing it. Many systems now designate a CPR coach whose only job is to watch compression quality (rate, depth, recoil, pauses) and give real-time feedback, freeing the team leader to focus on rhythm interpretation and overall management."}],"clinicalPearls":["CCF is a team score, not an individual one — everyone's pauses count against it.","Once an advanced airway is in, stop counting cycles of 30:2 — it's continuous compressions plus one breath every 6 seconds.","A closed loop takes two seconds and prevents a double dose or a missed task; skipping it to 'save time' usually costs more time later.","Silence during a resuscitation is a red flag — a quiet team is not necessarily a smooth one."],"redFlags":["Compression pauses creeping past 10 seconds for pulse checks, rhythm analysis, or airway attempts.","No one has been assigned to track time and compression quality (no CPR coach or timer role).","Team members hesitating to speak up about a perceived error because of hierarchy."],"commonMistakes":["Continuing 30:2 cycling after an advanced airway is already in place.","Vague, unaddressed orders ('someone give epi') instead of naming a specific person.","Allowing compression rate to drift above 120/min under adrenaline and stress, sacrificing depth and recoil."],"memoryAids":["'Airway in, cycle out' — advanced airway means continuous compressions, no more 30:2.","Closed loop: Say it, do it, confirm it.","CCF ≥60%, ideally >80% — protect it like a vital sign."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Ventilation Strategy During Arrest","content":"Cardiac arrest, CPR ongoing\n  → No advanced airway yet: 30 compressions : 2 breaths, minimize pause for breaths\n  → Advanced airway placed (SGA or ETT) and confirmed\n     → Continuous compressions (no pause for breaths)\n     → 1 breath every 6 seconds (~10/min), avoid hyperventilation\n  → Reassess quality every ~2 minutes: rate, depth, recoil, CCF, switch compressor"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support (CPR Quality)","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Adult Basic Life Support (Ventilation With an Advanced Airway)"]},"c03":{"id":"c03","title":"Airway Management & Waveform Capnography","shortTitle":"Airway & Capnography","estimatedStudyTime":35,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Compare bag-valve-mask (BVM) ventilation, supraglottic airway (SGA) insertion, and endotracheal (ET) intubation as advanced airway options during cardiac arrest.","Describe the indications, advantages, and limitations of supraglottic airways (i-gel, King LT) in resuscitation.","Explain the appropriate timing of endotracheal intubation during CPR and the measures needed to minimize compression interruptions.","Interpret waveform capnography to confirm ET tube placement, monitor CPR quality, and detect ROSC.","State the ETCO2 target during CPR and the threshold value that suggests return of spontaneous circulation.","Describe how waveform capnography serves as the gold standard for advanced airway confirmation.","Integrate advanced airway management with the concurrent goals of high-quality CPR and rhythm-specific therapy."],"summary":[{"title":"Advanced Airway Options in Cardiac Arrest","content":"During cardiac arrest, ACLS providers must secure an airway that allows effective ventilation while minimizing interruptions to chest compressions. The three primary options are bag-valve-mask (BVM) ventilation, supraglottic airways (SGAs) such as the i-gel and King LT, and endotracheal (ET) intubation. BVM with an oropharyngeal adjunct is the fastest to initiate and serves as the bridge to a more secure airway. SGAs are quicker to insert than an ET tube and require less skill to place, making them reasonable alternatives when intubation is not immediately available or when the intubation attempt would cause prolonged compression pauses. ET intubation provides the most definitive airway protection and allows precise ventilation control, but it requires experienced providers, causes compression interruptions during placement, and carries the risk of unrecognized esophageal intubation."},{"title":"Supraglottic Airways: i-gel and King LT","content":"The i-gel is a single-use SGA with a non-inflatable, gel-filled cushion that conforms to the perilaryngeal anatomy, requiring no cuff inflation. The King LT (and King LTS-D) is a dual-lumen SGA with a proximal and distal cuff that seals the esophagus and pharynx, directing gas flow through side ports into the glottis. Both devices can be inserted rapidly (typically under 15 seconds), do not require laryngoscopy, and provide a reasonable seal for positive-pressure ventilation. SGAs are particularly valuable in cardiac arrest because they allow relatively rapid airway establishment with minimal interruption of compressions. However, they do not provide absolute aspiration protection, and gastric insufflation can still occur. Position should be confirmed with waveform capnography after placement."},{"title":"Endotracheal Intubation During CPR","content":"When ET intubation is performed during cardiac arrest, the 2025 AHA Guidelines emphasize that it must be integrated without causing prolonged pauses in chest compressions. A single operator experienced in laryngoscopy should perform the attempt while another provider delivers continuous compressions using a mechanical device or a modified technique (e.g., jaw thrust without interrupting compressions). Video laryngoscopy is preferred over direct laryngoscopy when available because it may reduce first-pass failure and compression pauses. Each intubation attempt should not exceed 10 seconds. After placement, tube position must be confirmed immediately with waveform capnography. If ETCO2 is absent after intubation, the tube should be assumed to be esophageally placed and repositioned or replaced before ventilation continues."},{"title":"Waveform Capnography: The Gold Standard for Airway Confirmation","content":"Waveform capnography measures the concentration of carbon dioxide in exhaled breath and is the gold standard for confirming and continuously monitoring ET tube placement. Proper ET tube placement is confirmed by the presence of a characteristic rectangular waveform with a consistent ETCO2 reading on every breath cycle. The absence of a waveform after intubation strongly suggests esophageal placement, and the tube must be repositioned or replaced. A sudden loss of waveform with persistent effort may indicate tube displacement, obstruction, or cardiac arrest. Continuous waveform capnography should be displayed on the monitor throughout resuscitation once an advanced airway is in place."},{"title":"ETCO2 During CPR: Monitoring Quality and Detecting ROSC","content":"During cardiac arrest, ETCO2 reflects cardiac output because CO2 delivery to the lungs depends on blood flow generated by chest compressions. The 2025 AHA Guidelines identify an ETCO2 target of at least 10 mmHg during CPR as a marker of adequate compression quality. An ETCO2 persistently below 10 mmHg despite correct compression technique suggests inadequate compression rate, depth, recoil, or fraction, and should prompt reassessment of CPR quality. A sudden, sustained rise in ETCO2 — typically to values at or above 40 mmHg — during CPR is a reliable indicator of return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC) because the restoration of native cardiac output delivers substantially more CO2 to the lungs. This early ROSC detection allows the team to immediately transition to post-arrest care without waiting for a manual pulse check."},{"title":"Integrating Airway Management with High-Quality CPR","content":"Advanced airway management during cardiac arrest must never become the centerpiece of the resuscitation at the expense of compression quality. The correct sequence is: (1) begin and maintain high-quality BVM ventilation as part of BLS; (2) when an advanced airway provider is ready, insert the chosen device during compressions with minimal interruption; (3) confirm placement with waveform capnography; (4) continue CPR with continuous waveform capnography monitoring; (5) use ETCO2 values to guide compression quality and detect ROSC. At no point should the team pause compressions to troubleshoot ventilation for an extended period. If an SGA or ET tube is not successfully placed on the first attempt, immediately return to BVM ventilation and high-quality CPR before reattempting."}],"clinicalPearls":["Waveform capnography is the gold standard for ET tube placement confirmation — auscultation alone is insufficient during cardiac arrest.","ETCO2 persistently below 10 mmHg during CPR indicates poor compression quality and should trigger immediate reassessment of rate, depth, recoil, and fraction.","A sudden, sustained ETCO2 rise to 40 mmHg or above during CPR is a reliable indicator of ROSC — anticipate the pulse check and transition to post-arrest care.","Supraglottic airways are faster to place than ET tubes and cause fewer compression interruptions — they are reasonable alternatives when intubation is not immediately feasible.","Video laryngoscopy is preferred over direct laryngoscopy during cardiac arrest because it may reduce first-pass failure and compression pause duration.","Each intubation attempt should not exceed 10 seconds to minimize compression interruption."],"redFlags":["Absence of a capnography waveform after intubation — this is esophageal placement until proven otherwise.","ETCO2 persistently below 10 mmHg without reassessment of compression quality.","Extended compression pauses (>10 seconds) during intubation attempts or SGA placement.","Loss of the capnography waveform without clinical explanation — suspect tube displacement or obstruction.","Relying on auscultation and chest rise alone to confirm tube position without capnography."],"commonMistakes":["Prolonging compression pauses beyond 10 seconds for intubation attempts without adequate justification.","Failing to confirm ET tube placement with waveform capnography after every insertion attempt.","Over-ventilating after advanced airway placement, which can cause gastric insufflation and reduce coronary perfusion pressure.","Not using capnography to monitor CPR quality throughout the resuscitation, missing an opportunity to optimize compressions.","Attempting repeated intubation without returning to BVM ventilation between attempts."],"memoryAids":["'10-40-10 rule': ETCO2 below 10 mmHg = poor compressions; sudden rise above 40 mmHg = probable ROSC; every attempt under 10 seconds.","Waveform = yes = tube is tracheal; no waveform = tube is esophageal.","SGA first, tube if ready — supraglottic airways are fast and effective; ET intubation when the experienced provider can do it without long pauses.","Capnography watches the compressions for you — it tells you how hard you're pushing, not just where the tube is."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Advanced Airway Decision During CPR","content":"Cardiac arrest in progress, BVM ventilation underway\n  → Is an experienced intubation provider available without delaying compressions?\n     → YES → Attempt ET intubation during continuous compressions\n        → Attempt <10 seconds, confirm with waveform capnography\n        → Waveform present → Continue CPR with continuous capnography\n        → No waveform → Assume esophageal placement, reposition, return to BVM between attempts\n     → NO → Insert supraglottic airway (i-gel or King LT) during compressions\n        → Confirm with waveform capnography\n        → Waveform present → Continue CPR with continuous capnography\n        → No waveform → Reposition or replace; return to BVM between attempts\n  → Once advanced airway secured:\n     → Confirm with continuous waveform capnography\n     → Target ETCO2 ≥10 mmHg (compression quality goal)\n     → Sudden ETCO2 rise ≥40 mmHg → suspect ROSC → pulse check"},{"title":"ETCO2-Guided CPR Quality Feedback Loop","content":"Waveform capnography active during CPR\n  → ETCO2 ≥10 mmHg → Compressions are likely adequate; continue current technique\n  → ETCO2 persistently <10 mmHg → Reassess CPR quality:\n     → Rate 100–120/min?\n     → Depth ≥2 inches (5 cm) in adults?\n     → Full chest recoil between compressions?\n     → Compression fraction ≥80%?\n     → Correct any deficiency and reassess ETCO2\n  → Sudden sustained ETCO2 ≥40 mmHg → Possible ROSC → Manual pulse check → If pulse present → Transition to post-arrest care"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 5: Adult BLS and CPR Quality","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Executive Summary: Airway Management and Ventilation"],"graphics":[{"id":"c03_g01","section":"summary","sectionIndex":3,"url":"../../images/courses/acls/c03_g01.webp","alt":"Waveform Capnography Patterns","caption":"Schematic diagram of five capnography waveforms: Normal, Hyperventilation, Hypoventilation, Esophageal Intubation (flat line), and ROSC (sudden spike)."}]},"c04":{"id":"c04","title":"Rhythm Recognition for ACLS","shortTitle":"Rhythm Recognition","estimatedStudyTime":40,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Identify ventricular fibrillation (VF) and pulseless ventricular tachycardia (pVT) on the cardiac monitor and understand their identical ACLS treatment pathway.","Differentiate organized ventricular tachycardia (VT) with a pulse from supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) with aberrant conduction.","Recognize asystole on the monitor and explain why the 2025 AHA Guidelines no longer distinguish between 'fine' and 'coarse' asystole.","Identify pulseless electrical activity (PEA) — organized electrical activity without a palpable pulse — and distinguish it from true asystole.","Recognize artifact-dropping-into-VF and understand the management approach.","Describe the role of 12-lead ECG acquisition during cardiac arrest for identifying reversible causes and guiding post-ROSC care.","Apply a systematic approach to rhythm identification during ACLS resuscitation."],"summary":[{"title":"The Two Shockable Rhythms: VF and Pulseless VT","content":"Ventricular fibrillation (VF) and pulseless ventricular tachycardia (pVT) are the two shockable cardiac arrest rhythms and share an identical ACLS treatment pathway: immediate defibrillation followed by high-quality CPR, epinephrine, and antiarrhythmics for refractory cases. VF appears as chaotic, disorganized electrical activity with no identifiable QRS complexes — the waveform varies in amplitude from coarse (>0.2 mV) to fine (<0.2 mV), but this distinction has no therapeutic significance. Pulseless VT is a rapid, regular, wide-complex tachycardia at a rate typically above 150/min with no palpable pulse. Both demand immediate synchronized identification and defibrillation. The key clinical point is that any wide-complex tachycardia without a pulse should be treated as pulseless VT and defibrillated — do not delay to differentiate further."},{"title":"Organized VT with a Pulse vs SVT with Aberrancy","content":"One of the most challenging rhythm discrimination tasks in ACLS is distinguishing monomorphic ventricular tachycardia (VT) with a pulse from supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) with aberrant conduction (e.g., bundle branch block). Both present as wide-complex tachycardias, but their treatments differ significantly. VT with a pulse is treated with synchronized cardioversion at 100J (monomorphic) or antiarrhythmic therapy, while SVT with aberrancy responds to vagal maneuvers and adenosine. Clinical features favoring VT include: history of structural heart disease or prior MI, hemodynamic instability, AV dissociation on ECG, fusion or capture beats, and concordant precordial QRS concordance. When in doubt in an ACLS setting, treat as VT — it is the safer assumption because adenosine is unlikely to harm a VT patient but cardioversion of SVT is also safe. The 2025 guidelines continue to emphasize that unstable wide-complex tachycardia of uncertain origin should be treated with immediate synchronized cardioversion."},{"title":"Asystole: No Fine or Coarse Distinction","content":"Asystole is the complete absence of ventricular electrical activity — the monitor shows a flat line or, occasionally, isolated atrial activity (P waves without QRS). The 2025 AHA Guidelines explicitly state that the terms 'fine asystole' and 'coarse asystole' are no longer used because the distinction has no proven prognostic or therapeutic significance. All asystole is treated identically: high-quality CPR, epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO every 3–5 minutes, identification and treatment of reversible causes, and consideration of transcutaneous pacing if a bradycardic escape rhythm is suspected. Before diagnosing asystole, confirm: (1) the monitor leads are properly connected, (2) the gain/sensitivity is adequate, (3) the rhythm is present in at least two leads, and (4) it is not fine VF being under-displayed. Asystole is a non-shockable rhythm — defibrillation is contraindicated."},{"title":"Pulseless Electrical Activity (PEA)","content":"Pulseless electrical activity (PEA) is defined as any organized electrical rhythm on the monitor in the absence of a palpable pulse. PEA encompasses a wide spectrum of ECG morphologies: normal sinus rhythm, sinus bradycardia, junctional rhythms, first-degree AV block, and even organized wide-complex rhythms — all with the critical distinction that no effective mechanical cardiac contraction is producing a pulse. The key management principle is that PEA requires immediate high-quality CPR and a systematic search for reversible causes (the H's and T's) rather than defibrillation. Common reversible causes of PEA include hypovolemia, tension pneumothorax, cardiac tamponade, massive pulmonary embolism, severe hypoxia, acidosis, and drug overdose. An organized rhythm without a pulse must never be confused with a perfusing rhythm — always check a pulse before concluding the patient has ROSC."},{"title":"Artifact-Dropping-Into-VF","content":"Artifact-dropping-into-VF occurs when motion artifact on the cardiac monitor mimics or appears to transition into ventricular fibrillation. This is a recognized pitfall during resuscitation because patient movement during compressions, transport, or shivering can generate electrical artifact that resembles VF on the ECG. The management approach is to: (1) briefly pause compressions (no more than 5–10 seconds) while observing the rhythm — true VF persists without compressions, while artifact disappears; (2) check for a pulse; (3) if uncertain and the patient is in arrest, err on the side of treating as VF and defibrillate. A key principle is to never delay life-saving intervention for prolonged rhythm analysis. The clinical context (is the patient known to be in arrest? is there an organized rhythm on the previous strip?) should guide the team's decision."},{"title":"12-Lead ECG During Cardiac Arrest","content":"While 12-lead ECG acquisition is not a priority during active cardiac arrest resuscitation (compressions and rhythm checks take precedence), it becomes important at two critical moments: (1) immediately after ROSC, when a 12-lead can identify ST-elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) and guide the decision for emergent cardiac catheterization, and (2) during prolonged resuscitation, when intermittent rhythm strips and a 12-lead can help identify reversible causes such as massive PE (S1Q3T3, right heart strain), hyperkalemia (peaked T waves, wide QRS), or acute coronary ischemia. During arrest, the team should obtain a rhythm strip at every rhythm check; a full 12-lead is best obtained promptly after ROSC or when the rhythm provides diagnostic information not available from the rhythm strip alone."}],"clinicalPearls":["Any organized rhythm without a palpable pulse is PEA — do not be fooled by an 'organized-looking' ECG; always check a pulse.","The 2025 guidelines no longer distinguish between 'fine' and 'coarse' asystole — the distinction has no therapeutic or prognostic significance.","When in doubt between VT with a pulse and SVT with aberrancy, treat as VT — synchronized cardioversion is the safer choice.","Artifact can mimic VF — briefly pause compressions to clarify the rhythm, but never delay defibrillation if the patient is in arrest.","Asystole is confirmed in at least two leads with correct monitor settings before being diagnosed — ensure leads are connected and gain is adequate.","Obtain a 12-lead ECG promptly after ROSC to identify STEMI or other acute coronary pathology requiring emergent intervention."],"redFlags":["Defibrillating asystole — it is a non-shockable rhythm and defibrillation is contraindicated.","Treating an organized rhythm as a perfusing rhythm without checking a pulse (missing PEA).","Delaying rhythm-specific therapy while attempting to differentiate VT from SVT with prolonged analysis.","Misdiagnosing artifact as VF and delivering unnecessary shocks.","Failing to obtain a post-ROSC 12-lead, missing STEMI or other reversible pathology."],"commonMistakes":["Assuming an organized rhythm on the monitor indicates ROSC without confirming a pulse.","Attempting to differentiate fine vs coarse asystole and altering treatment accordingly.","Prolonging rhythm analysis for more than 10 seconds during a pause, which reduces compression fraction.","Failing to check leads and gain settings before diagnosing asystole.","Confusing artifact from compressions or transport with a new shockable rhythm."],"memoryAids":["VF/pVT = shockable; asystole/PEA = non-shockable — two treatment tracks.","Organized rhythm without a pulse = PEA — always check the pulse, never trust the monitor alone.","2025 update: no fine vs coarse asystole — all asystole is asystole.","If in doubt between VT and SVT with aberrancy: treat as VT, cardiovert at 100J.","Artifact check: pause compressions for 5 seconds — if it's artifact, the rhythm clears."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"ACLS Rhythm Identification and Treatment Pathway","content":"Cardiac arrest — rhythm check\n  → Rhythm is chaotic, no organized complexes (VF)\n     → SHOCKABLE: Defibrillate (biphasic 120–200J), resume CPR immediately\n  → Rhythm is rapid, regular, wide-complex with no pulse (pulseless VT)\n     → SHOCKABLE: Defibrillate (biphasic 120–200J), resume CPR immediately\n  → Rhythm is absent — flat line (asystole)\n     → NON-SHOCKABLE: CPR + epinephrine q3–5 min + treat reversible causes; do NOT shock\n  → Organized rhythm present but no pulse (PEA)\n     → NON-SHOCKABLE: CPR + epinephrine q3–5 min + systematic search for H's & T's; do NOT shock\n  → Uncertain rhythm (artifact vs VF)\n     → Brief pause (<10 sec) to assess; if patient is in arrest, treat as VF and defibrillate"},{"title":"Wide-Complex Tachycardia Decision Approach","content":"Wide-complex tachycardia identified on monitor\n  → Is the patient pulseless?\n     → YES → Pulseless VT → Defibrillate (120–200J biphasic)\n     → NO → Patient has a pulse\n        → Is the patient hemodynamically unstable (hypotension, altered mentation, chest pain, acute heart failure)?\n           → YES → Immediate synchronized cardioversion (100J monomorphic VT)\n           → NO → Attempt vagal maneuvers and adenosine for possible SVT\n              → Responds → SVT with aberrancy confirmed\n              → Does not respond → Treat as VT: amiodarone or procainamide, or synchronized cardioversion"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 5: Adult BLS and CPR Quality","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Executive Summary: Tachycardia and Bradycardia Algorithms"],"graphics":[{"id":"c04_g01","section":"summary","sectionIndex":0,"url":"../../images/courses/acls/c04_g01.webp","alt":"Core ACLS ECG Rhythms","caption":"Panel of ECG strips showing VF, pulseless VT, Mobitz Type II AV Block, Complete Heart Block, SVT, and Torsades de Pointes."}]},"c05":{"id":"c05","title":"Defibrillation, Cardioversion & Pacing","shortTitle":"Defibrillation & Pacing","estimatedStudyTime":40,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Differentiate between biphasic and monophasic defibrillation waveforms and explain the energy selection for each.","State the recommended biphasic first-shock energy for adults in VF/pVT (120–200J; 200J if waveform unknown) and monophasic energy (360J).","Describe synchronized cardioversion energy recommendations by rhythm: atrial fibrillation/flutter ≥200J, narrow-regular SVT 100J, monomorphic VT with a pulse 100J.","Explain why polymorphic VT is treated with unsynchronized high-energy defibrillation rather than synchronized cardioversion.","Identify the indications, technique, and safety considerations for transcutaneous pacing.","Describe overdrive pacing as a technique for managing certain tachyarrhythmias.","Integrate electrical therapy decisions with the overall ACLS algorithm for cardiac arrest and tachyarrhythmia management."],"summary":[{"title":"Biphasic vs Monophasic Waveforms","content":"Modern defibrillators use biphasic waveforms, which deliver current in two phases — a positive phase followed by a negative phase — resulting in more effective defibrillation at lower energy levels than older monophasic waveforms. Biphasic defibrillators are the standard of care and are found in virtually all hospital and EMS settings. Monophasic defibrillators, which deliver current in a single direction, are now largely obsolete but may still be encountered in resource-limited settings. The key clinical difference is energy requirement: biphasic defibrillators achieve successful defibrillation at 120–200J, while monophasic defibrillators typically require 360J. For biphasic defibrillators, the manufacturer's recommended energy should be used for the first shock; if the waveform is unknown, 200J biphasic is recommended. All subsequent shocks should use the maximum available energy."},{"title":"Defibrillation Energy Selection for VF/pVT","content":"For adult VF or pulseless VT, the 2025 AHA Guidelines recommend: (1) Biphasic first shock: 120–200J (use the manufacturer's recommended waveform energy; if unknown, use 200J). (2) Monophasic first shock: 360J. (3) For subsequent biphasic shocks, use the maximum available energy. The rationale for the biphasic 120–200J range is that biphasic waveforms are effective at lower energies and the optimal energy varies by waveform morphology. If the specific biphasic waveform and its recommended energy are unknown, 200J is a safe default. After the first shock, deliver CPR for 2 minutes before the next rhythm check and shock. If VF/pVT persists after the first shock, the team should consider escalating energy or at minimum using the maximum available biphasic energy for subsequent shocks."},{"title":"Synchronized Cardioversion Energy by Rhythm","content":"Synchronized cardioversion delivers a timed electrical shock synchronized with the R wave of the QRS complex, avoiding the vulnerable repolarization period (T wave) to prevent induction of VF. The 2025 AHA Guidelines recommend the following initial energies for synchronized cardioversion: (1) Atrial fibrillation and atrial flutter: ≥200J biphasic (a shift from prior lower starting energies, reflecting evidence that higher initial energies achieve better first-shock success). (2) Narrow-regular supraventricular tachycardia (SVT): 100J biphasic — often effective on the first shock. (3) Monomorphic ventricular tachycardia with a pulse: 100J biphasic. If the first shock is unsuccessful, energy should be escalated. All synchronized cardioversion should be performed with the patient sedated and analgesed when clinically feasible. If synchronization cannot be reliably achieved (e.g., very rapid or irregular rhythm), synchronized cardioversion is contraindicated and unsynchronized defibrillation should be used instead."},{"title":"Polymorphic VT: Unsynchronized Defibrillation","content":"Polymorphic VT (a wide-complex tachycardia with varying QRS morphology, often associated with QT prolongation as in Torsades de Pointes) presents a unique management challenge. Because the QRS morphology is variable and irregular, the defibrillator cannot reliably synchronize to the R wave, making synchronized cardioversion both technically unreliable and potentially dangerous (an unsynchronized shock delivered during the T wave could induce VF). Therefore, polymorphic VT is treated with unsynchronized high-energy defibrillation — essentially the same as treating VF. If the patient has a pulse, the team should proceed with unsynchronized defibrillation at standard biphasic energy (120–200J) while preparing for potential resuscitation if the rhythm degenerates. Treatment of the underlying cause (e.g., correcting electrolyte abnormalities, discontinuing QT-prolonging drugs, overdrive pacing for Torsades) is essential."},{"title":"Transcutaneous Pacing","content":"Transcutaneous pacing (TCP) is a temporary, non-invasive method of electrical pacing delivered through external electrode pads placed on the chest and back. It is indicated for hemodynamically significant bradycardia that is unresponsive to atropine and as a bridge to permanent or transvenous pacing. The technique involves: (1) Place anterior and posterior pacing pads per manufacturer instructions. (2) Set the device to demand (pacer) mode. (3) Start at 80 mA (milliamps) and increase by 10 mA every 2–3 minutes until electrical capture is achieved (visible wide QRS complexes on the monitor following each pacer spike). (4) The maximum output for adults is 200 mA. (5) After electrical capture, confirm mechanical capture by checking for a pulse with each paced complex. (6) Provide sedation and analgesia for patient comfort, as TCP is painful. Important: electrical capture (visible on monitor) does not guarantee mechanical capture (effective cardiac output) — always verify a pulse. Indications include symptomatic bradycardia (heart block, sinus node dysfunction) refractory to atropine, as a bridge to transvenous pacing or permanent pacemaker placement, and as a temporizing measure during cardiac arrest due to severe bradycardia."},{"title":"Overdrive Pacing","content":"Overdrive pacing (also called anti-tachycardia pacing or ATP) involves pacing the heart at a rate faster than the tachycardia rate to terminate re-entrant tachyarrhythmias. The pacing rate is typically set 10–20% above the tachycardia rate, delivered in brief bursts. Overdrive pacing is primarily used for: (1) organized ventricular tachycardia (monomorphic VT) that is hemodynamically tolerated — it can terminate re-entrant circuits more gently than cardioversion. (2) Certain supraventricular tachycardias resistant to medications. (3) Torsades de Pointes (polymorphic VT associated with QT prolongation) — overdrive pacing at a faster rate (pacing at 90–110/min) suppresses the premature ventricular complexes that trigger Torsades and can be both acutely therapeutic and preventive. Overdrive pacing requires a functioning pacemaker (transcutaneous or transvenous) and continuous ECG monitoring. It is performed under controlled conditions, typically in a monitored setting, and is not a first-line therapy during unstable arrest."}],"clinicalPearls":["Biphasic first-shock energy for adults: 120–200J (use manufacturer's recommendation; if unknown, default to 200J).","Monophasic first-shock energy: 360J — this is encountered less frequently but remains important to know.","Polymorphic VT = treat like VF with unsynchronized defibrillation — do NOT attempt synchronized cardioversion.","Synchronized cardioversion for afib/aflutter: start at ≥200J biphasic — higher initial energies improve first-shock success.","For narrow-regular SVT cardioversion: start at 100J biphasic — often effective on the first shock.","Transcutaneous pacing: start at 80 mA, increase by 10 mA every 2–3 minutes, max 200 mA — always confirm mechanical capture with a pulse.","Electrical capture on monitor does not equal mechanical capture — always check for a pulse."],"redFlags":["Attempting synchronized cardioversion on polymorphic VT — the irregular rhythm prevents reliable synchronization and risks inducing VF.","Relying solely on electrical capture during transcutaneous pacing without confirming mechanical capture (pulse).","Using monophasic energy levels (360J) on a biphasic defibrillator without cause.","Starting transcutaneous pacing above 80 mA without first optimizing medical therapy (atropine).","Failing to sedate a conscious patient before synchronized cardioversion."],"commonMistakes":["Using 200J for the first biphasic shock of VF/pVT when the manufacturer specifies a different energy for that waveform — always check the device if possible.","Attempting synchronized cardioversion on a patient with polymorphic VT instead of unsynchronized defibrillation.","Stopping at electrical capture during TCP without verifying mechanical capture with a pulse.","Choosing synchronized cardioversion for asystole or PEA (these are non-shockable rhythms).","Forgetting to provide sedation/analgesia before elective cardioversion in a conscious patient."],"memoryAids":["Biphasic = 120–200J (if unknown → 200J); Monophasic = 360J.","Poly VT = unsynchronized = treat like VF.","Atrial fibrillation cardioversion = '200 and go' (≥200J biphasic first shock).","TCP: 'Start at 80, climb by 10, never exceed 200' — and always check the pulse.","Electrical capture is not mechanical capture — always palpate."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Electrical Therapy Decision in Cardiac Arrest (VF/pVT)","content":"Cardiac arrest — rhythm check reveals VF or pulseless VT\n  → Defibrillate:\n     → Biphasic defibrillator: 120–200J (manufacturer's recommendation; if unknown, 200J)\n     → Monophasic defibrillator: 360J\n  → Resume CPR immediately for 2 minutes after shock\n  → After 2 minutes: rhythm check\n     → VF/pVT persists → Shock again (use max biphasic energy or 360J monophasic)\n     → Give epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO (after the second shock)\n     → Consider amiodarone 300 mg IV first dose or lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg for refractory cases\n  → Rhythm changes to organized but no pulse (PEA) → Non-shockable pathway\n  → Rhythm changes to asystole → Non-shockable pathway\n  → ROSC confirmed → Post-arrest care"},{"title":"Transcutaneous Pacing Setup and Titration","content":"Hemodynamically significant bradycardia identified (HR <50, symptomatic)\n  → Atropine 1 mg IV — repeat q3–5 min, max 3 mg\n  → If atropine ineffective:\n     → Prepare transcutaneous pacing pads (anterior-posterior placement)\n     → Set device to demand (pacer) mode\n     → Start at 80 mA\n     → Increase by 10 mA every 2–3 minutes until electrical capture (wide QRS following each spike)\n     → If electrical capture achieved at ≤200 mA:\n        → Confirm mechanical capture: palpate pulse with each paced complex\n        → If pulse present: TCP effective — arrange transvenous pacing or permanent pacemaker\n        → If no pulse: electrical capture without mechanical capture — continue/resume CPR and escalate care\n     → If no electrical capture at 200 mA: TCP has failed — escalate to transvenous pacing or cardiology consultation\n  → Provide sedation/analgesia for conscious patients (TCP is painful)"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 5: Adult BLS and CPR Quality","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Executive Summary: Tachycardia and Bradycardia Algorithms"],"graphics":[{"id":"c05_g01","section":"summary","sectionIndex":2,"url":"../../images/courses/acls/c05_g01.webp","alt":"Defibrillation vs. Synchronized Cardioversion Pad Placement","caption":"Torso diagram demonstrating Anterolateral pad placement (defibrillation) vs. Anteroposterior placement (synchronized cardioversion)."},{"id":"c05_g02","section":"summary","sectionIndex":4,"url":"../../images/courses/acls/c05_g02.webp","alt":"Transcutaneous Pacing Capture","caption":"ECG strip showing pacer spikes followed by wide QRS complexes (electrical capture) compared to pacing without capture."}]},"c06":{"id":"c06","title":"Cardiac Arrest: VF / Pulseless VT","shortTitle":"VF / pVT Arrest","estimatedStudyTime":35,"difficulty":"Advanced","learningObjectives":["Describe the immediate management sequence for ventricular fibrillation (VF) and pulseless ventricular tachycardia (pVT).","State the correct epinephrine dose and timing pattern during VF/pVT arrest.","State the correct antiarrhythmic doses (amiodarone and lidocaine) for refractory VF/pVT.","Explain why chest compressions resume immediately after a shock without a pulse check.","Describe the 2-minute CPR cycle structure and when rhythm/pulse checks occur.","Differentiate first-shock energy strategy from the drug-timing pattern that follows.","Identify when a VF/pVT arrest should prompt consideration of refractory-arrest strategies."],"summary":[{"title":"Recognizing a Shockable Rhythm","content":"Ventricular fibrillation (VF) is chaotic, disorganized electrical activity with no coordinated contraction; pulseless ventricular tachycardia (pVT) is a rapid, wide-complex rhythm without a palpable pulse. Both are shockable rhythms — the single most important intervention is immediate defibrillation, because survival from a shockable rhythm declines with every minute defibrillation is delayed."},{"title":"The Shock-CPR Cycle","content":"Deliver one shock at the manufacturer-recommended (or escalating) biphasic energy, then resume chest compressions immediately without checking a pulse or rhythm. Continue high-quality CPR for about 2 minutes, then briefly pause to check the rhythm (and pulse only if an organized rhythm appears). If still VF/pVT, shock again and repeat the cycle. Minimizing the pre- and post-shock pause is as important as the shock itself."},{"title":"Epinephrine Timing","content":"Give epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO as soon as it is reasonably available, typically established after the second shock in a persistent VF/pVT arrest, then repeated every 3–5 minutes for the duration of the arrest. Epinephrine does not interrupt the shock-CPR cycle — it is pushed during ongoing compressions and followed by a saline flush."},{"title":"Antiarrhythmics for Refractory VF/pVT","content":"If VF/pVT persists after the initial shocks and epinephrine, give an antiarrhythmic: amiodarone 300 mg IV/IO as the first dose, followed by a second dose of 150 mg IV/IO if VF/pVT continues; or lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO as the first dose, followed by 0.5–0.75 mg/kg IV/IO for subsequent doses. Use one agent consistently rather than alternating between them within the same arrest."},{"title":"Maintaining CPR Quality Through the Cycle","content":"Throughout every shock-drug-CPR cycle, protect the fundamentals: rate 100–120/min, depth 2–2.4 in (5–6 cm), full recoil, chest compression fraction ≥60%, and a compressor switch about every 2 minutes (conveniently timed with the rhythm check). Waveform capnography, once an advanced airway is placed, helps monitor CPR quality and detect ROSC."},{"title":"When to Consider Refractory-Arrest Strategies","content":"If VF/pVT persists despite standard shocks, epinephrine, and an antiarrhythmic (roughly after 3 or more shocks), the arrest is considered refractory. At this point, teams may consider selective strategies such as vector-change or dual sequential defibrillation, or evaluate the patient for ECPR candidacy where systems support it — these are detailed in the Reversible Causes & Refractory Arrest chapter rather than repeated here."}],"clinicalPearls":["Shock, then hands back on the chest immediately — never pause for a pulse check right after a shock.","Epinephrine and antiarrhythmics are pushed during ongoing compressions, not during a special pause.","Use one antiarrhythmic consistently (amiodarone or lidocaine) rather than switching between them mid-arrest.","Every minute of delayed defibrillation in a shockable rhythm measurably lowers survival — prioritize the shock over everything else at the first rhythm check."],"redFlags":["Long pre-shock or post-shock pauses in compressions.","Withholding or delaying defibrillation to first obtain IV access or place an airway.","Alternating between amiodarone and lidocaine within the same arrest without reason."],"commonMistakes":["Checking a pulse immediately after every shock instead of resuming compressions.","Giving epinephrine and the antiarrhythmic at the same moment rather than sequencing them across cycles as the rhythm persists.","Losing track of the 2-minute cycle timing and checking rhythm too frequently, adding unnecessary pauses."],"memoryAids":["'Shock, then push' — no pulse check right after defibrillation.","Epi every 3–5 min; amiodarone 300 then 150; lidocaine 1–1.5 then 0.5–0.75.","Rhythm check ≈ compressor switch — piggyback the two so you don't add extra pauses."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"VF/pVT Arrest Cycle","content":"VF or pVT confirmed on the monitor\n  → Shock immediately (biphasic, manufacturer/escalating energy)\n  → Resume CPR immediately, no pulse check → 2 min cycle\n  → Rhythm check\n     → Still VF/pVT: shock again; give epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO (start ~after 2nd shock, then q3–5 min)\n     → Still VF/pVT after next cycle: shock again; give amiodarone 300 mg IV/IO OR lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO\n     → Still VF/pVT: shock again; second antiarrhythmic dose (amiodarone 150 mg or lidocaine 0.5–0.75 mg/kg); continue epinephrine q3–5 min\n     → Persistent VF/pVT after ≥3 shocks: consider refractory-arrest strategies (see Reversible Causes & Refractory Arrest chapter)\n     → Organized rhythm appears: check pulse → ROSC pathway or PEA/asystole pathway as appropriate"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support (VF/pVT management)"],"graphics":[{"id":"c06_g01","section":"summary","sectionIndex":1,"url":"../../images/courses/acls/c06_g01.webp","alt":"VF / Pulseless VT Resuscitation Flowchart","caption":"Resuscitation flowchart showing CPR, Shock, Epinephrine administration, and Antiarrhythmic administration (Amiodarone/Lidocaine) sequence."}]},"c07":{"id":"c07","title":"Cardiac Arrest: Asystole / PEA","shortTitle":"Asystole / PEA Arrest","estimatedStudyTime":35,"difficulty":"Advanced","learningObjectives":["Describe the immediate management sequence for asystole and pulseless electrical activity (PEA).","Explain why defibrillation is NOT indicated for asystole or PEA.","State the correct epinephrine dose, concentration, and timing for nonshockable rhythms.","List and explain the H's and T's as reversible causes of cardiac arrest.","Differentiate the PEA subtypes and explain how they may guide treatment.","Describe how early epinephrine timing (within 3–5 minutes) is prioritized for nonshockable rhythms.","Explain the role of waveform capnography in confirming true asystole and monitoring CPR quality.","Describe when mechanical CPR devices may be considered."],"summary":[{"title":"Defining Asystole and PEA","content":"Asystole is the complete absence of ventricular electrical activity — a flatline on the ECG with no pulse. Pulseless electrical activity (PEA) is any organized electrical rhythm (normal or abnormal) on the ECG that fails to generate a palpable pulse. Both are nonshockable rhythms — the cornerstone of management is high-quality CPR and early identification and treatment of reversible causes, rather than defibrillation."},{"title":"The Asystole/PEA Algorithm","content":"Upon identifying asystole or PEA, the team immediately begins high-quality chest compressions and ventilations. Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000 concentration) is given as soon as feasible, ideally within 3–5 minutes of arrest onset for nonshockable rhythms, and repeated every 3–5 minutes. After every 2 minutes of CPR, a brief rhythm check is performed. If the rhythm transitions to VF/pVT, the VF/pVT algorithm is followed. If asystole or PEA persists, continue CPR-epinephrine cycles while actively searching for and treating reversible causes."},{"title":"Epinephrine Timing in Nonshockable Rhythms","content":"The 2025 guidelines emphasize early epinephrine for nonshockable rhythms. Unlike VF/pVT where epinephrine is typically given after the second shock, in asystole/PEA epinephrine should be administered as soon as an IV/IO line is established — ideally within 3–5 minutes of arrest onset. Evidence suggests that earlier epinephrine in nonshockable rhythms is associated with improved survival, particularly in witnessed arrests with a likely reversible cause."},{"title":"The H's and T's: Identifying Reversible Causes","content":"A systematic search for reversible causes is essential in asystole/PEA because these rhythms typically result from an identifiable, treatable underlying condition. The H's: Hypovolemia, Hypoxia, Hydrogen ion (acidosis), Hypo-/Hyperkalemia, Hypothermia. The T's: Tension pneumothorax, Tamponade (cardiac), Toxins, Thrombosis (pulmonary), Thrombosis (coronary). Each cause requires a specific diagnostic and therapeutic approach, and early identification dramatically affects the chance of ROSC."},{"title":"Confirming True Asystole with Waveform Capnography","content":"True asystole should be confirmed on at least two leads. Waveform capnography is invaluable: if there is no cardiac output (asystole or fine VF), ETCO₂ will be very low or absent despite adequate ventilations. An ETCO₂ <10 mmHg during CPR in a patient on an advanced airway is consistent with asystole and low cardiac output. ETCO₂ may also help distinguish pseudo-asystole artifacts from true asystole."},{"title":"PEA Subtypes and Their Treatment Implications","content":"PEA encompasses a spectrum — from narrow-complex organized rhythms with relatively preserved rate (which may be closest to producing a pulse) to wide-complex agonal rhythms with very slow rates. Narrow-complex PEA may suggest hypovolemia, tension pneumothorax, or cardiac tamponade as etiologies and may respond more rapidly to treatment. Wide-complex or very slow PEA may indicate severe metabolic derangement or extensive myocardial ischemia. Regardless of subtype, the algorithm is the same: CPR, epinephrine, and treat H's & T's."},{"title":"Mechanical CPR Considerations","content":"Routine use of mechanical CPR devices is not recommended. However, mechanical CPR (piston or load-distributing band devices) may be considered in specific circumstances where high-quality manual compressions are impractical or unsafe to sustain — such as prolonged transport, limited personnel, during ECPR cannulation, or in the catheterization lab. Performance of mechanical devices is comparable between piston and load-distributing band types."}],"clinicalPearls":["Asystole and PEA are nonshockable — do NOT defibrillate. Focus on CPR quality and identifying reversible causes.","Give epinephrine early for nonshockable rhythms — ideally within 3–5 minutes — do not delay to establish large-bore IV access when IO is available.","Always search for the 'why' — asystole/PEA is a symptom of an underlying cause, not a final diagnosis.","Use at least two ECG leads to confirm true asystole before removing pads; waveform capnography helps confirm absent cardiac output."],"redFlags":["Defibrillating asystole or PEA — this wastes time and harms the patient.","Failing to systematically search for and treat reversible causes (H's & T's).","Delayed epinephrine administration while establishing peripheral IV access — use IO if IV is not quickly available."],"commonMistakes":["Misidentifying fine VF as asystole — always check two leads and use capnography to confirm.","Failing to search for reversible causes while repeatedly giving epinephrine — drug alone without cause-directed therapy has limited benefit.","Assuming a very slow, wide-complex PEA rhythm is asystole and stopping resuscitation prematurely."],"memoryAids":["'No shock, just compressions and epi' — asystole/PEA is NOT a shockable rhythm.","H's and T's mnemonic: Hypo/Hyper (volume, O₂, K⁺, pH, temp) and the 4 T's (pneumothorax, tamponade, toxins, thrombosis).","Epi early for nonshockable — within 3–5 minutes — don't wait."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Asystole / PEA Arrest Algorithm","content":"Asystole or PEA identified on the monitor (confirm on at least 2 leads)\n  → Start high-quality CPR immediately (compressions + ventilations)\n  → Establish IV/IO access\n  → Give epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000) as soon as feasible, ideally within 3–5 minutes\n  → Continue CPR 2 min, then rhythm check\n     → Still asystole/PEA: resume CPR, repeat epinephrine q3–5 min, search for H's & T's\n     → Organized rhythm appears: check pulse\n        → Pulse present: ROSC pathway\n        → No pulse: continue as PEA\n     → VF/pVT develops: switch to VF/pVT algorithm (shock)\n  → Consider and treat reversible causes concurrently throughout:\n     H's: Hypovolemia, Hypoxia, Hydrogen ion, Hypo-/Hyperkalemia, Hypothermia\n     T's: Tension pneumothorax, Tamponade, Toxins, Thrombosis (pulmonary), Thrombosis (coronary)\n  → Consider waveform capnography to confirm asystole and monitor CPR quality"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support (Asystole/PEA management)","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Epinephrine timing in nonshockable rhythms"],"graphics":[{"id":"c07_g01","section":"summary","sectionIndex":1,"url":"../../images/courses/acls/c07_g01.webp","alt":"Asystole / PEA Resuscitation Flowchart","caption":"Resuscitation flowchart showing CPR, immediate Epinephrine, and search for H's and T's."}]},"c08":{"id":"c08","title":"Pharmacology of Cardiac Arrest","shortTitle":"Cardiac Arrest Pharmacology","estimatedStudyTime":35,"difficulty":"Advanced","learningObjectives":["State the dose, concentration, route, and timing of epinephrine during cardiac arrest.","Explain the mechanism of action and clinical indications for amiodarone and lidocaine in VF/pVT.","Describe when sodium bicarbonate is indicated during cardiac arrest and when it is not.","State the dose and indication for magnesium sulfate in cardiac arrest.","Explain why vasopressin is no longer preferred over epinephrine in cardiac arrest.","Describe the role of adenosine and explain why it is not used in pulseless arrest.","Compare IV vs IO access during cardiac arrest, including timing considerations.","Describe the correct saline flush protocol after drug administration during CPR."],"summary":[{"title":"Epinephrine: The Primary Vasopressor","content":"Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000 concentration, 0.1 mg/mL) is the primary vasopressor in all cardiac arrest rhythms. It is given every 3–5 minutes. For nonshockable rhythms (asystole/PEA), epinephrine should be given as soon as feasible — ideally within 3–5 minutes of arrest onset. For shockable rhythms (VF/pVT), it is typically administered after the second shock. Epinephrine's alpha-adrenergic vasoconstriction increases aortic diastolic pressure, improving coronary perfusion pressure during CPR. Its beta-adrenergic effects are less beneficial during arrest and may increase myocardial oxygen demand."},{"title":"Amiodarone: Antiarrhythmic for VF/pVT","content":"Amiodarone is the preferred antiarrhythmic for refractory VF/pVT. The first dose is 300 mg IV/IO as a rapid bolus, followed by a second dose of 150 mg IV/IO if VF/pVT persists. Amiodarone has combined Class I (sodium channel blockade), Class III (potassium channel blockade/prolonged repolarization), and Class IV (calcium channel blockade) antiarrhythmic properties. It stabilizes the myocardial membrane and suppresses ventricular arrhythmias. Side effects include hypotension (associated with the solvent polysorbate 80; standard amiodarone must be diluted in 5% dextrose in water [D5W], not normal saline, as it precipitates in saline) and bradycardia."},{"title":"Lidocaine: Alternative Antiarrhythmic","content":"Lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO is an alternative to amiodarone for refractory VF/pVT. The second dose is 0.5–0.75 mg/kg IV/IO. Lidocaine is a Class Ib antiarrhythmic that blocks fast sodium channels, shortening the action potential duration in ventricular tissue. It is preferred when amiodarone is unavailable or in the setting of cardiac arrest clearly due to acute ischemia/MI. Use one agent consistently rather than alternating between amiodarone and lidocaine within the same arrest."},{"title":"Sodium Bicarbonate: Specific Indications Only","content":"Sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO₃) 1 mEq/kg IV is NOT a routine cardiac arrest drug. It is indicated only for specific conditions: known or suspected hyperkalemia with cardiac arrest, tricyclic antidepressant overdose, and known bicarbonate-responsive acidosis. Routine use during cardiac arrest is not recommended because it can cause hypernatremia, hyperosmolality, and a paradoxical intracellular acidosis. It should be considered only after other interventions are underway, not as a first-line arrest drug."},{"title":"Magnesium Sulfate: Torsades de Pointes","content":"Magnesium sulfate 1–2 g IV over 5–20 minutes is indicated specifically for torsades de pointes (polymorphic VT with prolonged QT) and for suspected hypomagnesemia contributing to arrhythmias. It is NOT indicated for ordinary VF or pulseless VT. In torsades, magnesium stabilizes the cardiac membrane and suppresses the early afterdepolarizations that trigger the arrhythmia. For pulseless torsades, it may be given as a bolus; for torsades with a pulse, it is given as an infusion."},{"title":"Vasopressin: A Largely Replaced Agent","content":"Vasopressin (20 IU IV/IO) was previously used as an alternative or adjunct to epinephrine in cardiac arrest. The 2025 guidelines confirm that epinephrine alone is preferred — vasopressin offers no demonstrated survival advantage over epinephrine for most cardiac arrests. In selected in-hospital arrests, low-dose vasopressin with epinephrine and methylprednisolone followed by post-ROSC hydrocortisone may be considered (Class 2b), but this is not routine and not used for OHCA in this course."},{"title":"Adenosine: Not for Pulseless Arrest","content":"Adenosine is aAV nodal-blocking agent used for regular, narrow-complex supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) with a pulse. It is absolutely NOT indicated in pulseless arrest (asystole, PEA, VF, or pVT). Adenosine has an extremely short half-life (6 seconds) and requires rapid IV push followed by saline flush to reach the heart. It has no role in the cardiac arrest pharmacology toolkit."},{"title":"IV vs IO Access and Drug Delivery","content":"IV access is preferred first-line during cardiac arrest. IO access is reasonable when IV access cannot be obtained quickly — drugs delivered via IO reach the central circulation with comparable speed and bioavailability to IV access. All cardiac arrest drugs can be given by either route. After each drug bolus, a 10–20 mL normal saline flush should be administered, followed by IV/IO fluid push to ensure the drug reaches the central circulation. Position the extremity if using a peripheral IV to enhance venous return."}],"clinicalPearls":["Epinephrine 1:10,000 (NOT 1:1,000) — the wrong concentration can cause severe harm; always verify.","Amiodarone must be diluted in 5% dextrose in water (D5W) for infusions; standard amiodarone is incompatible with normal saline and will precipitate.","Sodium bicarbonate is not a routine arrest drug — reserve it for hyperkalemia, TCA overdose, and documented bicarbonate-responsive acidosis.","Adenosine has zero role in pulseless arrest — it is only for SVT with a pulse.","All arrest drugs can be given IV or IO; IO is faster to establish and has equivalent drug bioavailability."],"redFlags":["Using epinephrine 1:1,000 instead of 1:10,000 — this is a 10-fold overdose.","Diluting standard amiodarone in normal saline instead of dextrose (D5W) — normal saline causes drug precipitation.","Administering sodium bicarbonate as a routine arrest drug without specific indications.","Attempting adenosine in a pulseless rhythm — this is ineffective and wastes time."],"commonMistakes":["Giving epinephrine as a continuous infusion instead of intermittent 1 mg boluses every 3–5 minutes.","Alternating between amiodarone and lidocaine within the same arrest rather than using one consistently.","Forgetting the saline flush after drug administration — the drug may remain in peripheral veins without reaching the heart.","Using vasopressin as a first-line agent instead of epinephrine — epinephrine alone is preferred."],"memoryAids":["Epi 1 mg every 3–5 min — always 1:10,000.","Amiodarone: 300 first, 150 second. Lidocaine: 1–1.5 first, 0.5–0.75 second.","Bicarb is not routine — think Hyperkalemia, TCA, Acidosis.","Adenosine = pulse only, never arrest.","After every drug: flush, flush, flush."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Cardiac Arrest Drug Selection by Rhythm","content":"Cardiac arrest confirmed\n  → Is the rhythm shockable (VF/pVT)?\n     YES:\n       → Defibrillate immediately\n       → After 2nd shock: Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO q3–5 min\n       → If VF/pVT persists: Amiodarone 300 mg IV/IO first, then 150 mg\n         OR Lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO first, then 0.5–0.75 mg/kg\n     NO (Asystole/PEA):\n       → CPR + Ventilations\n       → Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO as soon as feasible (within 3–5 min), then q3–5 min\n       → Search for H's & T's\n       → Specific drugs for specific causes:\n          • Hyperkalemia → Calcium, insulin/glucose, NaHCO₃\n          • TCA OD → NaHCO₃ 1 mEq/kg IV\n          • Torsades → Magnesium 1–2 g IV\n  → Adenosine is NEVER used in any pulseless rhythm."}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support (Pharmacology)","AHA 2025 Drug Dosing Reference for ACLS"],"graphics":[{"id":"c08_g01","section":"summary","sectionIndex":7,"url":"../../images/courses/acls/c08_g01.webp","alt":"Intraosseous (IO) Access Sites","caption":"Anatomical diagram showing the primary insertion sites for adult IO access: proximal humerus and proximal tibia."}]},"c09":{"id":"c09","title":"Reversible Causes: H's & T's and Refractory Arrest","shortTitle":"H's & T's / Refractory Arrest","estimatedStudyTime":35,"difficulty":"Advanced","learningObjectives":["List and recall the H's and T's mnemonic of reversible cardiac arrest causes.","For each H and T, identify the key diagnostic test or bedside finding that confirms it.","Describe the initial management of each reversible cause once identified.","Define refractory VF/pVT and explain when it applies during a resuscitation.","Outline the sequential pharmacologic and electrical strategies for refractory VF/pVT, including antiarrhythmic stacking and dual sequential external defibrillation (DSED).","State the AHA recommendation class for DSED and vector-change defibrillation.","Explain the role of inhaled vasodilators in refractory VF/pVT and the evidence basis.","Describe CPR quality reassessment steps during refractory arrest."],"summary":[{"title":"The H's and T's: A Systematic Approach to Reversible Arrest","content":"Every cardiac arrest has a cause. The H's and T's mnemonic provides a systematic checklist that ensures potentially reversible etiologies are not overlooked during the chaos of resuscitation. The H's are: Hypovolemia, Hypoxia, Hydrogen ion (acidosis), Hypo-/Hyperkalemia, and Hypothermia. The T's are: Tension pneumothorax, Tamponade (cardiac), Toxins, Thrombosis (pulmonary), and Thrombosis (coronary). The team should begin considering these causes from the moment of arrest, not only after repeated failed interventions."},{"title":"The H's — Detailed Breakdown","content":"Hypovolemia: Recognized by clinical history (hemorrhage, dehydration) and bedside ultrasound (flat IVC); treated with volume resuscitation and blood products. Hypoxia: Common and correctable — ensure adequate oxygenation and ventilation once an advanced airway is in place. Hydrogen ion (acidosis): Severe metabolic acidosis from prolonged arrest impairs drug effectiveness and myocardial contractivity; treat with ventilation and address the underlying cause rather than empiric bicarbonate. Hypo-/Hyperkalemia: Hyperkalemia is the more immediately dangerous and common arrest electrolyte — look for peaked T waves, widened QRS; treat with calcium chloride, sodium bicarbonate, insulin/glucose, and albuterol. Hypothermia: In cold-exposure arrests, active rewarming is critical; do not declare futility until core temperature is at least 32°C."},{"title":"The T's — Detailed Breakdown","content":"Tension pneumothorax: Suspect when there are absent breath sounds, tracheal deviation, or jugular venous distention during arrest; decompress immediately with a large-bore needle in the second intercostal space, midclavicular line, followed by chest tube. Cardiac tamponade: Suspect with muffled heart sounds, JVD, and PEA arrest; treat with emergent pericardiocentesis or thoracotomy. Toxins: Consider drug overdose (tricyclics, beta-blockers, calcium-channel blockers, digoxin, local anesthetics); treat with specific antidotes when available (e.g., digoxin immune Fab, intralipid for local anesthetic toxicity). Pulmonary embolism: Massive PE causing arrest — consider systemic thrombolysis or surgical/catheter-based embolectomy. Coronary thrombosis: Acute MI causing VF — early defibrillation and coronary reperfusion (PCI) are essential."},{"title":"Refractory VF/pVT — Definition and Approach","content":"Refractory VF/pVT is defined as ventricular fibrillation or pulseless ventricular tachycardia that persists despite three or more consecutive defibrillation attempts with standard biphasic energies (typically 200 J). Once VF is refractory, the provider should systematically escalate through antiarrhythmic drugs (amiodarone or lidocaine), consider vector-change defibrillation, evaluate for DSED (Class 2b, LOE B-R), and reassess CPR quality, compressibility, and underlying causes before each subsequent shock."},{"title":"Antiarrhythmic Therapy for Refractory VF/pVT","content":"After the third shock, give amiodarone 300 mg IV/IO as a bolus for the first dose (may repeat once at 150 mg). Lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO is an acceptable alternative, especially if amiodarone is unavailable. Some systems use antiarrhythmic stacking — administering both amiodarone and lidocaine sequentially when VF is truly refractory — though this is an advanced, protocol-dependent strategy. Magnesium sulfate 1–2 g IV is considered specifically for polymorphic VT (torsades de pointes)."},{"title":"Dual Sequential External Defibrillation (DSED) and Vector-Change Defibrillation","content":"For truly refractory VF/pVT (≥3 shocks), two strategies may be considered: dual sequential external defibrillation (DSED), where two defibrillators deliver asynchronous shocks in rapid succession with pads placed in different positions, and vector-change defibrillation, where pad placement is altered to change the current path through the myocardium. Both are AHA Class 2b (LOE B-R) — meaning they may be considered but are not established as routine first-line therapy. Neither should delay standard high-quality CPR and timely epinephrine."},{"title":"Inhaled Vasodilators and Emerging Therapies","content":"Inhaled nitric oxide and other inhaled vasodilators are being investigated for refractory VF/pVT. The theoretical mechanism involves improving myocardial perfusion and reducing afterload during ongoing CPR. While promising in early studies, these remain investigational and are not yet established as standard therapy in the 2025 AHA Guidelines."},{"title":"CPR Quality Reassessment During Refractory Arrest","content":"Before each rhythm check and shock in refractory arrest, the team must reassess CPR quality: compression rate (100–120/min), depth (at least 2 inches / 5 cm, no more than 2.4 inches / 6 cm), full chest recoil, minimizing interruptions, and adequate ventilation (1 breath every 6 seconds with an advanced airway). Check ETCO₂ — a sudden drop may indicate deterioration in compression quality or a new reversible cause. Rotate compressors every 2 minutes. Verify pad position, contact, and impedance. Consider and treat the H's and T's with each cycle."}],"clinicalPearls":["The H's and T's are not a post-arrest checklist — begin evaluating reversible causes from the moment of arrest.","Hyperkalemia is the most common electrolyte cause of cardiac arrest; check potassium early and treat aggressively with calcium, bicarbonate, and insulin/glucose.","DSED and vector-change defibrillation are Class 2b options — they may be considered but should not replace or delay standard defibrillation, epinephrine, and antiarrhythmic drugs.","ETCO₂ trending during CPR is the best noninvasive monitor of CPR quality — a sudden drop means compressions have degraded or a new reversible cause has appeared.","Do not declare futility in hypothermic arrest until core temperature is at least 32°C, as hypothermic patients may have neurologically intact survival after prolonged resuscitation."],"redFlags":["Failing to consider and treat reversible causes (H's & T's) during ongoing arrest resuscitation.","Not escalating to antiarrhythmic drugs after the third defibrillation attempt for VF/pVT.","Neglecting CPR quality during the focus on advanced interventions in refractory arrest.","Declaring futility prematurely in hypothermic cardiac arrest before rewarming.","Using DSED or vector-change defibrillation as a substitute for rather than an adjunct to standard ACLS interventions."],"commonMistakes":["Not checking ETCO₂ or failing to trend it during ongoing CPR.","Repeating defibrillation at the same energy and pad position without considering vector change or DSED after ≥3 failed shocks.","Forgetting to seek and treat the underlying cause (e.g., tension pneumothorax, tamponade, PE) when VF is refractory to electrical therapy.","Administering amiodarone too slowly during cardiac arrest — the bolus should be given rapidly during ongoing compressions.","Withholding thrombolysis in suspected massive PE arrest when catheter-based therapy is not immediately available."],"memoryAids":["H's & T's: 'Hypo-Hypo-Hypo-Hypo-Hyper, Tox-Tamponade-PE-Tension-Things-coronary' — 5 H's and 5 T's.","Refractory VF = 3 shocks failed → think drugs, vector change, DSED, and always re-check the cause.","ETCO₂ is your CPR quality dashboard — if it drops, check the compressions first.","Calcium, Bicarb, Insulin/Glucose — the 'CBI-G' triad for hyperkalemic arrest."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Refractory VF/pVT Management Escalation","content":"VF/pVT identified → Defibrillate (biphasic 200 J)\n  → Resume CPR immediately for 2 minutes\n  → Rhythm check: still VF/pVT?\n     → Shock again (200 J biphasic)\n     → Resume CPR; give epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO\n     → Rhythm check: still VF/pVT after 3rd shock?\n        → REFRACTORY VF/pVT\n        → Give amiodarone 300 mg IV/IO bolus (or lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg)\n        → Consider vector-change defibrillation or DSED (Class 2b)\n        → REASSESS: CPR quality, ETCO₂, compressor rotation, pad position\n        → REASSESS: H's & T's — tension pneumo? tamponade? toxins? PE? hypoxia?\n        → Repeat shock (200 J) with antiarrhythmic on board\n        → Continue cycling: 2 min CPR → rhythm check → shock → reassess\n        → If still refractory: consider magnesium (polymorphic VT), additional antiarrhythmic stacking, ECPR if available"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support (Refractory VF/pVT, Reversible Causes)","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Executive Summary (DSED, vector-change defibrillation)","AHA 2025 Focused Update on DSED and Antiarrhythmic Therapy for Refractory VF/pVT"],"graphics":[{"id":"c09_g01","section":"summary","sectionIndex":0,"url":"../../images/courses/acls/c09_g01.webp","alt":"Reversible Causes: The H's & T's","caption":"Infographic displaying the 5 H's (Hypovolemia, Hypoxia, Hydrogen ion, Hypo-/Hyperkalemia, Hypothermia) and 5 T's (Tension pneumothorax, Tamponade, Toxins, Thrombosis pulmonary, Thrombosis coronary)."}]},"c10":{"id":"c10","title":"Bradycardia With a Pulse","shortTitle":"Bradycardia","estimatedStudyTime":30,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Define symptomatic bradycardia and list the signs of cardiopulmonary compromise that make it unstable.","State the correct dose, route, and repeat interval for atropine in symptomatic bradycardia.","Identify situations where atropine is unlikely to work and the next-line therapies to use instead.","Describe how to set up and operate transcutaneous pacing.","Compare dopamine and epinephrine infusions as second-line options for refractory symptomatic bradycardia.","Explain why asymptomatic bradycardia is observed rather than treated.","Identify reversible causes of bradycardia that should be sought and treated in parallel with drug/pacing therapy."],"summary":[{"title":"Recognizing Symptomatic Bradycardia","content":"Bradycardia is a heart rate typically under 50/min, but the rate alone does not define the emergency — the presence of symptoms does. Symptomatic (unstable) bradycardia shows signs of poor perfusion or cardiopulmonary compromise: hypotension, acutely altered mental status, signs of shock, ongoing ischemic chest discomfort, or acute heart failure. If the patient is bradycardic but has none of these findings, the priority is to monitor and observe while investigating the cause, not to treat the number."},{"title":"First-Line Drug Therapy: Atropine","content":"For symptomatic bradycardia, give atropine 1 mg IV or IO, and repeat every 3–5 minutes to a maximum total dose of 3 mg. Atropine works by blocking vagal tone at the sinoatrial and atrioventricular nodes, so it is most effective for sinus node dysfunction and low-grade AV block. It is unlikely to be effective for infranodal block (Mobitz type II or third-degree block with a wide QRS), where escalation to pacing or infusions should not be delayed while repeating ineffective atropine doses."},{"title":"When Atropine Fails or Is Unlikely to Work","content":"If atropine is ineffective, if the maximum dose has been reached, or if the block pattern predicts atropine will not help (e.g., Mobitz type II, high-grade or third-degree AV block, especially with a wide QRS), move promptly to transcutaneous pacing and/or a dopamine or epinephrine infusion. These options can be used while pacing pads are applied or while awaiting expert consultation or transvenous pacing."},{"title":"Transcutaneous Pacing","content":"Apply pacing pads in the standard anterior-posterior or anterolateral position, set the rate (commonly 60–80/min as a starting target), and increase the output (milliamps) until electrical capture is confirmed — a paced spike immediately followed by a wide QRS and a T wave, matched with a palpable pulse at the paced rate. Because it is uncomfortable, give analgesia/sedation if the patient is conscious and hemodynamically able to tolerate it."},{"title":"Infusions: Dopamine and Epinephrine","content":"Dopamine and epinephrine infusions are alternative (not necessarily sequential) second-line options when atropine is ineffective — they may be started instead of, or while awaiting, pacing, particularly if pacing is not immediately available or tolerated. Both are titrated to the patient's heart rate and blood pressure response; the exact starting and titration ranges should follow local protocol/pharmacy references, and the underlying cause should be sought in parallel."},{"title":"Treat the Underlying Cause in Parallel","content":"Bradycardia is often a symptom, not a primary disease: consider hypoxia, medication or toxin effect (beta-blocker, calcium-channel blocker, digoxin), electrolyte disturbance (hyperkalemia), hypothyroidism, inferior myocardial infarction, and increased intracranial pressure. Treating the reversible cause may resolve the bradycardia without needing to escalate to pacing."}],"clinicalPearls":["Treat the patient, not the monitor — a bradycardic rate with no instability is observed, not medicated.","Atropine's ceiling is 3 mg total; don't keep dosing past it while a patient with a wide-complex block deteriorates — move to pacing/infusion.","Confirm mechanical capture (a palpable pulse at the paced rate), not just electrical capture, before trusting the pacer.","Always screen for a reversible drug/toxin or metabolic cause — treating it may be more effective than escalating pacing."],"redFlags":["Repeating atropine past 3 mg total instead of escalating therapy.","Relying on electrical capture (pacing spikes) alone without confirming a pulse.","Missing beta-blocker, calcium-channel blocker, digoxin, or hyperkalemia as a treatable cause.","Delaying pacing/infusion in a clearly unstable patient with a high-grade block while atropine is tried repeatedly."],"commonMistakes":["Treating an asymptomatic bradycardic rate purely because it looks alarming on the monitor.","Giving atropine for a rhythm unlikely to respond (Mobitz II / third-degree block with wide QRS) and delaying pacing.","Forgetting analgesia/sedation for a conscious patient undergoing transcutaneous pacing.","Not seeking reversible causes (drugs, electrolytes, hypoxia) while escalating pacing/infusions."],"memoryAids":["'1 and done, up to 3' — atropine 1 mg, repeat q3–5 min, max 3 mg total.","No symptoms, no treatment — observe and investigate the cause.","Atropine fails → PACE or infuse (pacing / dopamine / epinephrine) — don't stall.","Capture on the monitor isn't capture in the patient — check the pulse."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Symptomatic Bradycardia Treatment Sequence","content":"Bradycardia identified (rate typically <50/min)\n  → Assess for signs of instability: hypotension, altered mental status, shock, ischemic chest pain, acute heart failure\n     → No instability: monitor, observe, investigate cause\n     → Instability present: SYMPTOMATIC BRADYCARDIA\n        → Give atropine 1 mg IV/IO; repeat q3–5 min to max 3 mg\n        → Atropine ineffective or unlikely to work (e.g., Mobitz II / 3rd-degree block, wide QRS)\n           → Start transcutaneous pacing (confirm mechanical capture) and/or dopamine or epinephrine infusion\n           → Consider expert consultation and transvenous pacing\n        → In parallel: identify and treat the underlying/reversible cause"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support (Bradycardia)"]},"c11":{"id":"c11","title":"Tachycardia With a Pulse","shortTitle":"Tachycardia","estimatedStudyTime":35,"difficulty":"Advanced","learningObjectives":["Differentiate stable from unstable tachycardia using clinical signs of hemodynamic compromise.","State when immediate synchronized cardioversion is indicated for unstable tachycardia.","Outline the management pathway for stable regular narrow-complex tachycardia (SVT).","Describe the adenosine dosing protocol (6 mg, then 12 mg) including administration technique.","Distinguish between stable and unstable wide-complex tachycardia and the rationale for assuming VT when uncertain.","State the dose and administration of amiodarone for stable wide-complex tachycardia.","Describe the management of irregular narrow-complex tachycardia (atrial fibrillation/flutter) for rate control.","Explain why polymorphic VT is treated with unsynchronized defibrillation rather than synchronized cardioversion.","Identify procainamide as an alternative to amiodarone for stable wide-complex tachycardia."],"summary":[{"title":"Stable vs Unstable Tachycardia — The First Decision","content":"The ACLS approach to tachycardia with a pulse begins with a single critical assessment: is the patient stable or unstable? Unstable tachycardia shows signs of hemodynamic compromise — hypotension (SBP <90 mmHg), acutely altered mental status, chest pain, acute heart failure, or signs of shock. An unstable patient with tachycardia requires immediate synchronized cardioversion regardless of the rhythm type. A stable patient allows time for diagnosis and pharmacologic or vagal therapy."},{"title":"Immediate Synchronized Cardioversion — When and How","content":"Unstable tachycardia = immediate synchronized cardioversion. Energy levels: regular narrow-complex SVT starts at 100 J biphasic; atrial fibrillation and atrial flutter start at ≥200 J biphasic; regular monomorphic VT starts at 100 J biphasic. Sedate if the patient is conscious and time permits. Polymorphic VT, however, is treated with UNSYNCHRONIZED defibrillation (not synchronized cardioversion), because the irregular waveform makes reliable R-wave synchronization impossible and delays are dangerous."},{"title":"Stable Narrow-Complex Regular Tachycardia — SVT","content":"Most regular narrow-complex tachycardias are supraventricular in origin (AV nodal reentrant tachycardia, AV reentrant tachycardia). For stable patients, start with vagal maneuvers (Valsalva, carotid sinus massage). If ineffective, give adenosine 6 mg rapid IV push via a proximal (near-the-heart) IV port followed by a rapid 20 mL saline flush; if no response, give 12 mg and may repeat once. Adenosine works by transiently blocking AV nodal conduction, terminating reentrant circuits that depend on the AV node."},{"title":"Stable Narrow-Complex Irregular Tachycardia","content":"Irregular narrow-complex tachycardia is most commonly atrial fibrillation or atrial flutter with variable block. For stable patients, rate control is the priority: beta-blockers (metoprolol), calcium-channel blockers (diltiazem), or amiodarone if both rate control and rhythm control are considered. Target a resting heart rate <110/min (lenient) or <80/min (strict) per clinical context. Adenosine is not effective for AF/AFlutter rate control but can be diagnostic to unmask flutter waves."},{"title":"Stable Wide-Complex Regular Tachycardia — VT vs SVT with Aberrancy","content":"A regular wide-complex tachycardia should be assumed to be ventricular tachycardia (VT) until proven otherwise — this is the safest assumption, as treating SVT as VT is less harmful than treating VT as SVT. Amiodarone 150 mg IV over 10 minutes is first-line for stable wide-complex tachycardia, and may be repeated once. Procainamide 20–50 mg/min IV is a reasonable alternative. If the patient becomes unstable at any point, switch to synchronized cardioversion starting at 100 J."},{"title":"Polymorphic VT — A Special Case","content":"Polymorphic VT (including torsades de pointes) is a wide-complex tachycardia with a continuously varying QRS axis and morphology. Unlike monomorphic VT, polymorphic VT is treated with UNSYNCHRONIZED defibrillation — synchronization is unreliable on an irregular waveform and delays defibrillation. Magnesium sulfate 1–2 g IV is given specifically for torsades de pointes. Correct underlying electrolyte abnormalities (hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia) promptly."},{"title":"Procainamide as an Alternative Antiarrhythmic","content":"Procainamide 20–50 mg/min IV (maximum cumulative dose 17 mg/kg) is an alternative to amiodarone for stable wide-complex tachycardia. It is effective for both regular and irregular wide-complex tachycardias. Monitor for hypotension (a common side effect) and QT prolongation. Procainamide is not recommended in patients with structural heart disease or significant heart failure, where amiodarone is preferred."}],"clinicalPearls":["Unstable tachycardia = immediate synchronized cardioversion — do not waste time on drug therapy.","When in doubt, assume VT — treating SVT as VT is safer than the reverse.","Adenosine must be given as a rapid IV push through a proximal (near-the-heart) IV port, followed by a rapid saline flush, to reach the heart before it is metabolized.","Polymorphic VT = UNSYNCHRONIZED defibrillation — synchronization is contraindicated on an irregular waveform.","Procainamide causes hypotension — give slowly and monitor blood pressure; it is a poor choice in cardiogenic shock."],"redFlags":["Attempting synchronized cardioversion on polymorphic VT (synchronization is contraindicated).","Giving adenosine through a distal IV port (too slow — drug is metabolized before reaching the heart).","Assuming a wide-complex tachycardia is SVT with aberrancy and giving verapamil (may cause hemodynamic collapse if it is VT).","Delayed cardioversion in an unstable tachycardic patient while attempting drug therapy.","Not recognizing atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response as the cause of hemodynamic instability."],"commonMistakes":["Hesitating to cardiovert an unstable patient because 'we should try drugs first.'","Using adenosine for rate control in atrial fibrillation — adenosine terminates AV-nodal-dependent reentrant tachycardias, not fibrillation.","Forgetting to set the defib to SYNCHRONIZED mode for cardioversion (risk of R-on-T precipitation of VF).","Giving procainamide too rapidly, causing hypotension in an already unstable patient.","Not confirming a regular vs irregular rhythm before choosing adenosine over rate-control agents."],"memoryAids":["Unstable = shock (cardiovert), stable = treat (drugs/vagal).","Wide-complex tachycardia = VT until proven otherwise.","Adenosine 6, then 12 — rapid push, proximal port, fast flush.","Poly VT = UNSYNC defibrillation — you can't sync what isn't regular.","Amiodarone 150 over 10 for wide-complex; procainamide is the alternative, but watch the pressure."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Tachycardia With a Pulse — ACLS Decision Algorithm","content":"Tachycardia identified (rate >100/min with a pulse)\n  → Assess for instability: hypotension, altered mental status, chest pain, acute heart failure, shock\n     → UNSTABLE: Immediate synchronized cardioversion\n        → Sedate if conscious and time permits\n        → Energy: 100 J for regular narrow or regular monomorphic VT; ≥200 J for AF/AFlutter\n        → If polymorphic VT: UNSYNCHRONIZED defibrillation (not synchronized)\n     → STABLE: Assess rhythm\n        → Narrow-complex, REGULAR (SVT):\n           → Vagal maneuvers first\n           → If ineffective: Adenosine 6 mg rapid IV push (proximal port + flush)\n           → If no response: 12 mg adenosine (may repeat once)\n           → If still refractory: beta-blocker or calcium-channel blocker\n        → Narrow-complex, IRREGULAR (AF/AFlutter):\n           → Rate control: diltiazem, metoprolol, or amiodarone\n           → Target resting HR <110/min (lenient) or <80/min (strict)\n           → Consider anticoagulation per guidelines\n        → Wide-complex, REGULAR (assume VT):\n           → Amiodarone 150 mg IV over 10 min (may repeat once)\n           → Alternative: Procainamide 20–50 mg/min IV\n           → If becomes unstable → synchronized cardioversion at 100 J\n        → Wide-complex, IRREGULAR:\n           → If polymorphic VT → UNSYNCHRONIZED defibrillation + magnesium\n           → If pre-excited AF → avoid AV-nodal blockers; consider procainamide or cardioversion\n  → In parallel: seek and treat reversible causes (hypoxia, electrolytes, toxins, ischemia)"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support (Tachycardia With a Pulse)","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Executive Summary (Synchronized cardioversion energies, adenosine protocol)","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9 (Procainamide, polymorphic VT management)"]},"c12":{"id":"c12","title":"Acute Coronary Syndromes","shortTitle":"ACS","estimatedStudyTime":40,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Identify STEMI on a 12-lead ECG and activate the appropriate reperfusion pathway.","State the 2025 first-medical-contact-to-device (door-to-balloon) goal for primary PCI.","Determine when fibrinolysis is indicated (onset <12 hours, anticipated PPCI delay >120 minutes) and list key contraindications.","Apply NSTEMI/unstable angina risk-stratification tools (TIMI, GRACE) to guide timing of invasive strategy.","Select appropriate initial antiplatelet and anticoagulation therapy for ACS.","Recognize nitroglycerin contraindications and the limited role of morphine and supplemental oxygen in ACS management.","Describe the 2025 ACC/AHA companion guideline recommendations for ACS management."],"summary":[{"title":"Recognition and Activation of the STEMI Pathway","content":"Acute coronary syndromes (ACS) encompass STEMI, NSTEMI, and unstable angina. The ACLS provider's first priority when STEMI is identified on a 12-lead ECG is immediate activation of the cardiac catheterization team for primary percutaneous coronary intervention (PPCI). The 2025 ACC/AHA companion guideline sets a first-medical-contact-to-device (FMC2D) time goal of ≤90 minutes — an aspirin-cath lab time — reflecting evidence that each 30-minute delay in reperfusion increases 1-year mortality by approximately 7.5% (relative). When ECG acquisition occurs in the prehospital setting, EMS should transmit the 12-lead to the receiving facility so the cath lab can be activated before the patient arrives."},{"title":"Fibrinolysis: When and How","content":"Fibrinolytic therapy (alteplase, tenecteplase) is indicated when symptom onset is within 12 hours and the anticipated door-to-balloon delay exceeds 120 minutes (e.g., transfer from a non-PCI-capable facility with estimated transport plus activation time >120 minutes). The 2025 AHA guideline reaffirms this threshold. Fibrinolysis is most effective within the first 3 hours of symptom onset and must be initiated rapidly (door-to-needle ≤30 minutes). Fibrinolysis is contraindicated with active internal bleeding (excluding menses), history of hemorrhagic stroke, ischemic stroke within 3 months, intracranial neoplasm or AVM, known active peptic ulcer, aortic dissection, significant head/facial trauma within 3 months, INR >1.7, platelet count <100,000/mm³, or current use of anticoagulants with supratherapeutic levels. Successful fibrinolysis (evidenced by ≥50% ST-elevation resolution within 60–90 minutes) should be followed by transfer to a PCI-capable center for routine early angiography (within 3–24 hours). Failed fibrinolysis warrants emergent rescue PCI."},{"title":"NSTEMI/Unstable Angina and Risk Stratification","content":"NSTEMI and unstable angina present without ST-segment elevation on ECG. Risk stratification using TIMI or GRACE scores guides the timing of invasive strategy: early invasive (within 24 hours) for high-risk features (recurrent angina, hemodynamic instability, dynamic ST/T changes, elevated troponin), and delayed invasive or ischemia-guided strategy for lower-risk presentations. Dual antiplatelet therapy (aspirin plus a P2Y12 inhibitor — ticagrelor or prasugrel preferred over clopidogrel per 2025 ACC/AHA recommendations) and anticoagulation with unfractionated heparin or enoxaparin are initiated early regardless of strategy."},{"title":"Initial Medical Therapy: Medications That Matter","content":"Aspirin 162–325 mg chewed immediately is the universal first drug for all ACS. A P2Y12 inhibitor (ticagrelor 180 mg loading or prasugrel 60 mg loading — prasugrel contraindicated with prior stroke/TIA or age ≥75) is added. Anticoagulation with unfractionated heparin (60 U/kg bolus, max 4,000 U, then 12 U/kg/hr infusion) or enoxaparin is started. Nitroglycerin 0.4 mg sublingual every 5 minutes ×3 doses for ongoing ischemic pain, but is contraindicated with right ventricular infarction (suspected by inferior STEMI with hypotension), recent PDE5 inhibitor use (sildenafil within 24 hours, tadalafil within 48 hours), or systolic blood pressure <90 mmHg. Supplemental oxygen is recommended ONLY if SpO₂ <90% or the patient is in respiratory distress — routine supplemental oxygen in normoxic ACS patients does not improve outcomes and may be harmful (DETO2X-AMI trial). Morphine use is cautioned against due to potential for delayed drug absorption (impairing P2Y12 inhibitor bioavailability) and adverse hemodynamic effects; it should be reserved for refractory chest pain unresponsive to nitroglycerin and only when the patient is hemodynamically stable."},{"title":"STEMI Identification at Scene: 12-Lead Interpretation","content":"The ACLS provider must acquire and interpret a 12-lead ECG rapidly. STEMI is defined as ≥1 mm ST elevation in two contiguous limb leads or ≥2 mm in two contiguous precordial leads (V2–V3: ≥2.5 mm in men ≥40, ≥1.5 mm in women). New or presumably new left bundle branch block (LBBB) in the clinical context of ischemia should be treated as STEMI-equivalent using modified Sgarbossa criteria (concordant ST elevation ≥1 mm, concordant ST depression ≥1 mm in V1–V3, or discordant ST elevation with S-wave amplitude ≥50% and ratio ST elevation/S-wave ≥0.25). Posterior MI (ST depression V1–V3) should be confirmed with posterior leads V7–V9 (ST elevation ≥0.5 mm). Right ventricular infarction should be assessed in inferior STEMI using right-sided lead V4R (ST elevation ≥1 mm)."},{"title":"2025 ACC/AHA Companion Guideline Highlights","content":"The 2025 ACC/AHA/ACEP/NAEMSP/SCAI guideline for acute coronary syndromes emphasizes: FMC2D ≤90 minutes for primary PCI; fibrinolysis when onset <12 hours and anticipated PPCI delay >120 minutes; routine early angiography within 3–24 hours after successful fibrinolysis; ticagrelor or prasugrel as preferred P2Y12 inhibitors over clopidogrel for invasive strategy; morphine use reserved for refractory pain with caution regarding drug absorption; oxygen only for SpO₂ <90%; and a shift toward risk-stratified timing of invasive intervention for NSTEMI rather than a one-size-fits-all approach."}],"clinicalPearls":["Each 30-minute delay in primary PCI increases 1-year mortality by approximately 7.5% — time is myocardium.","Fibrinolysis is most effective within the first 3 hours; even within the 12-hour window, earlier is better.","Nitroglycerin is contraindicated in right ventricular infarction — suspect RV infarction in any inferior STEMI with hypotension and check V4R.","Routine oxygen in normoxic ACS patients does not improve outcomes and may cause coronary vasoconstriction (DETO2X-AMI trial).","Morphine delays P2Y12 inhibitor absorption — avoid if possible; reserve for refractory pain after nitroglycerin failure.","Always transmit prehospital 12-leads so the cath lab activates before patient arrival."],"redFlags":["Inferior STEMI with hypotension — suspect right ventricular infarction; nitroglycerin is contraindicated.","Patient took a PDE5 inhibitor within 24–48 hours — nitroglycerin can cause life-threatening hypotension.","Fibrinolysis given without ruling out contraindications (active bleeding, recent stroke, INR >1.7, platelets <100K).","Symptom onset >12 hours with no ongoing ischemia — fibrinolysis is not indicated.","Routine supplemental oxygen in a patient with SpO₂ 98% — provides no benefit and may worsen coronary perfusion."],"commonMistakes":["Delaying ECG acquisition — a 12-lead should be obtained and interpreted within 10 minutes of first medical contact.","Giving nitroglycerin in an inferior STEMI with hypotension without checking for RV infarction first.","Using morphine as a first-line analgesic for ACS chest pain rather than after nitroglycerin failure.","Administering routine oxygen to ACS patients with normal SpO₂.","Confusing door-to-balloon (D2B) time with first-medical-contact-to-device (FMC2D) time — FMC2D starts at first medical contact, not at the emergency department door.","Failing to identify posterior MI (ST depression V1–V3) and obtain posterior leads V7–V9."],"memoryAids":["'Time is myocardium' — every 30 min delay costs ~7.5% more mortality at 1 year.","'N-O-M-I' for nitroglycerin contraindications: Nitro off if RV infarct, On PDE5 inhibitors, Mean arterial pressure too low (SBP <90).","Fibrinolysis = '12 and 120' — onset within 12 hours, PPCI delay >120 minutes.","O₂ only <90% — don't oxygenate normal patients.","Aspirin first, always — 162–325 mg chewed before anything else."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"ACS Initial Management Pathway","content":"Chest pain / ACS presentation\n  → 12-lead ECG within 10 minutes of first medical contact\n  → ST elevation or new LBBB identified (STEMI)\n     → Activate cath lab immediately (FMC2D ≤90 min)\n     → Aspirin 162–325 mg chewed\n     → If PPCI achievable within 90 min → primary PCI\n     → If PPCI delayed >120 min AND onset <12 hours → fibrinolysis (door-to-needle ≤30 min)\n        → Successful (≥50% ST resolution) → transfer to PCI center for angiography within 3–24 h\n        → Failed → rescue PCI\n     → Check right-sided leads (V4R) if inferior STEMI → if RV infarction → NO nitroglycerin\n  → No ST elevation (NSTEMI / unstable angina)\n     → Aspirin + P2Y12 inhibitor (ticagrelor/prasugrel) + anticoagulation (heparin)\n     → Risk stratify (TIMI/GRACE)\n     → High-risk → early invasive strategy within 24 h\n     → Lower risk → delayed invasive or ischemia-guided strategy\n  → Oxygen ONLY if SpO₂ <90%\n  → Morphine ONLY for refractory pain after nitroglycerin failure; caution with P2Y12 absorption"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC","2025 ACC/AHA/ACEP/NAEMSP/SCAI Guideline for the Management of Patients With Acute Coronary Syndromes","DETO2X-AMI Trial — Routine Oxygen in Suspected Myocardial Infarction (NEJM 2017)","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support"],"graphics":[{"id":"c12_g01","section":"summary","sectionIndex":0,"url":"../../images/courses/acls/c12_g01.webp","alt":"Acute Coronary Syndrome: Coronary Angioplasty (PCI)","caption":"Cross-section of a coronary artery showing catheter balloon inflation and stent placement."}]},"c13":{"id":"c13","title":"Acute Stroke","shortTitle":"Stroke","estimatedStudyTime":35,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Describe the stroke chain of survival and the role of the ACLS provider in stroke recognition and stabilization.","Perform and interpret the Cincinnati Prehospital Stroke Scale and FAST screening tools.","State the IV thrombolysis (alteplase/tPA) time window, dose, and administration protocol.","List the key blood pressure management thresholds before, during, and after IV thrombolysis.","Identify indications and the time window for mechanical thrombectomy.","Recognize common stroke mimics and differentiate them from true stroke.","Apply glucose and fever management principles in the acute stroke patient."],"summary":[{"title":"Stroke Chain of Survival","content":"The stroke chain of survival parallels the cardiac arrest chain but emphasizes speed of recognition and time to definitive reperfusion: detection and activation (recognition of stroke symptoms and EMS activation), dispatch and prehospital care (rapid EMS response, Cincinnati/FAST screening in the field, prehospital notification to the receiving stroke center), delivery of acute treatment (door-to-CT and door-to-needle for IV thrombolysis; door-to-groin-puncture for thrombectomy), and recovery and rehabilitation. The ACLS provider's role is early recognition, stabilization (airway, glucose, blood pressure), and rapid transport to the most appropriate stroke center — time is brain."},{"title":"Stroke Screening: Cincinnati and FAST","content":"The Cincinnati Prehospital Stroke Scale (CPSS) tests three findings: facial droop (ask the patient to smile — asymmetry is abnormal), arm drift (ask the patient to close eyes and extend both arms — downward drift is abnormal), and speech abnormality (ask the patient to say 'You can't teach an old dog new tricks' — slurred or inappropriate words are abnormal). The presence of any one of these three findings has a high probability of stroke. The FAST mnemonic (Face, Arms, Speech, Time) is a public-facing equivalent. Both tools are designed for rapid identification, not for differentiating stroke subtypes — the ACLS provider does not need to distinguish ischemic from hemorrhagic stroke in the field; the priority is rapid transport and prehospital notification."},{"title":"IV Thrombolysis: Alteplase (tPA) Protocol","content":"Intravenous alteplase (tPA) is the pharmacologic treatment for acute ischemic stroke when symptom onset is within 4.5 hours. The dose is 0.9 mg/kg IV (maximum 90 mg): 10% of the total dose is given as an IV bolus over 1 minute, and the remaining 90% is infused over 60 minutes. A non-contrast CT of the head must be obtained BEFORE tPA administration to exclude intracranial hemorrhage. Blood pressure must be lowered to <185/110 mmHg before tPA initiation and maintained at <180/105 mmHg during and for 24 hours after infusion. Key contraindications include: evidence of intracranial hemorrhage on CT, symptoms suggestive of subarachnoid hemorrhage, active internal bleeding, platelet count <100,000/mm³, INR >1.7, current use of direct thrombin inhibitors or factor Xa inhibitors with elevated lab tests, blood glucose <50 mg/dL, CT showing multilobar infarction (>1/3 of cerebral hemisphere). The 2025 AHA guidelines reaffirm the 4.5-hour window as the standard for IV thrombolysis."},{"title":"Blood Pressure Management in Acute Stroke","content":"Blood pressure management depends on whether tPA is administered. For patients receiving tPA: pre-tPA, blood pressure must be <185/110 mmHg (use IV labetalol 10–20 mg over 1–2 min, repeat once if needed, or nicardipine infusion 5 mg/hr titrated up by 2.5 mg/hr every 5–15 min, max 15 mg/hr); post-tPA, maintain BP <180/105 mmHg for at least 24 hours and reduce blood pressure by approximately 15% in the first 24 hours after treatment. For patients NOT receiving tPA: permissive hypertension is allowed up to 220/120 mmHg in the first 24 hours if there is no evidence of intracranial hemorrhage, cardiac ischemia, or aortic dissection, to maintain cerebral perfusion. The 2025 AHA guidelines maintain these well-established thresholds."},{"title":"Mechanical Thrombectomy: Indications and Time Window","content":"Endovascular mechanical thrombectomy is indicated for acute ischemic stroke caused by large-vessel occlusion (LVO) of the internal carotid artery or proximal middle cerebral artery (M1 segment). The standard time window is within 6 hours of symptom onset based on conventional imaging. However, advanced neuroimaging (CT perfusion or diffusion-weighted MRI) demonstrating a salvageable penumbra with limited completed infarction core can extend the thrombectomy window up to 24 hours in selected patients, as supported by the DAWN and DEFUSE-3 trials and reaffirmed in the 2025 guidelines. Patients eligible for both tPA and thrombectomy should receive tPA immediately and proceed to thrombectomy without delay — tPA should not be withheld while awaiting thrombectomy."},{"title":"Stroke Mimics and Stabilization","content":"Common stroke mimics include hypoglycemia (always check glucose first), seizures with postictal paralysis (Todd's paralysis), migraine with aura, complex partial seizures, Bell's palsy (spares the forehead), and brain tumors. Hypoglycemia is the most important mimic to rule out because it is immediately correctable. Fever (temperature >38°C) should be treated aggressively with antipyretics and cooling measures, as hyperthermia worsens ischemic brain injury. Glucose should be maintained in the normal range (70–180 mg/dL); both hypoglycemia (<60 mg/dL) and severe hyperglycemia (>180 mg/dL) are associated with worse outcomes. The ACLS provider's role includes airway management if needed, glucose normalization, fever treatment, and rapid transport — the provider does not determine stroke subtype in the field."}],"clinicalPearls":["Time is brain — approximately 1.9 million neurons are lost per minute of untreated large-vessel ischemic stroke.","Always check glucose first — hypoglycemia is the most critical and treatable stroke mimic.","tPA dose: 0.9 mg/kg (max 90 mg), 10% bolus over 1 min, remainder over 60 min — do NOT use the cardiac arrest tPA dose (which is different).","Blood pressure targets: <185/110 before tPA, <180/105 during and after tPA, with ~15% reduction in the first 24 hours.","Permissive hypertension up to 220/120 in non-tPA candidates for the first 24 hours (no ICH, no cardiac ischemia).","CT head before tPA — always. The only absolute indication for tPA is acute ischemic stroke within 4.5 hours with no hemorrhage on imaging."],"redFlags":["Giving tPA without a non-contrast CT — intracranial hemorrhage must be excluded first.","Blood pressure >185/110 at time of tPA administration — must be lowered first.","Suspected stroke with glucose <50 mg/dL — correct the glucose; this may be the only problem.","Symptom onset >4.5 hours with no advanced imaging — standard IV tPA window has closed.","Lateralizing deficits resolving completely (TIA) — still warrants urgent evaluation; TIAs are warning signs."],"commonMistakes":["Using the cardiac arrest tPA dose (different from stroke tPA) — stroke dose is 0.9 mg/kg, not a flat dose.","Failing to check blood glucose in every suspected stroke presentation.","Delaying CT scan because 'it's obviously a stroke' — hemorrhage must be excluded before tPA.","Lowering blood pressure too aggressively in non-tPA candidates, risking cerebral hypoperfusion.","Confusing Bell's palsy (forehead spared) with central facial droop (forehead involved) — both cause unilateral weakness but the distribution differs.","Withholding tPA while awaiting thrombectomy evaluation — tPA should be given immediately if the patient meets criteria."],"memoryAids":["FAST: Face, Arms, Speech, Time — if any one is abnormal, activate stroke response.","tPA dose = '0.9, max 90' — 0.9 mg/kg, max 90 mg; 10% bolus, 90% over 60 min.","BP targets = '185/110 before, 180/105 after' tPA.","Thrombectomy window = '6 standard, 24 with penumbra imaging'.","Always glucose first — 'Stroke + low sugar = sugar first.'","Permissive BP = '220/120 for non-tPA — but only if no bleed.'"],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Acute Stroke Initial Management (ACLS Provider)","content":"Suspected stroke identified (CPSS/FAST positive)\n  → Activate stroke alert / notify receiving stroke center\n  → Check blood glucose immediately\n     → If <50 mg/dL → administer IV dextrose; reassess (may be stroke mimic)\n  → 12-lead ECG, vital signs, SpO₂\n  → Transport to nearest stroke-capable center (preferably Comprehensive Stroke Center if LVO suspected)\n  → On arrival: non-contrast CT head (MANDATORY before any reperfusion)\n     → Intracranial hemorrhage found → no tPA; neurosurgical consultation\n     → No hemorrhage; ischemic stroke confirmed\n        → Symptom onset ≤4.5 hours AND no contraindications\n           → Blood pressure <185/110? (lower with labetalol/nicardipine if needed)\n              → YES → tPA: 0.9 mg/kg (max 90 mg), 10% bolus over 1 min, remainder over 60 min\n              → Maintain BP <180/105 during and for 24 h after tPA\n        → Large-vessel occlusion suspected and onset ≤6 h (or ≤24 h with perfusion imaging)\n           → Proceed to mechanical thrombectomy (do not delay tPA for this)\n        → Symptom onset >4.5 h or tPA contraindicated\n           → Permissive hypertension up to 220/120 if no hemorrhage/cardiac ischemia\n           → If LVO and within window → thrombectomy\n  → Maintain normothermia (treat fever >38°C aggressively)\n  → Maintain glucose 70–180 mg/dL"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC","AHA/ASA Guidelines for the Early Management of Patients With Acute Ischemic Stroke (2019, reaffirmed 2025)","DAWN Trial — Thrombectomy 6–24 Hours After Stroke (NEJM 2018)","DEFUSE-3 Trial — Thrombectomy 6–16 Hours After Stroke (NEJM 2018)","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support"]},"c14":{"id":"c14","title":"Post-Cardiac Arrest Care, ECPR & Recovery","shortTitle":"Post-Arrest & ECPR","estimatedStudyTime":45,"difficulty":"Advanced","learningObjectives":["Describe the post-ROSC bundle including airway management, hemodynamic targets, 12-lead ECG, temperature management, and neuroprognostication.","State the 2025 AHA recommended temperature management targets and duration after ROSC.","Identify hemodynamic targets (MAP, SBP) for post-ROSC patients and the rationale for hemodynamic optimization.","Explain why neuroprognostication must be deferred to ≥72 hours after ROSC and the multimodal approach used.","Describe the indications, contraindications, and procedural considerations for extracorporeal CPR (ECPR).","Outline the process for weaning from mechanical circulatory support and early rehabilitation and recovery planning."],"summary":[{"title":"The Post-ROSC Bundle","content":"Return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC) is not the end of resuscitation — it is the beginning of post-cardiac arrest care, which the 2025 AHA guidelines frame as a direct continuation of resuscitation. The post-ROSC bundle includes: (1) airway management — confirm and secure the advanced airway with continuous waveform capnography (target ETCO₂ 35–45 mmHg during normothermic ventilation; avoid both hypo- and hyperventilation); (2) hemodynamic optimization — MAP ≥65 mmHg (SBP >90 mmHg) using IV fluid boluses and vasopressors (norepinephrine preferred) as needed; (3) 12-lead ECG — obtain immediately to identify STEMI, which is present in approximately 25–50% of cardiac arrest patients and mandates emergent coronary angiography and PCI; (4) temperature management — initiate temperature control (see below); (5) identify and treat reversible causes — ongoing H's and T's evaluation; (6) neuroprognostication — deferred to ≥72 hours after ROSC."},{"title":"Temperature Management After Cardiac Arrest","content":"The 2025 AHA guidelines recommend maintaining temperature ≤37.5°C after cardiac arrest. Continuous temperature monitoring is mandatory (using core probes: esophageal, bladder, or pulmonary artery). If targeted temperature management (TTM) is chosen as a therapeutic strategy, the recommended target range is 32–37.5°C, maintained for at least 36 hours. Fever (>37.5°C) must be treated aggressively and immediately with active cooling measures and antipyretics, as hyperthermia exacerbates ischemic brain injury. The 2025 guidelines support an approach of controlled normothermia (≤37.5°C) as the minimum standard, with 32–37.5°C TTM as an acceptable option — neither approach has been shown to be clearly superior, and the choice should be guided by institutional protocol and individual patient factors. Rewarming, if TTM was used, should be slow and controlled (rate ≤0.25°C per hour)."},{"title":"Hemodynamic Targets After ROSC","content":"Systemic ischemia-reperfusion injury after cardiac arrest causes vasoplegia, myocardial stunning, and distributive shock. The goal is MAP ≥65 mmHg (SBP >90 mmHg) to maintain adequate cerebral and coronary perfusion. Vasopressors — particularly norepinephrine (starting 0.1–0.5 mcg/kg/min, titrated to MAP) — are first-line; dobutamine (2.5–20 mcg/kg/min) may be added if there is myocardial dysfunction with adequate preload but persistent hypotension. IV fluid resuscitation with isotonic crystalloid boluses (250–500 mL) is used for hypovolemia but should be cautious to avoid fluid overload in the setting of myocardial stunning. Central venous pressure, mixed venous oxygen saturation (SvO₂), and point-of-care echocardiography can guide further hemodynamic management. Avoid hypotension (MAP <60) and hypertension (MAP >100) — both worsen neurological outcomes."},{"title":"Neuroprognostication: Timing, Approach, and Modalities","content":"Neuroprognostication MUST be deferred to at least 72 hours after ROSC — or after rewarming if TTM was used — to allow clearance of sedation, paralytic agents, metabolic derangements, and hypothermia effects that confound neurological examination. The 2025 AHA guidelines emphasize a multimodal approach combining: (1) clinical examination — bilateral absent pupillary and corneal reflexes at ≥72 hours, absent motor response to painful stimuli (extensor posturing or less) at ≥72 hours; (2) electrophysiology — bilateral absent somatosensory evoked potentials (SSEPs) at ≥72 hours, continuous EEG patterns (status myoclonus, burst suppression without epileptiform discharges, malignant patterns); (3) serum biomarkers — neuron-specific enolase (NSE) >33 mcg/L at 48–72 hours and S-100B protein; (4) neuroimaging — CT showing diffuse cerebral edema or loss of gray-white differentiation, MRI showing restricted diffusion in cortical and deep gray matter. NO SINGLE modality is sufficient alone; the combination of modalities increases prognostic accuracy. An early poor examination (before 72 hours) does NOT reliably predict poor outcome and must not be used to withdraw life-sustaining therapy."},{"title":"Extracorporeal CPR (ECPR): Indications and Approach","content":"ECPR (extracorporeal CPR) involves rapid initiation of veno-arterial extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (VA-ECMO) to provide temporary circulatory and oxygenation support during cardiac arrest. Per the 2025 AHA guidelines, ECPR may be considered for selected patients with refractory cardiac arrest (persistent VF/pVT despite standard ACLS measures including high-quality CPR, appropriate medications, and defibrillation), when low-flow time is expected to be <60 minutes, the patient has a potentially reversible cause of arrest, and the patient is a suitable candidate (age, comorbidities, functional status). ECPR requires an experienced, high-volume team and institutional infrastructure — it is NOT a standalone intervention but part of a comprehensive post-arrest care program. Cannulation is typically femoral (venous drainage from the femoral vein, arterial return to the femoral artery), performed percutaneously under ultrasound guidance. Complications include limb ischemia (distal perfusion catheter recommended), bleeding, cannula malposition, and hemolysis. ECPR is a bridge to further therapy (PCI, TTM, recovery) — weaning depends on recovery of native cardiac function."},{"title":"Weaning, Rehabilitation, and Recovery Planning","content":"Patients on mechanical circulatory support (ECMO, IABP, Impella) are weaned as native cardiac function recovers, guided by echocardiographic assessment (ejection fraction, wall motion), hemodynamic stability on decreasing support, and ETCO₂ trends. Weaning is performed in a monitored setting (ICU or cath lab) with resuscitation equipment immediately available. Early rehabilitation begins in the ICU with passive range of motion, upright positioning when hemodynamically stable, and early mobilization as tolerated. The recovery link of the chain encompasses: comprehensive neurorehabilitation, psychological support for the survivor and family, assessment of quality of life, identification of reversible arrest causes requiring ongoing treatment (e.g., coronary disease, arrhythmia management), and advance care planning discussions. Referral to cardiac rehabilitation, neurorehabilitation, and psychosocial support services should be initiated before discharge."}],"clinicalPearls":["ROSC is the start of a new resuscitation, not the end of the old one — the post-ROSC bundle must be initiated immediately.","Obtain a 12-lead ECG immediately after ROSC — up to 50% of post-arrest patients have acute STEMI and need emergent PCI.","Temperature ≤37.5°C is the minimum standard; if TTM is used, 32–37.5°C for ≥36 hours.","Neuroprognostication before 72 hours is unreliable — sedation, paralysis, and metabolic derangements confound the exam.","Use MULTIPLE modalities for neuroprognostication — no single test is sufficient.","ECPR is a bridge, not a destination — it buys time for reversible causes to be treated.","MAP ≥65 mmHg is the minimum; both hypotension and hypertension worsen neurological outcomes."],"redFlags":["Withdrawing life-sustaining therapy based on a neurological exam performed before 72 hours post-ROSC.","Fever (>37.5°C) in the first 72 hours after cardiac arrest — must be treated immediately.","Hypotension (MAP <60) after ROSC — aggressively support hemodynamics to protect the brain.","ECPR attempted without a reversible cause identified or with low-flow time expected >60 minutes.","Rapid rewarming after TTM — must be controlled at ≤0.25°C/hour to prevent rebound intracranial hypertension.","Ignoring STEMI on post-ROSC ECG — emergent PCI is indicated and should not be delayed."],"commonMistakes":["Hyperventilating the post-arrest patient (low ETCO₂) — target ETCO₂ 35–45 mmHg; avoid both hypo- and hyperventilation.","Performing neuroprognostication too early (before 72 hours) — this leads to premature withdrawal of care.","Using a single prognostic test to determine outcome — multimodal assessment is mandatory.","Failing to check a 12-lead ECG after ROSC — STEMI may be present and treatable.","Aggressive fluid resuscitation in myocardial stunning without echocardiographic guidance — risks pulmonary edema.","Using sedation/paralysis to control temperature without documenting clearance before neuroprognostication.","Confusing ECPR with standard ACLS — ECPR is a specialized intervention requiring institutional capability."],"memoryAids":["Post-ROSC bundle: 'Airway, Hemodynamics, 12-lead, Temperature, H's/T's, Prognostication' — AHTHP.","Temperature: '37.5 max, 32–36 TTM, 36 hours minimum'.","Neuroprognostication: '72 hours, then assess — multimodal, not singular'.","ECPR: 'Refractory VF/pVT, <60 min low-flow, reversible cause, experienced team'.","Hemodynamics: 'MAP 65, SBP 90 — not too low, not too high'.","Post-ROSC ECG: '25–50% have STEMI — don't miss it'."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Post-ROSC Management Bundle","content":"ROSC achieved\n  → Confirm and secure airway with waveform capnography (ETCO₂ 35–45 mmHg)\n  → IV fluid bolus (250–500 mL) + vasopressor (norepinephrine) to MAP ≥65 mmHg\n  → 12-lead ECG immediately\n     → STEMI identified → emergent coronary angiography + PCI\n     → No STEMI → continue monitoring\n  → Non-contrast CT head (exclude intracranial hemorrhage)\n  → Initiate temperature management\n     → Maintain ≤37.5°C at minimum\n     → If TTM chosen → 32–37.5°C for ≥36 hours\n     → Treat any fever >37.5°C immediately\n  → Continuous monitoring (arterial line, ETCO₂, temperature)\n  → Identify and treat reversible causes (H's and T's)\n  → Sedation/analgesia as needed for comfort and temperature management\n  → Neuroprognostication deferred ≥72 hours after ROSC (or after rewarming)\n     → Multimodal: clinical exam + SSEPs + EEG + NSE/S-100B + imaging\n  → Rehabilitation planning and family communication"},{"title":"ECPR Selection and Initiation","content":"Refractory cardiac arrest (persistent VF/pVT despite standard ACLS)\n  → Is the arrest potentially reversible? (acute MI, PE, myocarditis, drug toxicity, hypothermia)\n     → NO → continue standard ACLS; consider cessation criteria\n     → YES → evaluate ECPR candidacy\n        → Low-flow time expected <60 minutes? (time from CPR start to ECMO flow)\n           → NO → ECPR unlikely to benefit; continue standard ACLS\n           → YES → candidate suitable? (age, comorbidities, functional status, no absolute contraindications)\n              → NO → continue standard ACLS\n              → YES → Activate ECPR team\n                 → Rapid femoral cannulation (venous + arterial) under ultrasound guidance\n                 → Initiate VA-ECMO flow\n                 → Place distal perfusion catheter to prevent limb ischemia\n                 → Continue resuscitation with ECMO support\n                 → Identify and treat reversible cause (PCI if acute MI, etc.)\n                 → Post-ROSC management bundle\n  → Weaning from ECMO: guided by echocardiographic recovery of cardiac function, hemodynamic stability on decreasing flow, and clinical assessment"}],"references":["AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 11: Post-Cardiac Arrest Care","AHA 2025 Guidelines for CPR and ECC — Part 9: Adult Advanced Life Support","TTM2 Trial — Targeted Hypothermia vs Normothermia After Cardiac Arrest (NEJM 2021)","ECPR Consensus on Patient Selection and Techniques (ILCOR 2023)","AHA/ILCOR Advisory — Extracorporeal CPR for Cardiac Arrest (2025)"],"graphics":[{"id":"c14_g01","section":"summary","sectionIndex":4,"url":"../../images/courses/acls/c14_g01.webp","alt":"Veno-Arterial ECMO (VA-ECMO) for ECPR","caption":"Diagram of a patient receiving veno-arterial ECMO during ECPR, showing femoral venous drainage, pump, oxygenator, and femoral arterial return."}]}},"flashcards":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cards":[{"id":"c01_fc01","question":"What are the six links of the 2025 AHA universal Chain of Survival?","answer":"Activation of emergency response, high-quality CPR, defibrillation, advanced resuscitation interventions, post-cardiac arrest care, and recovery.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc02","question":"Which link of the chain does the ACLS provider primarily own?","answer":"Link 4 — advanced resuscitation interventions (airway management, IV/IO access, rhythm-specific therapy, medications, treatment of reversible causes).","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc03","question":"What is the main systems-of-care emphasis for OHCA?","answer":"Bystander recognition and CPR, dispatcher-assisted instructions, public-access AED use, and rapid EMS response.","category":"OHCA vs IHCA"},{"id":"c01_fc04","question":"What is the main systems-of-care emphasis for IHCA?","answer":"Surveillance and prevention — continuous monitoring, early-warning scores, and rapid-response/medical emergency teams that catch deterioration before full arrest.","category":"OHCA vs IHCA"},{"id":"c01_fc05","question":"What capabilities define a regionalized cardiac arrest center?","answer":"24/7 coronary angiography/PCI capability, targeted temperature management, multimodal neuroprognostication, and ECPR capability when indicated.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc06","question":"Why should advanced interventions never come at the cost of compression fraction?","answer":"Because high-quality, minimally-interrupted CPR and early defibrillation remain the strongest predictors of survival; advanced care is additive, not a substitute.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc07","question":"Name three metrics tracked in Utstein-style CQI reporting.","answer":"Any three of: chest compression fraction, time to first shock, time to first epinephrine dose, ROSC rate, survival to discharge, neurologic outcome.","category":"Quality Improvement"},{"id":"c01_fc08","question":"Why is post-cardiac arrest care described as a 'continuation' of resuscitation rather than a separate phase?","answer":"Because the same anticipatory, team-based mindset and treatment of reversible causes carries forward after ROSC into airway, hemodynamic, and temperature management — it is not the finish line.","category":"Post-Arrest"},{"id":"c01_fc09","question":"What system tool helps prevent in-hospital cardiac arrest before it happens?","answer":"Early-warning scores paired with rapid-response or medical emergency teams that respond to deteriorating patients.","category":"IHCA"},{"id":"c01_fc10","question":"What is the purpose of debriefing after a resuscitation?","answer":"To identify system and team performance gaps using real data, feeding lessons back into training and protocols (part of continuous quality improvement).","category":"Quality Improvement"},{"id":"c01_fc11","question":"What replaced the previously separate adult/pediatric and IHCA/OHCA chains in 2025?","answer":"A single universal six-link Chain of Survival, with a separate Neonatal Chain of Care for newborns.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc12","question":"What is the sixth link of the Chain of Survival and what does it include?","answer":"Recovery — rehabilitation, psychological support, treatment planning, and support for survivors and families.","category":"Recovery"},{"id":"c01_fc13","question":"What analogous systems of care are cardiac arrest centers modeled after?","answer":"Trauma systems and stroke systems of care, which regionalize time-critical patients to centers with specialized capability.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc14","question":"What should never be delayed by attempts at advanced airway or IV/IO access?","answer":"Chest compressions and defibrillation — advanced procedures must be fit around, not instead of, high-quality CPR.","category":"Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc15","question":"Give an example of a rhythm-appropriate ACLS therapy that begins at Link 4.","answer":"Examples include defibrillation/cardioversion timing refinement, epinephrine and antiarrhythmic administration, and advanced airway placement with capnography.","category":"Systems of Care"},{"id":"c01_fc16","question":"Why is team-based, multidisciplinary care emphasized in ACLS?","answer":"Resuscitation requires simultaneous tasks (compressions, airway, drugs, documentation, family communication) that no single provider can perform alone, so defined roles and closed-loop communication are essential.","category":"Team Dynamics"}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","cards":[{"id":"c02_fc01","question":"What is the target compression rate and depth in ACLS?","answer":"Rate 100–120/min; depth at least 2 in (5 cm) and not more than 2.4 in (6 cm), with full recoil.","category":"CPR Quality"},{"id":"c02_fc02","question":"What is chest compression fraction (CCF) and its target?","answer":"The proportion of resuscitation time spent actually compressing; target at least 60%, ideally above 80%.","category":"CPR Quality"},{"id":"c02_fc03","question":"How often should compressors switch and why?","answer":"About every 2 minutes (or sooner if fatigued), because compression quality decays with rescuer fatigue even before it is subjectively noticed.","category":"CPR Quality"},{"id":"c02_fc04","question":"What ventilation pattern is used once an advanced airway is placed?","answer":"Continuous compressions with 1 breath every 6 seconds (about 10 breaths/min), no longer pausing compressions for breaths.","category":"Ventilation"},{"id":"c02_fc05","question":"Why is over-ventilation harmful during CPR?","answer":"It raises intrathoracic pressure, reduces venous return, and lowers cardiac output, worsening perfusion during compressions.","category":"Ventilation"},{"id":"c02_fc06","question":"What is closed-loop communication?","answer":"An order given to a named person, repeated back by the receiver, and confirmed once completed, to prevent missed or duplicated tasks.","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c02_fc07","question":"Give an example of closed-loop communication for a medication order.","answer":"Leader: 'Sarah, push epinephrine 1 mg now.' Sarah: 'Giving epinephrine 1 mg now.' Sarah (after): 'Epinephrine 1 mg given.'","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c02_fc08","question":"What is 'knowing your limitations' in team dynamics?","answer":"Communicating to the team when a task is beyond your training or current capability, so someone else can take it over safely.","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c02_fc09","question":"What is constructive intervention?","answer":"Respectfully speaking up when you notice an error or unsafe action about to happen, rather than staying silent due to hierarchy.","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c02_fc10","question":"What is the role of a dedicated CPR coach?","answer":"To watch and give real-time feedback on compression rate, depth, recoil, and pause duration, freeing the team leader to manage rhythm and overall care.","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c02_fc11","question":"What compression-to-breath ratio is used before an advanced airway is placed?","answer":"30 compressions to 2 breaths, minimizing the pause for breath delivery.","category":"Ventilation"},{"id":"c02_fc12","question":"Why is mutual respect emphasized as a team dynamics element?","answer":"Because a stressed, hierarchical, or disrespectful environment discourages team members from speaking up about errors, degrading patient safety.","category":"Team Dynamics"},{"id":"c02_fc13","question":"What should a team do if compression pauses are trending longer than 10 seconds?","answer":"Identify the cause (e.g., slow rhythm check, prolonged airway attempt) and correct it immediately — pauses over 10 seconds sharply reduce perfusion.","category":"CPR Quality"},{"id":"c02_fc14","question":"Why is CCF called a 'team score' rather than an individual one?","answer":"Because every team member's actions (or delays) that pause compressions reduce the shared CCF metric for the whole resuscitation.","category":"CPR Quality"},{"id":"c02_fc15","question":"What is a common mistake with ventilation timing after an advanced airway is placed?","answer":"Continuing to cycle 30:2 instead of switching to continuous compressions with a breath every 6 seconds.","category":"Common Mistakes"},{"id":"c02_fc16","question":"Besides depth and rate, what other compression quality element must be maintained?","answer":"Full chest recoil between compressions, allowing the heart to refill.","category":"CPR Quality"}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","cards":[{"id":"c03_fc01","question":"What is the gold standard for confirming endotracheal tube placement?","answer":"Waveform capnography — the presence of a characteristic rectangular CO2 waveform with a consistent ETCO2 reading on every breath confirms tracheal placement.","category":"Airway Confirmation"},{"id":"c03_fc02","question":"What does an absent capnography waveform after intubation strongly suggest?","answer":"Esophageal tube placement — the tube must be repositioned or replaced immediately before ventilation is continued.","category":"Airway Confirmation"},{"id":"c03_fc03","question":"What is the target ETCO2 value during CPR that indicates adequate compression quality?","answer":"ETCO2 ≥10 mmHg — values below this threshold suggest inadequate compression rate, depth, recoil, or fraction and should prompt CPR quality reassessment.","category":"Capnography"},{"id":"c03_fc04","question":"What does a sudden, sustained ETCO2 rise to 40 mmHg or above during CPR typically indicate?","answer":"Return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC) — restored native cardiac output delivers substantially more CO2 to the lungs, causing a sharp rise in ETCO2.","category":"Capnography"},{"id":"c03_fc05","question":"Name the two supraglottic airways commonly used in ACLS and describe their key difference.","answer":"The i-gel uses a non-inflatable gel-filled cushion for sealing; the King LT uses a dual-lumen design with proximal and distal cuffs to seal the esophagus and pharynx.","category":"Supraglottic Airways"},{"id":"c03_fc06","question":"How does waveform capnography reflect CPR quality during cardiac arrest?","answer":"ETCO2 values depend on CO2 delivery to the lungs, which depends on cardiac output from compressions. Higher ETCO2 reflects better compressions; lower ETCO2 suggests inadequate compressions.","category":"Capnography"},{"id":"c03_fc07","question":"What is the maximum recommended duration for a single intubation attempt during cardiac arrest?","answer":"10 seconds — each attempt must be limited to minimize compression interruption.","category":"Intubation"},{"id":"c03_fc08","question":"Which laryngoscopy technique is preferred during cardiac arrest, direct or video?","answer":"Video laryngoscopy is preferred because it may reduce first-pass failure and the duration of compression pauses.","category":"Intubation"},{"id":"c03_fc09","question":"Why is supraglottic airway placement often preferred over ET intubation during cardiac arrest?","answer":"SGAs are faster to insert (typically under 15 seconds), require less skill, and cause fewer compression interruptions, which is critical during CPR.","category":"Supraglottic Airways"},{"id":"c03_fc10","question":"What should you do if an SGA or ET tube fails on the first attempt during cardiac arrest?","answer":"Immediately return to BVM ventilation with high-quality CPR, reassess, and reattempt only when ready — do not make repeated attempts without returning to effective BVM ventilation.","category":"Airway Management"},{"id":"c03_fc11","question":"What does the waveform shape on capnography look like for a correctly placed ET tube?","answer":"A characteristic rectangular waveform with an expiratory plateau, consistent ETCO2 value on each breath, and an inspiratory baseline near zero.","category":"Capnography"},{"id":"c03_fc12","question":"What are the three primary advanced airway options during cardiac arrest?","answer":"Bag-valve-mask (BVM) ventilation with oropharyngeal adjunct, supraglottic airways (i-gel, King LT), and endotracheal intubation.","category":"Airway Management"},{"id":"c03_fc13","question":"Why should over-ventilation be avoided after advanced airway placement during CPR?","answer":"Excessive ventilation rate or volume increases intrathoracic pressure, which reduces venous return, coronary perfusion pressure, and can cause gastric insufflation.","category":"Ventilation"},{"id":"c03_fc14","question":"What role does capnography play in detecting tube displacement after initial confirmation?","answer":"Continuous waveform capnography provides ongoing monitoring — sudden loss of the waveform with persistent respiratory effort suggests tube displacement, obstruction, or patient arrest.","category":"Capnography"},{"id":"c03_fc15","question":"During BVM ventilation in an arrest, what is the recommended ventilation rate before an advanced airway is placed?","answer":"One breath every 6 seconds (10 breaths per minute) during BLS CPR, delivered over 1 second each, with visible chest rise — without interrupting compressions.","category":"Ventilation"},{"id":"c03_fc16","question":"How does waveform capnography help detect ROSC before a manual pulse check?","answer":"A sudden, sustained ETCO2 rise to ≥40 mmHg reflects restored cardiac output, allowing early ROSC detection and transition to post-arrest care without waiting for a pulse check.","category":"Capnography"}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","cards":[{"id":"c04_fc01","question":"What are the two shockable cardiac arrest rhythms in ACLS?","answer":"Ventricular fibrillation (VF) and pulseless ventricular tachycardia (pVT) — both require immediate defibrillation.","category":"Shockable Rhythms"},{"id":"c04_fc02","question":"What is the 2025 AHA guideline regarding 'fine' vs 'coarse' asystole?","answer":"The 2025 guidelines no longer distinguish between fine and coarse asystole — the distinction has no proven prognostic or therapeutic significance, and all asystole is treated identically.","category":"Asystole"},{"id":"c04_fc03","question":"How is pulseless electrical activity (PEA) defined?","answer":"Any organized electrical rhythm on the monitor in the absence of a palpable pulse. The ECG morphology can range from normal sinus rhythm to wide-complex organized rhythms — the key is no effective cardiac output.","category":"PEA"},{"id":"c04_fc04","question":"What are the two non-shockable cardiac arrest rhythms?","answer":"Asystole and pulseless electrical activity (PEA) — both are treated with high-quality CPR, epinephrine, and identification/treatment of reversible causes.","category":"Non-Shockable Rhythms"},{"id":"c04_fc05","question":"How do you differentiate organized VT with a pulse from SVT with aberrancy?","answer":"Favor VT if the patient has structural heart disease, prior MI, hemodynamic instability, AV dissociation, fusion/capture beats, or concordant precordial QRS concordance. When uncertain, treat as VT.","category":"VT vs SVT"},{"id":"c04_fc06","question":"What should you do if you suspect artifact is being misread as VF on the monitor?","answer":"Briefly pause compressions for 5–10 seconds while observing the rhythm — true VF persists without compressions while artifact disappears. If uncertain and the patient is in arrest, treat as VF.","category":"Artifact"},{"id":"c04_fc07","question":"When should a 12-lead ECG be obtained during or after cardiac arrest?","answer":"A rhythm strip is obtained at every rhythm check during arrest. A full 12-lead ECG should be obtained promptly after ROSC to identify STEMI or other acute pathology, and can be obtained during prolonged resuscitation to identify reversible causes.","category":"12-Lead ECG"},{"id":"c04_fc08","question":"Before diagnosing asystole, what must be confirmed?","answer":"Ensure leads are properly connected, gain/sensitivity is adequate, the rhythm is present in at least two leads, and it is not fine VF being under-displayed.","category":"Asystole"},{"id":"c04_fc09","question":"Why is asystole a non-shockable rhythm?","answer":"Asystole represents complete absence of ventricular electrical activity. Defibrillation requires disorganized or abnormal electrical activity to reset — there is nothing to defibrillate in asystole.","category":"Asystole"},{"id":"c04_fc10","question":"Name three reversible causes of PEA.","answer":"Hypovolemia, tension pneumothorax, cardiac tamponade, massive pulmonary embolism, severe hypoxia, acidosis, drug overdose, hyperkalemia, hypothermia.","category":"PEA"},{"id":"c04_fc11","question":"What is the treatment for pulseless VT?","answer":"Identical to VF: immediate defibrillation (biphasic 120–200J), followed by high-quality CPR, epinephrine, and antiarrhythmics for refractory cases.","category":"Shockable Rhythms"},{"id":"c04_fc12","question":"What does the ECG of VF typically look like?","answer":"Chaotic, disorganized electrical activity with no identifiable QRS complexes. The amplitude varies from coarse (>0.2 mV) to fine (<0.2 mV), but this distinction has no therapeutic significance.","category":"Shockable Rhythms"},{"id":"c04_fc13","question":"Why must you always check a pulse before concluding ROSC from an organized rhythm on the monitor?","answer":"PEA presents as an organized rhythm without a pulse — the monitor can show what appears to be a perfusing rhythm (even normal sinus rhythm) while the patient has no cardiac output.","category":"PEA"},{"id":"c04_fc14","question":"What is the management approach when wide-complex tachycardia of uncertain origin is hemodynamically unstable?","answer":"Immediate synchronized cardioversion at 100J (monomorphic VT energy), regardless of whether it is VT or SVT with aberrancy — stability takes priority over rhythm diagnosis.","category":"VT vs SVT"},{"id":"c04_fc15","question":"Why is artifact-dropping-into-VF a clinical concern during resuscitation?","answer":"Motion artifact from compressions, transport, or shivering can mimic VF on the monitor, potentially leading to unnecessary defibrillation or incorrect rhythm identification.","category":"Artifact"},{"id":"c04_fc16","question":"What two heart rhythms require defibrillation during ACLS?","answer":"Ventricular fibrillation (VF) and pulseless ventricular tachycardia (pVT) — these are the only two shockable cardiac arrest rhythms.","category":"Shockable Rhythms"}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","cards":[{"id":"c05_fc01","question":"What is the recommended biphasic first-shock energy for adult VF/pVT?","answer":"120–200J biphasic (use the manufacturer's recommended energy for the specific waveform; if unknown, default to 200J).","category":"Defibrillation"},{"id":"c05_fc02","question":"What is the recommended monophasic first-shock energy for adult VF/pVT?","answer":"360J — monophasic defibrillators require higher energy than biphasic to achieve successful defibrillation.","category":"Defibrillation"},{"id":"c05_fc03","question":"What is the recommended initial synchronized cardioversion energy for atrial fibrillation or atrial flutter?","answer":"≥200J biphasic — the 2025 guidelines recommend higher initial energies to improve first-shock cardioversion success.","category":"Cardioversion"},{"id":"c05_fc04","question":"What energy is used for synchronized cardioversion of narrow-regular SVT?","answer":"100J biphasic — this is often effective on the first shock for SVT.","category":"Cardioversion"},{"id":"c05_fc05","question":"What energy is used for synchronized cardioversion of monomorphic VT with a pulse?","answer":"100J biphasic for the first shock; escalate energy if the first shock is unsuccessful.","category":"Cardioversion"},{"id":"c05_fc06","question":"Why is polymorphic VT treated with unsynchronized defibrillation rather than synchronized cardioversion?","answer":"Polymorphic VT has variable, irregular QRS morphology, making reliable R-wave synchronization impossible. Attempting synchronized cardioversion risks delivering a shock during the T wave (R-on-T), which could induce VF.","category":"Polymorphic VT"},{"id":"c05_fc07","question":"What is the starting current for transcutaneous pacing in adults?","answer":"80 mA — increase by 10 mA every 2–3 minutes until electrical capture is achieved, with a maximum output of 200 mA.","category":"Pacing"},{"id":"c05_fc08","question":"What is the difference between electrical capture and mechanical capture during transcutaneous pacing?","answer":"Electrical capture is visible on the monitor (wide QRS complexes following each pacer spike). Mechanical capture means the paced complexes produce effective cardiac output with a palpable pulse — always verify mechanical capture.","category":"Pacing"},{"id":"c05_fc09","question":"What is overdrive pacing and when is it used?","answer":"Overdrive pacing (anti-tachycardia pacing/ATP) paces the heart at 10–20% above the tachycardia rate to terminate re-entrant tachyarrhythmias. Used for monomorphic VT with a pulse, certain SVTs, and Torsades de Pointes.","category":"Overdrive Pacing"},{"id":"c05_fc10","question":"What is the maximum transcutaneous pacing output for adults?","answer":"200 mA — if electrical capture is not achieved at 200 mA, TCP has failed and escalation (transvenous pacing, cardiology consultation) is needed.","category":"Pacing"},{"id":"c05_fc11","question":"How does a biphasic waveform differ from a monophasic waveform?","answer":"Biphasic delivers current in two phases (positive then negative), achieving defibrillation at lower energies (120–200J). Monophasic delivers current in a single direction, requiring higher energy (360J).","category":"Defibrillation"},{"id":"c05_fc12","question":"What sedation should be provided before elective synchronized cardioversion?","answer":"A conscious patient should receive sedation and analgesia (e.g., midazolam, etomidate, propofol, or ketamine per protocol) before synchronized cardioversion, as the procedure is painful.","category":"Cardioversion"},{"id":"c05_fc13","question":"When should you escalate biphasic defibrillation energy during VF/pVT?","answer":"If the first biphasic shock at 120–200J is unsuccessful, subsequent shocks should use the maximum available biphasic energy.","category":"Defibrillation"},{"id":"c05_fc14","question":"What is the primary indication for transcutaneous pacing in ACLS?","answer":"Hemodynamically significant bradycardia (symptomatic, hypotensive) that is unresponsive to atropine, as a bridge to transvenous or permanent pacing.","category":"Pacing"},{"id":"c05_fc15","question":"How is Torsades de Pointes managed with pacing?","answer":"Overdrive pacing at 90–110/min suppresses the premature ventricular complexes that trigger Torsades and can be both acutely therapeutic and preventive.","category":"Overdrive Pacing"},{"id":"c05_fc16","question":"What should you always verify after achieving electrical capture with transcutaneous pacing?","answer":"Mechanical capture — palpate for a pulse with each paced complex. Electrical capture without mechanical capture means the paced complexes are not producing effective cardiac output.","category":"Pacing"}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","cards":[{"id":"c06_fc01","question":"What is the most critical intervention for a patient in VF or pVT?","answer":"Immediate defibrillation. Survival from a shockable rhythm declines with every minute defibrillation is delayed.","category":"Defibrillation"},{"id":"c06_fc02","question":"What biphasic defibrillation energy should be used for the first shock in VF/pVT?","answer":"120–200 J (manufacturer-specific or escalating). If the exact biphasic waveform energy is unknown, use the maximum energy available.","category":"Defibrillation"},{"id":"c06_fc03","question":"What defibrillation energy is used for monophasic waveforms?","answer":"360 J for all monophasic shocks.","category":"Defibrillation"},{"id":"c06_fc04","question":"What should you do immediately after delivering a defibrillation shock?","answer":"Resume chest compressions immediately — do NOT pause for a pulse or rhythm check. Continue CPR for approximately 2 minutes.","category":"CPR Quality"},{"id":"c06_fc05","question":"What is the target chest compression fraction (CCF) during VF/pVT arrest?","answer":"≥60%, ideally ≥80%. High CCF is independently associated with improved survival.","category":"CPR Quality"},{"id":"c06_fc06","question":"What are the key CPR quality targets during VF/pVT arrest?","answer":"Rate 100–120/min, depth 2–2.4 in (5–6 cm), allow full chest recoil, minimize interruptions, switch compressors approximately every 2 minutes.","category":"CPR Quality"},{"id":"c06_fc07","question":"When should epinephrine be given during a VF/pVT arrest?","answer":"Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO is given as soon as reasonably available, typically after the second shock, then repeated every 3–5 minutes.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c06_fc08","question":"What concentration of epinephrine is used in cardiac arrest?","answer":"1:10,000 (0.1 mg/mL). Give 1 mg IV/IO every 3–5 minutes.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c06_fc09","question":"What is the first-dose amiodarone for refractory VF/pVT?","answer":"300 mg IV/IO as a bolus. If VF/pVT persists, a second dose of 150 mg IV/IO may be given.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c06_fc10","question":"What is the alternative antiarrhythmic to amiodarone for refractory VF/pVT?","answer":"Lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO as the first dose, followed by 0.5–0.75 mg/kg IV/IO for subsequent doses.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c06_fc11","question":"Why should you not alternate between amiodarone and lidocaine within the same arrest?","answer":"Use one agent consistently rather than alternating, to maintain predictable drug levels and avoid cumulative toxicity without clear benefit.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c06_fc12","question":"What is the duration of each CPR cycle between rhythm checks in VF/pVT arrest?","answer":"Approximately 2 minutes of continuous compressions, then a brief pause for rhythm check (and pulse check only if an organized rhythm appears).","category":"ACLS Protocol"},{"id":"c06_fc13","question":"When should a pulse check be performed during a VF/pVT resuscitation?","answer":"Only after a rhythm check reveals an organized (non-VF/pVT) rhythm. Do not check a pulse after delivering a shock or during ongoing VF/pVT.","category":"ACLS Protocol"},{"id":"c06_fc14","question":"How should pre-shock and post-shock pauses in compressions be managed?","answer":"Minimize both. The pre-shock pause should be as brief as possible (rescuer hands on chest until last moment), and compressions should resume immediately after the shock without hesitation.","category":"CPR Quality"},{"id":"c06_fc15","question":"At what point should refractory-arrest strategies be considered in VF/pVT?","answer":"After approximately 3 or more shocks with persistent VF/pVT despite standard therapy (shocks, epinephrine, and an antiarrhythmic), consider vector-change or dual sequential external defibrillation (DSED), and evaluate ECPR candidacy.","category":"Refractory Arrest"},{"id":"c06_fc16","question":"What role does waveform capnography play during VF/pVT resuscitation?","answer":"Once an advanced airway is placed, waveform capnography monitors CPR quality (ETCO₂ correlates with cardiac output during CPR) and can detect ROSC (sudden sustained rise in ETCO₂).","category":"Monitoring"},{"id":"c06_fc17","question":"What are vector-change and dual sequential external defibrillation (DSED)?","answer":"Vector-change defibrillation alters pad placement to change the electrical vector through the myocardium. DSED uses two defibrillators with sequential shocks. Both are Class 2b options (may be considered) for refractory VF/pVT.","category":"Refractory Arrest"}]},"c07":{"chapter":"c07","cards":[{"id":"c07_fc01","question":"Why is defibrillation NOT indicated for asystole or PEA?","answer":"Asystole and PEA are nonshockable rhythms. There is no disorganized electrical activity to defibrillate (asystole) or the rhythm is already organized but not generating a pulse (PEA). Defibrillation wastes time and does not treat the underlying cause.","category":"Fundamentals"},{"id":"c07_fc02","question":"What is the most important initial intervention for asystole or PEA?","answer":"High-quality chest compressions and ventilations, combined with early identification and treatment of reversible causes.","category":"ACLS Protocol"},{"id":"c07_fc03","question":"When should epinephrine be given for a nonshockable rhythm (asystole/PEA)?","answer":"As soon as IV/IO access is established, ideally within 3–5 minutes of arrest onset. Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000) is repeated every 3–5 minutes.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c07_fc04","question":"What is the epinephrine dose and concentration for cardiac arrest?","answer":"1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000 concentration, i.e., 0.1 mg/mL) every 3–5 minutes.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c07_fc05","question":"List the H's of reversible causes of cardiac arrest.","answer":"Hypovolemia, Hypoxia, Hydrogen ion (acidosis), Hypo-/Hyperkalemia, Hypothermia.","category":"Reversible Causes"},{"id":"c07_fc06","question":"List the T's of reversible causes of cardiac arrest.","answer":"Tension pneumothorax, Tamponade (cardiac), Toxins, Thrombosis (pulmonary — massive PE), Thrombosis (coronary — acute MI).","category":"Reversible Causes"},{"id":"c07_fc07","question":"Why is early epinephrine particularly important in nonshockable rhythms?","answer":"Evidence suggests earlier epinephrine in nonshockable rhythms (asystole/PEA) is associated with improved survival. The 2025 guidelines recommend giving it as soon as feasible, ideally within 3–5 minutes.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c07_fc08","question":"How is true asystole confirmed?","answer":"On at least 2 ECG leads. Waveform capnography helps: absent or very low ETCO₂ (<10 mmHg) during CPR on an advanced airway is consistent with no cardiac output (asystole or fine VF).","category":"Monitoring"},{"id":"c07_fc09","question":"What is the difference between asystole and PEA?","answer":"Asystole is the complete absence of ventricular electrical activity (flatline). PEA is any organized electrical rhythm (normal or abnormal morphology) that fails to generate a palpable pulse.","category":"Fundamentals"},{"id":"c07_fc10","question":"How long should CPR be performed between rhythm checks in asystole/PEA?","answer":"Approximately 2 minutes of continuous high-quality compressions, followed by a brief rhythm check.","category":"ACLS Protocol"},{"id":"c07_fc11","question":"If a patient in asystole transitions to VF during resuscitation, what should the team do?","answer":"Switch to the VF/pVT algorithm — immediately defibrillate. The management pathway changes based on the rhythm identified at each check.","category":"ACLS Protocol"},{"id":"c07_fc12","question":"Why is a two-lead ECG confirmation important in suspected asystole?","answer":"A single lead may show an artifact resembling asystole (e.g., lead disconnection). Confirming on at least two leads and checking capnography prevents misidentifying a shockable rhythm or pseudo-asystole artifact.","category":"Monitoring"},{"id":"c07_fc13","question":"What does ETCO₂ <10 mmHg during CPR with an advanced airway suggest?","answer":"Very low or absent cardiac output, consistent with asystole, fine VF, or extremely poor CPR quality. This helps confirm true asystole and assess CPR effectiveness.","category":"Monitoring"},{"id":"c07_fc14","question":"How do PEA subtypes differ clinically?","answer":"Narrow-complex PEA (faster rate, normal QRS) may suggest hypovolemia, pneumothorax, or tamponade and may respond quickly to treatment. Wide-complex/slow PEA may indicate severe metabolic derangement or extensive myocardial ischemia. Both are managed with the same algorithm.","category":"PEA Subtypes"},{"id":"c07_fc15","question":"When may mechanical CPR devices be considered?","answer":"Only in specific circumstances where high-quality manual compressions are impractical or unsafe — prolonged transport, limited personnel, during ECPR cannulation, or in the catheterization lab. Routine use is not recommended.","category":"Mechanical CPR"},{"id":"c07_fc16","question":"What rhythm should you treat for if asystole is misidentified?","answer":"Fine ventricular fibrillation can mimic asystole. If VF is present, it is a shockable rhythm and should be treated with defibrillation — the opposite of the asystole/PEA pathway. Always confirm with two leads and capnography.","category":"Fundamentals"}]},"c08":{"chapter":"c08","cards":[{"id":"c08_fc01","question":"What is the correct epinephrine dose and concentration for cardiac arrest?","answer":"1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000 concentration, 0.1 mg/mL) every 3–5 minutes.","category":"Epinephrine"},{"id":"c08_fc02","question":"Why is epinephrine 1:1,000 never used in cardiac arrest?","answer":"1:1,000 is 10 times more concentrated than the correct 1:10,000 dose. Using it would deliver a 10-fold overdose that could cause severe hypertension and myocardial injury.","category":"Epinephrine"},{"id":"c08_fc03","question":"When is epinephrine first given for VF/pVT versus asystole/PEA?","answer":"For VF/pVT: after the second shock, then every 3–5 min. For asystole/PEA: as soon as feasible, ideally within 3–5 minutes of arrest onset, then every 3–5 min.","category":"Epinephrine"},{"id":"c08_fc04","question":"What is the mechanism of action of epinephrine during cardiac arrest?","answer":"Alpha-adrenergic vasoconstriction increases aortic diastolic pressure and coronary perfusion pressure during CPR. Beta-adrenergic effects are less beneficial during arrest and may increase myocardial oxygen demand.","category":"Epinephrine"},{"id":"c08_fc05","question":"What is the first dose of amiodarone for refractory VF/pVT?","answer":"300 mg IV/IO as a rapid bolus, followed by 150 mg IV/IO if VF/pVT persists.","category":"Amiodarone"},{"id":"c08_fc06","question":"What is the second dose of amiodarone for refractory VF/pVT?","answer":"150 mg IV/IO.","category":"Amiodarone"},{"id":"c08_fc07","question":"Why must standard amiodarone be diluted in dextrose (D5W) and not normal saline?","answer":"Standard amiodarone is incompatible with normal saline and precipitates. It must be diluted in D5W. The solvent in the formulation (polysorbate 80) can cause hypotension during infusion, which is a drug property and not caused by dextrose.","category":"Amiodarone"},{"id":"c08_fc08","question":"What is the first dose of lidocaine as an alternative to amiodarone for VF/pVT?","answer":"1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO, followed by 0.5–0.75 mg/kg for subsequent doses.","category":"Lidocaine"},{"id":"c08_fc09","question":"When is lidocaine preferred over amiodarone for VF/pVT?","answer":"Lidocaine is an alternative when amiodarone is unavailable, or when the arrest is clearly due to acute ischemia/MI.","category":"Lidocaine"},{"id":"c08_fc10","question":"Why should you not alternate between amiodarone and lidocaine within the same arrest?","answer":"Using one agent consistently maintains predictable drug levels and avoids cumulative toxicity without clear benefit from alternating.","category":"Antiarrhythmics"},{"id":"c08_fc11","question":"When is sodium bicarbonate indicated during cardiac arrest?","answer":"Only for specific indications: known/suspected hyperkalemia, tricyclic antidepressant (TCA) overdose, and known bicarbonate-responsive acidosis. NOT a routine arrest drug.","category":"Sodium Bicarbonate"},{"id":"c08_fc12","question":"What is the sodium bicarbonate dose for cardiac arrest?","answer":"1 mEq/kg IV.","category":"Sodium Bicarbonate"},{"id":"c08_fc13","question":"When is magnesium sulfate indicated during cardiac arrest?","answer":"For torsades de pointes (polymorphic VT with prolonged QT): 1–2 g IV over 5–20 minutes. Also for suspected hypomagnesemia contributing to arrhythmias. NOT for ordinary VF or pVT.","category":"Magnesium"},{"id":"c08_fc14","question":"What is the vasopressin dose in cardiac arrest, and is it preferred over epinephrine?","answer":"20 IU IV/IO (single dose). Vasopressin is NOT preferred — epinephrine alone remains the recommended vasopressor. Vasopressin offers no demonstrated survival advantage.","category":"Vasopressin"},{"id":"c08_fc15","question":"Is adenosine ever used in pulseless arrest?","answer":"NO. Adenosine is used only for regular narrow-complex SVT with a pulse. It has zero role in pulseless arrest (asystole, PEA, VF, or pVT).","category":"Adenosine"},{"id":"c08_fc16","question":"Why is IO access acceptable during cardiac arrest?","answer":"Drugs delivered via IO reach the central circulation with comparable speed and bioavailability to IV access. IO is faster to establish when IV access is not quickly available.","category":"Drug Delivery"},{"id":"c08_fc17","question":"What is the correct saline flush protocol after drug administration during CPR?","answer":"After each drug bolus, administer 10–20 mL normal saline flush, followed by an IV/IO fluid push to ensure the drug reaches the central circulation. Position the extremity if using peripheral IV.","category":"Drug Delivery"},{"id":"c08_fc18","question":"What Class antiarrhythmic agents are amiodarone and lidocaine respectively?","answer":"Amiodarone: combined Class I (Na⁺ channel), Class III (K⁺ channel/repolarization), and Class IV (Ca²⁺ channel) properties. Lidocaine: Class Ib (fast Na⁺ channel blocker, shortens action potential duration in ventricular tissue).","category":"Antiarrhythmics"}]},"c09":{"chapter":"c09","cards":[{"id":"c09_fc01","question":"List the five H's in the H's & T's mnemonic.","answer":"Hypovolemia, Hypoxia, Hydrogen ion (acidosis), Hypo-/Hyperkalemia, and Hypothermia.","category":"H's & T's"},{"id":"c09_fc02","question":"List the five T's in the H's & T's mnemonic.","answer":"Tension pneumothorax, Tamponade (cardiac), Toxins, Thrombosis (pulmonary), and Thrombosis (coronary).","category":"H's & T's"},{"id":"c09_fc03","question":"What is the bedside finding most suggestive of tension pneumothorax during arrest?","answer":"Absent breath sounds on one side, tracheal deviation, jugular venous distention, and hyperresonance to percussion — treat with immediate needle decompression.","category":"H's & T's"},{"id":"c09_fc04","question":"How is hyperkalemic cardiac arrest initially treated?","answer":"Calcium chloride 1 g IV (or calcium gluconate), sodium bicarbonate, insulin with glucose (10 units regular insulin + 50 mL D50), and inhaled albuterol.","category":"H's & T's"},{"id":"c09_fc05","question":"At what core temperature should resuscitation NOT be declared futile in a hypothermic arrest?","answer":"Do not declare futility until core temperature is at least 32°C (89.6°F) — hypothermic patients may achieve neurologically intact survival after prolonged resuscitation.","category":"H's & T's"},{"id":"c09_fc06","question":"What is the first-dose amiodarone bolus for refractory VF/pVT after ≥3 shocks?","answer":"Amiodarone 300 mg IV/IO as a single bolus, may repeat once at 150 mg.","category":"Refractory Arrest"},{"id":"c09_fc07","question":"What is the lidocaine dose for refractory VF/pVT?","answer":"Lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO as a single bolus, acceptable alternative to amiodarone.","category":"Refractory Arrest"},{"id":"c09_fc08","question":"What is dual sequential external defibrillation (DSED)?","answer":"Using two defibrillators to deliver asynchronous shocks in rapid succession with pads placed in different positions to maximize current delivery through the myocardium.","category":"Refractory Arrest"},{"id":"c09_fc09","question":"What AHA recommendation class is DSED for refractory VF/pVT?","answer":"Class 2b (LOE B-R) — may be considered but is not established as routine first-line therapy.","category":"Refractory Arrest"},{"id":"c09_fc10","question":"What is vector-change defibrillation?","answer":"Altering defibrillator pad placement to change the electrical current path through the myocardium, attempted after standard pad positions fail to terminate refractory VF.","category":"Refractory Arrest"},{"id":"c09_fc11","question":"What ETCO₂ value trend is the best noninvasive indicator of CPR quality?","answer":"A sudden drop in ETCO₂ (below 10 mmHg during CPR) suggests inadequate compressions or a new reversible cause; trending is more useful than any single value.","category":"CPR Quality"},{"id":"c09_fc12","question":"How do you treat cardiac tamponade causing PEA arrest?","answer":"Emergent pericardiocentesis (needle aspiration of pericardial fluid) or, if available, thoracotomy with pericardiotomy.","category":"H's & T's"},{"id":"c09_fc13","question":"When should you consider thrombolysis during a cardiac arrest?","answer":"When massive pulmonary embolism is the suspected cause of arrest, and catheter-based embolectomy is not immediately available.","category":"H's & T's"},{"id":"c09_fc14","question":"What electrolyte abnormality is the most common metabolic cause of cardiac arrest?","answer":"Hyperkalemia — look for peaked T waves, widened QRS on ECG; treat aggressively.","category":"H's & T's"},{"id":"c09_fc15","question":"What does 'antiarrhythmic stacking' mean in refractory VF management?","answer":"Administering both amiodarone and lidocaine sequentially when VF is truly refractory, as an advanced, protocol-dependent strategy.","category":"Refractory Arrest"},{"id":"c09_fc16","question":"What should you reassess BEFORE each defibrillation attempt in refractory arrest?","answer":"CPR quality (rate, depth, recoil, fraction), ETCO₂ trend, compressor rotation, defibrillator pad position and contact, and the presence of reversible causes (H's & T's).","category":"CPR Quality"}]},"c10":{"chapter":"c10","cards":[{"id":"c10_fc01","question":"What defines 'symptomatic' bradycardia?","answer":"A slow heart rate accompanied by signs of cardiopulmonary compromise: hypotension, acutely altered mental status, shock, ischemic chest discomfort, or acute heart failure.","category":"Recognition"},{"id":"c10_fc02","question":"What is the atropine dose and interval for symptomatic bradycardia?","answer":"1 mg IV or IO, repeated every 3–5 minutes, to a maximum total dose of 3 mg.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c10_fc03","question":"In which block patterns is atropine unlikely to work?","answer":"Infranodal blocks such as Mobitz type II or third-degree (complete) AV block, especially with a wide QRS.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c10_fc04","question":"What should you do if atropine is ineffective or unlikely to work?","answer":"Move promptly to transcutaneous pacing and/or a dopamine or epinephrine infusion; consider expert consultation and transvenous pacing.","category":"Escalation"},{"id":"c10_fc05","question":"How do you confirm transcutaneous pacing is actually working?","answer":"Confirm electrical capture (paced spike followed by a wide QRS and T wave) AND mechanical capture — a palpable pulse matching the paced rate.","category":"Pacing"},{"id":"c10_fc06","question":"Why give analgesia/sedation during transcutaneous pacing?","answer":"Transcutaneous pacing causes significant skeletal muscle contraction and discomfort in a conscious patient.","category":"Pacing"},{"id":"c10_fc07","question":"What should you do for a bradycardic patient with NO signs of instability?","answer":"Monitor and observe while investigating the cause; do not treat the rate itself.","category":"Recognition"},{"id":"c10_fc08","question":"Name two infusion options for refractory symptomatic bradycardia.","answer":"Dopamine infusion or epinephrine infusion, titrated to heart rate and blood pressure response.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c10_fc09","question":"Name three reversible/underlying causes of bradycardia to screen for.","answer":"Any three of: hypoxia, beta-blocker or calcium-channel blocker or digoxin toxicity, hyperkalemia, hypothyroidism, inferior MI, increased intracranial pressure.","category":"Underlying Causes"},{"id":"c10_fc10","question":"Why does atropine work well for sinus node dysfunction but poorly for infranodal block?","answer":"Atropine blocks vagal tone at the SA and AV nodes; infranodal (below-the-AV-node) blocks are not vagally mediated, so atropine has little effect there.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c10_fc11","question":"What is the maximum total atropine dose in one bradycardia episode?","answer":"3 mg total (1 mg doses repeated every 3–5 minutes).","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c10_fc12","question":"A patient is bradycardic at 42/min but alert, normotensive, and asymptomatic. What is the priority?","answer":"Observe, monitor, and investigate the cause rather than immediately giving atropine or pacing.","category":"Recognition"},{"id":"c10_fc13","question":"What rate is commonly used as a starting transcutaneous pacing rate?","answer":"Commonly 60–80/min as a starting target, titrated to clinical response.","category":"Pacing"},{"id":"c10_fc14","question":"Should dopamine/epinephrine infusion wait until pacing pads fail?","answer":"No — infusions may be started instead of, or alongside, pacing, especially if pacing is not immediately available or tolerated; they are alternative second-line options, not strictly sequential.","category":"Escalation"},{"id":"c10_fc15","question":"What toxidrome-related drugs commonly cause bradycardia that should be considered as a reversible cause?","answer":"Beta-blockers, calcium-channel blockers, and digoxin.","category":"Underlying Causes"},{"id":"c10_fc16","question":"What signs indicate cardiopulmonary compromise from bradycardia?","answer":"Hypotension, acutely altered mental status, signs of shock, ongoing ischemic chest discomfort, and acute heart failure.","category":"Recognition"}]},"c11":{"chapter":"c11","cards":[{"id":"c11_fc01","question":"What defines unstable tachycardia?","answer":"Tachycardia (rate >100/min with a pulse) accompanied by signs of hemodynamic compromise: hypotension (SBP <90 mmHg), acutely altered mental status, chest pain, acute heart failure, or signs of shock.","category":"Recognition"},{"id":"c11_fc02","question":"What is the first-line treatment for unstable tachycardia?","answer":"Immediate synchronized cardioversion, regardless of the rhythm type. Sedate if conscious and time permits.","category":"Treatment"},{"id":"c11_fc03","question":"Why is polymorphic VT treated with unsynchronized defibrillation instead of synchronized cardioversion?","answer":"The irregular, continuously varying waveform of polymorphic VT makes reliable R-wave synchronization impossible, and attempting to synchronize delays defibrillation.","category":"Treatment"},{"id":"c11_fc04","question":"What is the adenosine dose protocol for stable SVT?","answer":"6 mg rapid IV push via a proximal IV port followed by a rapid 20 mL saline flush; if no response, 12 mg (may repeat once).","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c11_fc05","question":"Why must adenosine be given through a proximal (near-the-heart) IV port?","answer":"Adenosine has an extremely short half-life (~6 seconds); a proximal port delivers it to the heart before it is metabolized by red blood cells and endothelium.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c11_fc06","question":"When you see a wide-complex tachycardia and are unsure of the diagnosis, what is the safest assumption?","answer":"Assume it is ventricular tachycardia (VT) until proven otherwise — treating SVT as VT is far less harmful than treating VT as SVT.","category":"Diagnosis"},{"id":"c11_fc07","question":"What is the first-line drug for stable wide-complex tachycardia?","answer":"Amiodarone 150 mg IV over 10 minutes, may repeat once.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c11_fc08","question":"What is the alternative antiarrhythmic to amiodarone for stable wide-complex tachycardia?","answer":"Procainamide 20–50 mg/min IV (maximum cumulative dose 17 mg/kg), given slowly with blood pressure monitoring.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c11_fc09","question":"What energy level is used for synchronized cardioversion of atrial fibrillation?","answer":"≥200 J biphasic for the initial shock.","category":"Cardioversion"},{"id":"c11_fc10","question":"What energy level is used for synchronized cardioversion of regular monomorphic VT?","answer":"100 J biphasic for the initial shock.","category":"Cardioversion"},{"id":"c11_fc11","question":"What is the rate-control target for atrial fibrillation in stable patients?","answer":"Resting heart rate <110/min (lenient) or <80/min (strict), depending on clinical context and symptoms.","category":"Rate Control"},{"id":"c11_fc12","question":"Name two drug classes used for rate control in atrial fibrillation.","answer":"Beta-blockers (e.g., metoprolol) and calcium-channel blockers (e.g., diltiazem); amiodarone is also used.","category":"Rate Control"},{"id":"c11_fc13","question":"What is the specific treatment for torsades de pointes (polymorphic VT with prolonged QT)?","answer":"Unsynchronized defibrillation plus magnesium sulfate 1–2 g IV; correct hypokalemia and hypomagnesemia.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c11_fc14","question":"Why should AV-nodal blockers (verapamil, diltiazem, adenosine) be avoided in pre-excited atrial fibrillation?","answer":"They can increase conduction through the accessory pathway, potentially accelerating the ventricular rate and precipitating VF.","category":"Pharmacology"},{"id":"c11_fc15","question":"What is the key clinical difference between regular and irregular wide-complex tachycardia management?","answer":"Regular wide-complex: assume VT, treat with amiodarone or procainamide, cardiovert if unstable. Irregular wide-complex: consider polymorphic VT (defibrillate), pre-excited AF (avoid AV-nodal blockers), or AF with aberrancy.","category":"Diagnosis"},{"id":"c11_fc16","question":"What sedation options are appropriate before elective synchronized cardioversion?","answer":"Short-acting agents such as midazolam, etomidate, or propofol, depending on the clinical setting and patient status.","category":"Cardioversion"}]},"c12":{"chapter":"c12","cards":[{"id":"c12_fc01","question":"What is the 2025 first-medical-contact-to-device (FMC2D) goal for primary PCI in STEMI?","answer":"≤90 minutes from first medical contact to device activation in the coronary artery.","category":"STEMI"},{"id":"c12_fc02","question":"When is fibrinolysis indicated for STEMI?","answer":"When symptom onset is within 12 hours AND the anticipated door-to-balloon (PPCI) delay exceeds 120 minutes.","category":"Fibrinolysis"},{"id":"c12_fc03","question":"What are the two preferred P2Y12 inhibitors for ACS according to the 2025 ACC/AHA guideline?","answer":"Ticagrelor and prasugrel are preferred over clopidogrel. Prasugrel is contraindicated with prior stroke/TIA or age ≥75.","category":"Medications"},{"id":"c12_fc04","question":"What are the three absolute contraindications to nitroglycerin in ACS?","answer":"Right ventricular infarction (inferior STEMI with hypotension), recent PDE5 inhibitor use (sildenafil <24 h, tadalafil <48 h), and systolic BP <90 mmHg.","category":"Medications"},{"id":"c12_fc05","question":"When should supplemental oxygen be given in ACS?","answer":"ONLY when SpO₂ <90% or the patient is in respiratory distress. Routine supplemental oxygen in normoxic ACS patients provides no benefit and may be harmful.","category":"Medications"},{"id":"c12_fc06","question":"Why is morphine use cautioned in ACS?","answer":"Morphine may delay P2Y12 inhibitor absorption (reducing antiplatelet efficacy), cause hypotension, and has no demonstrated mortality benefit in ACS. Reserve for refractory chest pain after nitroglycerin failure.","category":"Medications"},{"id":"c12_fc07","question":"How much does each 30-minute delay in primary PCI increase 1-year mortality?","answer":"Approximately 7.5% relative increase in 1-year mortality for each 30-minute delay in reperfusion.","category":"STEMI"},{"id":"c12_fc08","question":"What is the definition of STEMI on 12-lead ECG?","answer":"≥1 mm ST elevation in ≥2 contiguous limb leads OR ≥2 mm in ≥2 contiguous precordial leads (V2–V3: ≥2.5 mm in men ≥40, ≥1.5 mm in women).","category":"ECG"},{"id":"c12_fc09","question":"What lead should be obtained to assess for right ventricular infarction?","answer":"Right-sided lead V4R — ST elevation ≥1 mm in V4R indicates RV infarction (check in all inferior STEMIs).","category":"ECG"},{"id":"c12_fc10","question":"What leads confirm a posterior MI when ST depression is seen in V1–V3?","answer":"Posterior leads V7–V9 — ST elevation ≥0.5 mm in V7–V9 confirms posterior MI.","category":"ECG"},{"id":"c12_fc11","question":"What is the dose of unfractionated heparin for ACS?","answer":"60 U/kg IV bolus (max 4,000 U), then 12 U/kg/hr infusion.","category":"Medications"},{"id":"c12_fc12","question":"What should happen after successful fibrinolysis for STEMI?","answer":"Transfer to a PCI-capable center for routine early angiography within 3–24 hours. Failed fibrinolysis (no ST resolution at 60–90 min) warrants rescue PCI.","category":"Fibrinolysis"},{"id":"c12_fc13","question":"What P2Y12 loading dose should be given: ticagrelor or prasugrel?","answer":"Ticagrelor 180 mg PO or prasugrel 60 mg PO. Prasugrel is contraindicated in prior stroke/TIA and age ≥75.","category":"Medications"},{"id":"c12_fc14","question":"What does the modified Sgarbossa criterion add for diagnosing STEMI in the setting of LBBB?","answer":"Concordant ST elevation ≥1 mm, concordant ST depression ≥1 mm in V1–V3, or discordant ST elevation with ST/S ratio ≥0.25. Any of these in the context of ischemia should be treated as STEMI-equivalent.","category":"ECG"},{"id":"c12_fc15","question":"What are the TIMI/GRACE risk stratification tools used for in NSTEMI?","answer":"They guide the timing of invasive strategy: high-risk (early invasive within 24 h) vs lower-risk (delayed invasive or ischemia-guided strategy).","category":"NSTEMI"},{"id":"c12_fc16","question":"What should aspirin dose be for ACS and when should it be given?","answer":"162–325 mg chewed immediately upon recognition of ACS — this is the first drug given in all ACS presentations.","category":"Medications"}]},"c13":{"chapter":"c13","cards":[{"id":"c13_fc01","question":"What does the FAST mnemonic stand for in stroke screening?","answer":"Face (droop), Arms (drift), Speech (abnormal), Time (call EMS immediately).","category":"Screening"},{"id":"c13_fc02","question":"What are the three components of the Cincinnati Prehospital Stroke Scale?","answer":"Facial droop (ask to smile), arm drift (extend both arms with eyes closed), and speech abnormality (repeat a phrase).","category":"Screening"},{"id":"c13_fc03","question":"What is the dose and administration protocol for IV alteplase (tPA) in acute ischemic stroke?","answer":"0.9 mg/kg IV (max 90 mg): 10% as bolus over 1 minute, remaining 90% infused over 60 minutes.","category":"Thrombolysis"},{"id":"c13_fc04","question":"What is the time window for IV thrombolysis in acute ischemic stroke?","answer":"Within 4.5 hours of symptom onset.","category":"Thrombolysis"},{"id":"c13_fc05","question":"What blood pressure must be achieved BEFORE administering tPA?","answer":"Blood pressure must be <185/110 mmHg before tPA initiation. Use IV labetalol or nicardipine to achieve this.","category":"Blood Pressure"},{"id":"c13_fc06","question":"What blood pressure target must be maintained DURING and AFTER tPA infusion?","answer":"<180/105 mmHg during and for at least 24 hours after tPA, with approximately 15% reduction in BP in the first 24 hours.","category":"Blood Pressure"},{"id":"c13_fc07","question":"What is the permissive hypertension threshold for non-tPA stroke patients?","answer":"Up to 220/120 mmHg in the first 24 hours if no intracranial hemorrhage, cardiac ischemia, or aortic dissection.","category":"Blood Pressure"},{"id":"c13_fc08","question":"What imaging MUST be done before administering tPA for stroke?","answer":"Non-contrast CT of the head — mandatory to exclude intracranial hemorrhage before any tPA administration.","category":"Thrombolysis"},{"id":"c13_fc09","question":"What is the indication for mechanical thrombectomy?","answer":"Acute ischemic stroke caused by large-vessel occlusion (ICA or proximal MCA/M1) within 6 hours, or up to 24 hours with advanced imaging showing salvageable penumbra.","category":"Thrombectomy"},{"id":"c13_fc10","question":"What is the most critical stroke mimic that must be ruled out first?","answer":"Hypoglycemia — always check blood glucose immediately in any suspected stroke presentation. It is the most common and most treatable mimic.","category":"Stroke Mimics"},{"id":"c13_fc11","question":"How does Bell's palsy differ from central facial droop in stroke?","answer":"Bell's palsy (peripheral) spares the forehead (both upper and lower face affected); central facial droop (stroke) affects only the contralateral lower face (forehead is spared because it receives bilateral cortical input).","category":"Stroke Mimics"},{"id":"c13_fc12","question":"What should be done with fever in an acute stroke patient?","answer":"Treat aggressively with antipyretics and cooling measures — temperature >38°C worsens ischemic brain injury and must be controlled immediately.","category":"Stabilization"},{"id":"c13_fc13","question":"What glucose range should be maintained in acute stroke?","answer":"70–180 mg/dL — both hypoglycemia (<60 mg/dL) and severe hyperglycemia (>180 mg/dL) are associated with worse outcomes.","category":"Stabilization"},{"id":"c13_fc14","question":"Should tPA be withheld while waiting for thrombectomy evaluation?","answer":"No — tPA should be given immediately if the patient meets criteria. Thrombectomy and tPA are not mutually exclusive; patients eligible for both receive tPA first and proceed to thrombectomy without delay.","category":"Thrombectomy"},{"id":"c13_fc15","question":"What drugs lower blood pressure before tPA?","answer":"IV labetalol 10–20 mg over 1–2 minutes (repeat once), or nicardipine infusion starting at 5 mg/hr, titrated up by 2.5 mg/hr every 5–15 min (max 15 mg/hr).","category":"Blood Pressure"},{"id":"c13_fc16","question":"What does 'time is brain' mean in stroke care?","answer":"Approximately 1.9 million neurons are lost per minute during untreated large-vessel ischemic stroke — every minute of delay in reperfusion worsens outcome.","category":"Concepts"}]},"c14":{"chapter":"c14","cards":[{"id":"c14_fc01","question":"What are the components of the post-ROSC bundle?","answer":"Airway management with capnography (ETCO₂ 35–45), hemodynamic optimization (MAP ≥65), 12-lead ECG, temperature management (≤37.5°C), ongoing H's and T's evaluation, and deferred neuroprognostication (≥72 h).","category":"Post-ROSC"},{"id":"c14_fc02","question":"What is the recommended temperature management after cardiac arrest?","answer":"Maintain temperature ≤37.5°C at minimum. If targeted temperature management (TTM) is chosen, use 32–37.5°C for at least 36 hours. Treat any fever >37.5°C immediately.","category":"Temperature"},{"id":"c14_fc03","question":"What is the MAP target after ROSC?","answer":"MAP ≥65 mmHg (SBP >90 mmHg). Avoid both hypotension (MAP <60) and hypertension (MAP >100), as both worsen neurological outcomes.","category":"Hemodynamics"},{"id":"c14_fc04","question":"When must neuroprognostication be performed after cardiac arrest?","answer":"Deferred to ≥72 hours after ROSC (or after rewarming if TTM was used), once sedation, paralytics, and metabolic derangements have cleared.","category":"Neuroprognostication"},{"id":"c14_fc05","question":"What imaging should be obtained immediately after ROSC?","answer":"12-lead ECG (to identify STEMI — present in up to 25–50% of post-arrest patients) and non-contrast CT head (to exclude intracranial hemorrhage).","category":"Post-ROSC"},{"id":"c14_fc06","question":"What percentage of post-cardiac arrest patients may have STEMI on post-ROSC ECG?","answer":"Approximately 25–50% of cardiac arrest survivors have acute STEMI on post-ROSC 12-lead ECG and require emergent coronary angiography and PCI.","category":"Post-ROSC"},{"id":"c14_fc07","question":"What is the target ETCO₂ range during normothermic ventilation after ROSC?","answer":"35–45 mmHg. Avoid both hypoventilation (ETCO₂ >45) and hyperventilation (ETCO₂ <35), as both worsen cerebral perfusion.","category":"Airway"},{"id":"c14_fc08","question":"What are the indications for ECPR?","answer":"Selected refractory cardiac arrest (persistent VF/pVT despite standard ACLS), expected low-flow time <60 minutes, potentially reversible cause, suitable candidate (age, comorbidities, functional status).","category":"ECPR"},{"id":"c14_fc09","question":"What is the preferred cannulation site for ECPR?","answer":"Femoral venous drainage and femoral arterial return (VA-ECMO), placed percutaneously under ultrasound guidance. A distal perfusion catheter should be placed to prevent limb ischemia.","category":"ECPR"},{"id":"c14_fc10","question":"Why must neuroprognostication NOT be performed before 72 hours?","answer":"Sedation, paralytic agents, metabolic derangements, and hypothermia all confound the neurological examination, making early assessments unreliable. An early poor exam does not reliably predict poor outcome.","category":"Neuroprognostication"},{"id":"c14_fc11","question":"Name the multimodal tools used for neuroprognostication.","answer":"Clinical exam (pupillary/corneal reflexes, motor response), SSEPs (bilateral absence), continuous EEG, serum biomarkers (NSE >33 mcg/L, S-100B), and neuroimaging (CT/MRI).","category":"Neuroprognostication"},{"id":"c14_fc12","question":"What is the first-line vasopressor for hemodynamic support after ROSC?","answer":"Norepinephrine (starting 0.1–0.5 mcg/kg/min, titrated to MAP ≥65 mmHg). Dobutamine may be added for myocardial dysfunction with adequate preload.","category":"Hemodynamics"},{"id":"c14_fc13","question":"What is the recommended rewarming rate after TTM?","answer":"≤0.25°C per hour — slow and controlled rewarming to prevent rebound intracranial hypertension and hemodynamic instability.","category":"Temperature"},{"id":"c14_fc14","question":"What does ECPR serve as — a destination or a bridge?","answer":"A bridge — ECPR provides temporary circulatory and oxygenation support while the reversible cause of arrest is identified and treated. It is weaned as native cardiac function recovers.","category":"ECPR"},{"id":"c14_fc15","question":"What serum biomarker level suggests poor neurological prognosis after cardiac arrest?","answer":"Neuron-specific enolase (NSE) >33 mcg/L at 48–72 hours post-ROSC is associated with poor neurological outcome, but should be interpreted in the multimodal context.","category":"Neuroprognostication"},{"id":"c14_fc16","question":"What imaging finding on post-arrest CT suggests poor neurological prognosis?","answer":"Diffuse cerebral edema or loss of gray-white matter differentiation on CT, indicating severe hypoxic-ischemic brain injury.","category":"Neuroprognostication"},{"id":"c14_fc17","question":"What does the recovery link of the chain of survival include for cardiac arrest survivors?","answer":"Neurorehabilitation, psychological support for survivors and families, cardiac rehabilitation, assessment of ongoing arrhythmia/coronary disease management, and advance care planning.","category":"Recovery"}]}},"quizzes":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","questions":[{"id":"c01_q01","question":"How many links make up the 2025 AHA universal Chain of Survival?","options":["A. Four","B. Five","C. Six","D. Eight"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The 2025 guidelines consolidated adult/pediatric and IHCA/OHCA chains into one universal six-link chain, with a separate Neonatal Chain of Care.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q02","question":"Which link of the Chain of Survival does the ACLS provider primarily own?","options":["A. Link 1 — activation","B. Link 3 — defibrillation only","C. Link 4 — advanced resuscitation interventions","D. Link 6 — recovery"],"correct":2,"rationale":"ACLS providers primarily deliver Link 4: advanced airway management, IV/IO access, rhythm-specific therapy, medications, and treatment of reversible causes, while also protecting the earlier links.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q03","question":"A resident wants to intubate immediately upon arrival at a code, before establishing compressions and pads. What is the correct priority?","options":["A. Intubate first to secure the airway","B. Start/continue high-quality compressions and apply the defibrillator first; intubation is layered in without interrupting compressions","C. Intubation always takes priority in ACLS","D. Wait for a physician before doing anything"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Advanced interventions are additive to, not substitutes for, high-quality CPR and early defibrillation, which remain the strongest predictors of survival.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q04","question":"What is the primary systems-of-care emphasis for out-of-hospital cardiac arrest (OHCA)?","options":["A. Early-warning scores and rapid-response teams","B. Bystander recognition/CPR, dispatcher-assisted instructions, and public-access AEDs","C. Multimodal neuroprognostication","D. ECPR cannulation protocols"],"correct":1,"rationale":"OHCA systems depend heavily on bystanders and dispatch to bridge the gap before EMS/ACLS providers arrive.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q05","question":"What is the primary systems-of-care emphasis for in-hospital cardiac arrest (IHCA)?","options":["A. Public-access defibrillation programs","B. Surveillance and prevention using early-warning scores and rapid-response teams","C. Community CPR training","D. Regional trauma triage"],"correct":1,"rationale":"IHCA systems focus on catching deterioration early through monitoring and rapid-response systems so that many arrests are prevented before they occur.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q06","question":"A patient achieves ROSC after a refractory OHCA in a system with regionalized cardiac arrest centers. What should be considered?","options":["A. Transport to the nearest facility regardless of capability","B. Consider triage/transfer to a cardiac arrest center capable of PCI, temperature control, and ECPR","C. Discharge home once a pulse returns","D. Withhold further care since ROSC was achieved"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Analogous to trauma and stroke systems, regionalized cardiac arrest centers with 24/7 PCI, temperature management, and ECPR capability improve outcomes for appropriate patients.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q07","question":"Which of the following is an Utstein-style CQI metric?","options":["A. Patient's insurance status","B. Chest compression fraction","C. Hospital parking capacity","D. Ambulance color"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Chest compression fraction, time to first shock, time to epinephrine, ROSC rate, survival to discharge, and neurologic outcome are standard Utstein-style metrics used to measure and improve system performance.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q08","question":"Why is post-cardiac arrest care described as a continuation of resuscitation rather than a separate phase?","options":["A. Because it uses entirely different providers and skills","B. Because the same anticipatory, team-based approach and treatment of reversible causes carries forward after ROSC","C. Because it only involves paperwork","D. Because monitoring stops once a pulse returns"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The 2025 guidelines frame post-ROSC care as continued resuscitation — airway, hemodynamics, temperature control, and cause-directed therapy all extend the same mindset used during arrest.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q09","question":"What has replaced the previously separate adult/pediatric and IHCA/OHCA Chains of Survival?","options":["A. Four separate specialty chains","B. A single universal six-link chain plus a distinct Neonatal Chain of Care","C. No chain concept is used anymore","D. A three-link simplified chain"],"correct":1,"rationale":"2025 consolidated the multiple chains into one universal chain applicable across settings and ages, with newborns following a separate Neonatal Chain of Care.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q10","question":"A hospital wants to reduce in-hospital arrests. Which system tool most directly supports this goal?","options":["A. Public-access AED placement in the community","B. Early-warning scores paired with a rapid-response team","C. A regional ECPR referral network","D. Dispatcher-assisted CPR scripts"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Early-warning scores identify deteriorating inpatients so a rapid-response/medical emergency team can intervene before a full arrest occurs.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q11","question":"During a code, the team lead notices the code documenter has not recorded times of drug administration. What system consequence does this create?","options":["A. None — timing doesn't matter for CQI","B. It weakens the CQI/Utstein data (e.g., time-to-epinephrine) needed to evaluate and improve system performance","C. It only affects billing","D. It has no effect on patient care or system review"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Accurate timing data underpins CQI metrics like time-to-epinephrine and time-to-shock; without it, systems cannot measure or improve performance.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c01_q12","question":"Which best describes the relationship between BLS and ACLS?","options":["A. ACLS replaces the need for high-quality BLS","B. ACLS layers advanced interventions onto an uninterrupted BLS foundation of compressions and defibrillation","C. BLS and ACLS are unrelated skill sets","D. ACLS is only used after BLS has failed for 30 minutes"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ACLS providers must protect the BLS foundation (compressions, early defibrillation) while adding airway, IV/IO access, and drug therapy — advanced care is additive.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q13","question":"What does the recovery link (Link 6) of the Chain of Survival include?","options":["A. Only hospital discharge paperwork","B. Rehabilitation, psychological support, treatment planning, and family support","C. Repeating BLS training annually","D. Nothing beyond ROSC"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Recovery reframes survival as an ongoing process needing rehabilitation and psychosocial support for both the survivor and family, not just a return of pulse.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q14","question":"A busy resuscitation team performs a debrief immediately after a code using real-time data. What is the primary purpose of this debrief?","options":["A. To assign blame for errors","B. To identify system and team performance gaps and feed lessons back into training/protocols (CQI)","C. To satisfy a legal requirement only","D. To determine reimbursement"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Debriefing is a core continuous-quality-improvement activity, using data from the event to improve future team and system performance.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q15","question":"Which statement about advanced airway placement during cardiac arrest is TRUE?","options":["A. It should be attempted before starting compressions","B. It must be integrated without causing prolonged pauses in chest compressions","C. It always takes priority over defibrillation","D. It replaces the need for capnography"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Airway management is layered into ongoing compressions; a red flag is any advanced procedure causing a long pause in compressions.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q16","question":"Why are trauma and stroke systems of care referenced when discussing cardiac arrest centers?","options":["A. They share no relevant similarities","B. Cardiac arrest centers are modeled on the same regionalization principle — routing time-critical patients to specialized capability","C. Cardiac arrest centers replace trauma centers","D. Only rural systems use this model"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Like trauma and stroke systems, regionalized cardiac arrest centers concentrate specialized post-arrest capabilities (PCI, temperature control, neuroprognostication, ECPR) to improve outcomes.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","questions":[{"id":"c02_q01","question":"What is the target chest compression depth for an adult in ACLS?","options":["A. At least 1 in (2.5 cm)","B. At least 2 in (5 cm), not more than 2.4 in (6 cm)","C. Exactly 3 in (7.5 cm)","D. As deep as possible with no upper limit"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Adult compression depth should be at least 2 in (5 cm) but not exceed 2.4 in (6 cm) to maximize blood flow while avoiding injury.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q02","question":"What is chest compression fraction (CCF)?","options":["A. The percentage of compressions delivered at correct depth","B. The proportion of total resuscitation time spent actually compressing the chest","C. The number of compressors used per code","D. The ratio of compressions to breaths"],"correct":1,"rationale":"CCF measures how much of the total resuscitation time compressions are actually occurring; a higher CCF (≥60%, ideally >80%) correlates with better outcomes.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q03","question":"An advanced airway has just been successfully placed and confirmed during ongoing CPR. What ventilation strategy is now correct?","options":["A. Continue 30:2 cycling","B. Continuous compressions with 1 breath every 6 seconds","C. Stop compressions to give 2 breaths every cycle","D. Ventilate as fast as possible"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Once an advanced airway is placed, compressions become continuous and a single breath is given every 6 seconds (~10/min), independent of the compression cycle.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q04","question":"Why does over-ventilation harm a patient in cardiac arrest?","options":["A. It has no physiologic effect","B. It raises intrathoracic pressure, reduces venous return, and lowers cardiac output","C. It improves oxygenation with no downside","D. It only matters after ROSC"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Excessive ventilation rate or volume increases intrathoracic pressure, impeding venous return to the heart and reducing the cardiac output generated by compressions.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q05","question":"What is the recommended interval for switching chest compressors?","options":["A. Every 30 seconds","B. About every 2 minutes, or sooner if fatigued","C. Only at the end of the code","D. Every 10 minutes"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Compressor fatigue degrades quality even before the rescuer feels tired, so switching roughly every 2 minutes (often paired with rhythm checks) preserves compression quality.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q06","question":"A team leader says 'Someone give epinephrine.' What team dynamics principle is being violated?","options":["A. Knowing your limitations","B. Closed-loop communication and clear, directed orders","C. Mutual respect","D. Reevaluation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Orders should be directed to a specific named person and closed with a repeat-back and confirmation; vague, undirected orders risk being missed or duplicated.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q07","question":"What is the correct sequence of closed-loop communication?","options":["A. Order given to a named person → receiver repeats it back → receiver confirms completion","B. Order given generally to the room → no confirmation needed","C. Task performed first, then discussed","D. Only the leader speaks during the code"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Closed-loop communication requires a directed order, a verbal repeat-back, and confirmation once the task is complete.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q08","question":"A junior team member notices the code leader about to order a second dose of a drug already given. What should they do?","options":["A. Stay silent because the leader outranks them","B. Respectfully speak up immediately (constructive intervention)","C. Wait until after the code to mention it","D. Give the drug anyway without comment"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Constructive intervention means any team member should speak up promptly and respectfully when they notice a potential error, regardless of hierarchy.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q09","question":"What is the primary role of a dedicated CPR coach during a resuscitation?","options":["A. To administer all medications","B. To monitor and give real-time feedback on compression rate, depth, recoil, and pauses","C. To lead the code and make all treatment decisions","D. To document only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A CPR coach focuses exclusively on compression quality metrics, allowing the team leader to focus on rhythm interpretation and overall management.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q10","question":"What compression-to-ventilation ratio is used before an advanced airway is in place?","options":["A. 15:2","B. 30:2","C. 5:1","D. Continuous compressions with no breaths"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Without an advanced airway, adult CPR uses a 30:2 compression-to-breath ratio.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q11","question":"During a code, compression pauses for rhythm checks are consistently running 15–20 seconds. What should the team do?","options":["A. Accept it as normal","B. Identify the cause of the delay and shorten the pause to under 10 seconds","C. Stop checking rhythms altogether","D. Increase compression rate to compensate"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Pauses should be kept under 10 seconds; a team noticing longer pauses should identify and correct the cause (e.g., slow AED analysis, difficulty visualizing the rhythm) to protect CCF.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c02_q12","question":"Which best describes 'knowing your limitations' as a team dynamics element?","options":["A. Refusing any task outside your comfort zone without explanation","B. Proactively communicating when a task is beyond your training so someone else can take over","C. Attempting every task regardless of skill level","D. Only the team leader needs to know their limitations"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Team members should openly communicate when a task exceeds their training or ability so responsibility can shift to someone more capable, preserving patient safety.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q13","question":"What effect does chronic rescuer fatigue have on compression quality if compressors are not switched?","options":["A. No measurable effect","B. Compression depth and rate quality decline, often before the rescuer subjectively feels tired","C. Only compression rate is affected, never depth","D. Fatigue improves consistency"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Studies show compression quality (especially depth) degrades with fatigue, often before the rescuer notices — hence the routine ~2-minute switch.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c02_q14","question":"Which statement about full chest recoil is correct?","options":["A. Leaning on the chest between compressions improves blood flow","B. Full recoil between compressions allows the heart to refill and is required for effective CPR","C. Recoil is only relevant for pediatric patients","D. Recoil does not affect compression quality"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Full recoil between compressions permits venous return and cardiac filling; leaning on the chest reduces effective blood flow.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q15","question":"A resuscitation team never verbally confirms medication doses given. What is the primary risk?","options":["A. Improved efficiency","B. Missed doses or accidental duplicate dosing due to lost situational awareness","C. No risk if the leader remembers everything","D. Faster completion of the code"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Without closed-loop confirmation, the team can lose track of what has been given, risking missed or duplicated doses, especially in long or high-stress resuscitations.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q16","question":"What best describes the relationship between CCF and outcomes?","options":["A. CCF has no established relationship with survival","B. Higher CCF (≥60%, ideally >80%) is associated with better perfusion and outcomes","C. Lower CCF is preferred to allow more frequent pulse checks","D. CCF only matters after ROSC"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Chest compression fraction reflects how much of the resuscitation time compressions were actually delivered; higher CCF supports better perfusion and is linked with improved outcomes.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q17","question":"Why should ventilation rate be independent of the compression cycle once an advanced airway is placed?","options":["A. Because compressions must pause for each breath","B. Because compressions are continuous and breaths (1 every 6 seconds) are delivered asynchronously without pausing compressions","C. Because ventilation is no longer needed","D. Because breaths should match the compression rate exactly"],"correct":1,"rationale":"With an advanced airway, ventilations (1 every 6 seconds) are delivered independently while compressions continue uninterrupted.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q18","question":"A new nurse is unsure how to titrate a vasopressor infusion ordered mid-code. What is the correct action per team dynamics principles?","options":["A. Guess and proceed without saying anything","B. Clearly state the limitation to the team leader so someone qualified can take over or assist","C. Refuse to participate in the code at all","D. Delay the whole code until they figure it out alone"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Knowing your limitations means openly communicating a skills gap so the task can be reassigned or supported, keeping the resuscitation safe and efficient.","difficulty":"Medium"}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","questions":[{"id":"c03_q01","question":"What is the gold standard for confirming endotracheal tube placement during cardiac arrest?","options":["A. Auscultation of bilateral breath sounds","B. Observation of chest rise","C. Waveform capnography","D. Chest X-ray"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Waveform capnography is the gold standard for ET tube placement confirmation. Auscultation and chest rise are unreliable during cardiac arrest due to poor perfusion and background noise.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q02","question":"What is the target ETCO2 value during CPR that indicates adequate chest compression quality?","options":["A. ≥5 mmHg","B. ≥10 mmHg","C. ≥25 mmHg","D. ≥40 mmHg"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ETCO2 ≥10 mmHg is the AHA goal during CPR, reflecting adequate cardiac output from compressions. Values below 10 mmHg suggest the need to reassess compression quality.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q03","question":"During CPR, the ETCO2 suddenly rises from 8 mmHg to 45 mmHg and stays elevated. What is the most likely explanation?","options":["A. The ET tube has become esophageal","B. Compressions have improved","C. Return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC)","D. The capnography sensor is malfunctioning"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A sudden, sustained ETCO2 rise to ≥40 mmHg during CPR is a reliable indicator of ROSC, reflecting restored native cardiac output delivering more CO2 to the lungs.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q04","question":"What is the maximum duration recommended for a single intubation attempt during cardiac arrest?","options":["A. 5 seconds","B. 10 seconds","C. 20 seconds","D. 30 seconds"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Each intubation attempt during cardiac arrest should not exceed 10 seconds to minimize chest compression interruptions.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q05","question":"An ETCO2 of 6 mmHg is consistently measured during CPR despite correct compression technique by the team. What is the most appropriate next step?","options":["A. Stop compressions to troubleshoot the capnography waveform","B. Reassess compression rate, depth, recoil, and fraction; check for hypovolemia or tension pneumothorax","C. Remove the advanced airway and return to BVM","D. Administer more epinephrine"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Persistent ETCO2 below 10 mmHg despite apparently correct technique warrants a systematic reassessment of CPR quality (rate, depth, recoil, fraction) and reversible causes (hypovolemia, tension pneumothorax, massive PE).","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q06","question":"Which laryngoscopy technique is preferred for ET intubation during cardiac arrest?","options":["A. Direct laryngoscopy only","B. Video laryngoscopy","C. Fiber-optic intubation","D. Digital (tactile) intubation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Video laryngoscopy is preferred during cardiac arrest because it may reduce first-pass failure and compression pause duration compared with direct laryngoscopy.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q07","question":"After inserting a supraglottic airway during cardiac arrest, what must you do before continuing ventilation?","options":["A. Obtain a chest X-ray","B. Confirm placement with waveform capnography","C. Listen for breath sounds only","D. Wait for the patient to breathe spontaneously"],"correct":1,"rationale":"All advanced airways, including SGAs, must be confirmed with waveform capnography. The presence of a waveform indicates effective ventilation through the device.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q08","question":"What is a key advantage of supraglottic airways over ET intubation during cardiac arrest?","options":["A. They provide superior aspiration protection","B. They are faster to insert and cause fewer compression interruptions","C. They allow higher tidal volumes","D. They do not require capnography for confirmation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"SGAs can be inserted in under 15 seconds without laryngoscopy, causing fewer compression interruptions — a critical advantage during CPR. They do not provide absolute aspiration protection.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q09","question":"After ET intubation, the capnography waveform is absent. What is the correct action?","options":["A. Begin ventilating and recheck in 2 minutes","B. Assume esophageal placement; reposition or replace the tube and confirm with capnography","C. The waveform may take time to appear; continue ventilation","D. Confirm placement by auscultation alone"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An absent capnography waveform after intubation strongly suggests esophageal placement. The tube must be repositioned or replaced immediately, not ventilated through.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q10","question":"Why does ETCO2 correlate with CPR quality during cardiac arrest?","options":["A. ETCO2 reflects the patient's metabolic rate","B. ETCO2 reflects cardiac output from compressions, which drives CO2 delivery to the lungs","C. ETCO2 reflects the depth of the airway tube","D. ETCO2 is independent of blood flow during arrest"],"correct":1,"rationale":"During cardiac arrest, CO2 delivery to the lungs depends entirely on blood flow generated by chest compressions. Higher ETCO2 indicates better compressions; lower ETCO2 suggests inadequate flow.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q11","question":"The i-gel supraglottic airway differs from the King LT in which way?","options":["A. The i-gel requires cuff inflation; the King LT does not","B. The i-gel uses a non-inflatable gel cushion; the King LT uses inflatable cuffs","C. The King LT is single-lumen; the i-gel is dual-lumen","D. The King LT is placed first during cardiac arrest"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The i-gel features a non-inflatable gel-filled cushion that conforms to perilaryngeal anatomy. The King LT uses a dual-lumen design with proximal and distal inflatable cuffs.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q12","question":"What is the recommended ventilation rate after an advanced airway is placed during cardiac arrest?","options":["A. One breath every 2–3 seconds (20–30 breaths/min)","B. One breath every 6 seconds (10 breaths/min), delivered independently of compressions","C. Ventilations are synchronized with compressions at a 30:2 ratio","D. Continuous positive-pressure ventilation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"After an advanced airway is placed, ventilations are delivered at one breath every 6 seconds (10 breaths/min) independently of chest compressions, without interrupting compressions.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q13","question":"Which of the following would NOT be an appropriate action when ETCO2 is persistently below 10 mmHg during CPR?","options":["A. Reassess compression depth and rate","B. Check for complete chest recoil between compressions","C. Immediately remove the ET tube and switch to BVM","D. Evaluate for reversible causes such as tension pneumothorax or hypovolemia"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Persistent low ETCO2 should trigger reassessment of CPR quality and reversible causes, not immediate tube removal. The airway should remain secured while the underlying issue is addressed.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c03_q14","question":"Over-ventilation during CPR can cause all of the following EXCEPT:","options":["A. Increased intrathoracic pressure","B. Reduced venous return","C. Improved coronary perfusion pressure","D. Gastric insufflation"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Over-ventilation increases intrathoracic pressure, which reduces venous return and coronary perfusion pressure — the opposite of what is needed during CPR. It also promotes gastric insufflation.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c03_q15","question":"Why is capnography more reliable than auscultation for confirming tube position during cardiac arrest?","options":["A. Auscultation is never useful in any clinical scenario","B. During cardiac arrest, poor perfusion, low flow states, and background noise make auscultation unreliable","C. Capnography does not require an intact circulation","D. Both B and C are correct"],"correct":3,"rationale":"During cardiac arrest, poor perfusion means breath sounds may be faint or absent even with correct tube placement, and background noise interferes with auscultation. Capnography detects CO2 in exhaled gas regardless of perfusion status, though ETCO2 values will be low during low-flow states.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c03_q16","question":"After successfully placing an ET tube and confirming with capnography (ETCO2 = 15 mmHg), the team notices the waveform disappears and the patient's SpO2 begins to fall. What is the most likely cause?","options":["A. The patient has achieved ROSC","B. The ET tube has become displaced or obstructed","C. The capnography circuit is disconnected but the tube is still in place","D. ETCO2 naturally fluctuates during arrest"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Sudden loss of the capnography waveform with falling SpO2 after confirmed tracheal placement most strongly suggests tube displacement or obstruction, requiring immediate re-confirmation and repositioning.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","questions":[{"id":"c04_q01","question":"Which of the following cardiac arrest rhythms is shockable?","options":["A. Asystole","B. Pulseless electrical activity (PEA)","C. Ventricular fibrillation (VF)","D. Sinus bradycardia without a pulse"],"correct":2,"rationale":"VF and pulseless VT are the only two shockable cardiac arrest rhythms. Asystole and PEA are non-shockable and treated with CPR and epinephrine.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q02","question":"The 2025 AHA Guidelines no longer distinguish between which two types of asystole?","options":["A. Fine and coarse asystole","B. Complete and incomplete asystole","C. Primary and secondary asystole","D. Atrial and ventricular asystole"],"correct":0,"rationale":"The 2025 guidelines explicitly removed the fine vs coarse asystole distinction because it has no proven prognostic or therapeutic significance.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q03","question":"A patient in cardiac arrest shows an organized rhythm on the monitor at a rate of 75/min with clear P waves and QRS complexes, but no pulse is palpable. What is this rhythm?","options":["A. Normal sinus rhythm with ROSC","B. Pulseless electrical activity (PEA)","C. Asystole","D. Fine ventricular fibrillation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"PEA is defined as any organized electrical activity without a palpable pulse. The ECG can appear perfectly normal while the patient has no effective cardiac output.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q04","question":"How should the team handle an organized wide-complex tachycardia at 180/min when the patient has a radial pulse but blood pressure of 72/40 mmHg?","options":["A. Administer adenosine 6 mg IV","B. Perform vagal maneuvers","C. Immediate synchronized cardioversion at 100J","D. Observe and recheck in 10 minutes"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A hemodynamically unstable wide-complex tachycardia (hypotension present) should be treated with immediate synchronized cardioversion. The 2025 guidelines prioritize stability over rhythm diagnosis.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q05","question":"During CPR, the monitor shows what appears to be VF. What should the team do to verify this is not artifact?","options":["A. Deliver a shock immediately without further analysis","B. Briefly pause compressions for 5–10 seconds to observe the rhythm; if VF persists, defibrillate","C. Stop the resuscitation to obtain a 12-lead ECG","D. Switch to a different monitoring lead and continue compressions for 2 minutes"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Briefly pausing compressions helps distinguish true VF (which persists) from artifact (which disappears). If the patient is known to be in arrest and VF is confirmed, defibrillate.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q06","question":"What is the key difference between VF and pulseless VT in terms of ACLS treatment?","options":["A. VF requires defibrillation; pVT requires antiarrhythmics only","B. VF requires CPR first; pVT requires epinephrine first","C. Both are treated identically with immediate defibrillation","D. VF is shockable; pVT is not shockable"],"correct":2,"rationale":"VF and pulseless VT share an identical ACLS treatment pathway: immediate defibrillation followed by CPR, epinephrine, and antiarrhythmics for refractory cases.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q07","question":"Before diagnosing asystole, which of the following should be confirmed?","options":["A. Leads are connected, gain is adequate, and rhythm is present in at least two leads","B. The patient has received at least 3 doses of epinephrine","C. A pacemaker has been attempted","D. The defibrillator has been charged"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Asystole must be confirmed with proper lead connections, adequate gain, and presence in at least two leads to avoid misdiagnosing fine VF or lead disconnection as asystole.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q08","question":"Which clinical feature on ECG most strongly suggests VT rather than SVT with aberrancy?","options":["A. Heart rate of 170/min","B. Wide QRS complexes","C. AV dissociation with independent P waves and QRS complexes","D. Regular rhythm"],"correct":2,"rationale":"AV dissociation — where P waves and QRS complexes march through independently — is a strong ECG indicator of VT. Wide QRS and regular rhythm can occur in both VT and SVT with aberrancy.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q09","question":"A patient with known dilated cardiomyopathy presents with a wide-complex tachycardia at 200/min. The patient is conscious but hypotensive (BP 80/50). What is the best initial management?","options":["A. Adenosine 6 mg IV push","B. Vagal maneuvers","C. Immediate synchronized cardioversion at 100J","D. Amiodarone 150 mg IV over 10 minutes"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Hemodynamic instability (hypotension) in a wide-complex tachycardia mandates immediate synchronized cardioversion regardless of the underlying rhythm. Structural heart disease further favors VT.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q10","question":"Why is artifact-dropping-into-VF a particular concern during cardiac resuscitation?","options":["A. Artifact always indicates the patient is improving","B. Motion from compressions, transport, or shivering can generate electrical artifact mimicking VF","C. Artifact is only seen on defibrillator pads, not on telemetry","D. Artifact indicates the monitor is malfunctioning"],"correct":1,"rationale":"During resuscitation, physical movement from compressions, transport, or shivering can create electrical artifact on the ECG that resembles VF, potentially leading to misdiagnosis.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q11","question":"When should a full 12-lead ECG be obtained during cardiac arrest management?","options":["A. Immediately upon recognizing the arrest, before starting CPR","B. At every rhythm check during compressions","C. Promptly after ROSC, and during prolonged resuscitation when the rhythm provides diagnostic information","D. Only after the patient is discharged from the hospital"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A 12-lead ECG is most valuable after ROSC (to identify STEMI) or during prolonged resuscitation (to identify reversible causes). It is not a priority during active CPR but should be obtained as soon as clinically appropriate.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c04_q12","question":"A patient in cardiac arrest shows a narrow-complex regular rhythm at 40/min on the monitor but has no pulse. The team diagnoses asystole. What error might they be making?","options":["A. None — this is correctly diagnosed as asystole","B. This may be PEA (an organized rhythm without a pulse) rather than asystole","C. They should be defibrillating this rhythm","D. They need to check the rhythm in only one lead"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A narrow-complex regular rhythm at 40/min without a pulse is organized electrical activity — this is PEA, not asystole. The team must check a pulse and treat as PEA (CPR + epinephrine + reversible causes).","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c04_q13","question":"Why should you never confuse an organized rhythm on the monitor with a perfusing rhythm?","options":["A. All organized rhythms are perfusing","B. PEA demonstrates that organized electrical activity can exist without effective cardiac output or a palpable pulse","C. Only VF produces loss of pulse","D. Organized rhythms always indicate ROSC"],"correct":1,"rationale":"PEA is the defining example that organized electrical activity does not guarantee mechanical cardiac output. Always check for a pulse before concluding ROSC.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q14","question":"What is the correct approach when you cannot determine whether a wide-complex tachycardia is VT or SVT with aberrancy in an ACLS setting?","options":["A. Assume it is SVT and give adenosine","B. Treat as VT — synchronized cardioversion or antiarrhythmic therapy is the safer choice","C. Wait 30 minutes for the rhythm to self-resolve","D. Only shock if the patient is in cardiac arrest"],"correct":1,"rationale":"When VT vs SVT with aberrancy cannot be reliably distinguished, treating as VT is the safer approach. Cardioversion is effective for both; adenosine is not effective for VT and could cause harm in some contexts.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c04_q15","question":"A team is performing CPR and the monitor rhythm changes from asystole to a regular organized rhythm at 60/min. The team leader announces ROSC. What should the compressor do?","options":["A. Immediately stop compressions and prepare for post-arrest care","B. Pause briefly to check for a pulse — an organized rhythm without a pulse is PEA, not ROSC","C. Continue compressions for 2 more minutes regardless","D. Defibrillate the organized rhythm"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An organized rhythm appearing during CPR must be confirmed with a pulse check. PEA presents as organized activity without a pulse. Do not assume ROSC without pulse confirmation.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c04_q16","question":"Which of the following is TRUE about fine VF compared to coarse VF?","options":["A. Fine VF requires different energy levels for defibrillation","B. Fine VF is treated differently than coarse VF in the 2025 guidelines","C. Both are treated identically as VF — the fine/coarse distinction has no therapeutic significance","D. Fine VF should be treated as asystole"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The 2025 AHA Guidelines do not distinguish between fine and coarse VF for treatment purposes. Both are treated as VF with immediate defibrillation. Fine VF should not be misdiagnosed as asystole.","difficulty":"Medium"}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","questions":[{"id":"c05_q01","question":"What is the recommended biphasic first-shock energy for adult VF/pVT?","options":["A. 50–100J","B. 120–200J","C. 300J","D. 360J"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The 2025 AHA Guidelines recommend 120–200J biphasic for the first shock in adult VF/pVT, using the manufacturer's recommended energy for the specific waveform; if unknown, use 200J.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q02","question":"A monophasic defibrillator is the only device available during a VF arrest. What energy should be used for the first shock?","options":["A. 120J","B. 200J","C. 300J","D. 360J"],"correct":3,"rationale":"Monophasic defibrillators require 360J for defibrillation. This is the standard first-shock energy for monophasic devices.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q03","question":"What is the recommended initial synchronized cardioversion energy for atrial fibrillation?","options":["A. 50J","B. 100J","C. ≥200J biphasic","D. 360J"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The 2025 guidelines recommend ≥200J biphasic as the initial synchronized cardioversion energy for atrial fibrillation and atrial flutter, reflecting evidence that higher initial energies improve first-shock success.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q04","question":"What energy is used for synchronized cardioversion of narrow-regular SVT?","options":["A. 50J","B. 100J biphasic","C. 200J","D. 360J"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Narrow-regular SVT responds well to synchronized cardioversion starting at 100J biphasic, which is often effective on the first shock.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q05","question":"Why is synchronized cardioversion contraindicated in polymorphic VT?","options":["A. Polymorphic VT always converts spontaneously","B. The irregular, variable QRS morphology prevents reliable R-wave synchronization, risking R-on-T induction of VF","C. Polymorphic VT does not require treatment","D. Synchronized cardioversion is only for atrial arrhythmias"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Polymorphic VT has variable QRS morphology, making R-wave synchronization unreliable. Delivering an unsynchronized shock during the T wave (R-on-T) could induce VF. Polymorphic VT is treated with unsynchronized defibrillation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q06","question":"What is the starting current and titration schedule for transcutaneous pacing in adults?","options":["A. Start at 50 mA, increase by 5 mA every minute","B. Start at 80 mA, increase by 10 mA every 2–3 minutes, max 200 mA","C. Start at 100 mA, increase by 20 mA every minute","D. Start at 200 mA and maintain"],"correct":1,"rationale":"TCP starts at 80 mA and is increased by 10 mA every 2–3 minutes until electrical capture is achieved, with a maximum output of 200 mA for adults.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q07","question":"A patient has electrical capture on the monitor during transcutaneous pacing (wide QRS complexes follow each pacer spike at 90/min), but no pulse is palpable. What does this indicate?","options":["A. TCP is working perfectly","B. Electrical capture without mechanical capture — the paced complexes are not producing effective cardiac output","C. The pacemaker is malfunctioning","D. The patient has ROSC"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Electrical capture (visible on monitor) does not guarantee mechanical capture (effective cardiac output). Always verify by palpating a pulse with each paced complex. No pulse = no effective output.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q08","question":"A biphasic defibrillator's manual does not specify the recommended waveform energy. The team is treating VF. What energy should be used for the first shock?","options":["A. 120J","B. 150J","C. 200J","D. 360J"],"correct":2,"rationale":"When the biphasic waveform is unknown, the AHA recommends 200J as a safe default for the first shock.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q09","question":"What is the maximum current output for transcutaneous pacing in adults?","options":["A. 100 mA","B. 150 mA","C. 200 mA","D. 300 mA"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The maximum TCP output for adults is 200 mA. If electrical capture is not achieved by this level, TCP has failed and escalation to transvenous pacing or cardiology consultation is required.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q10","question":"What is overdrive pacing (anti-tachycardia pacing) primarily used for in ACLS?","options":["A. Treating asystole","B. Terminating re-entrant tachyarrhythmias such as monomorphic VT with a pulse, certain SVTs, and Torsades de Pointes","C. Increasing heart rate in bradycardia only","D. Defibrillating VF"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Overdrive pacing paces the heart at 10–20% above the tachycardia rate to interrupt re-entrant circuits. It is used for organized VT with a pulse, certain SVTs, and Torsades de Pointes (pacing at 90–110/min).","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q11","question":"A patient with monomorphic VT with a pulse is hemodynamically unstable. What is the recommended initial synchronized cardioversion energy?","options":["A. 50J","B. 100J biphasic","C. 200J","D. 360J"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Monomorphic VT with a pulse is cardioverted starting at 100J biphasic. If unsuccessful, energy should be escalated.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q12","question":"After a successful first-shock biphasic defibrillation of VF, what is the next step before the second rhythm check?","options":["A. Immediately re-analyze the rhythm","B. Resume CPR for 2 minutes, then re-analyze","C. Administer epinephrine immediately","D. Attempt transcutaneous pacing"],"correct":1,"rationale":"After each defibrillation shock, CPR should be resumed immediately for 2 minutes before the next rhythm check and potential subsequent shock.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q13","question":"Which of the following rhythms is treated with unsynchronized defibrillation rather than synchronized cardioversion?","options":["A. Monomorphic VT with a pulse","B. Atrial fibrillation","C. Polymorphic VT","D. Narrow-regular SVT"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Polymorphic VT is treated with unsynchronized high-energy defibrillation because the variable QRS morphology prevents reliable R-wave synchronization, making synchronized cardioversion dangerous.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q14","question":"What is the primary indication for transcutaneous pacing in ACLS?","options":["A. Ventricular fibrillation","B. Hemodynamically significant bradycardia unresponsive to atropine","C. Atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response","D. Asystole"],"correct":1,"rationale":"TCP is indicated for symptomatic bradycardia that does not respond to atropine, as a bridge to transvenous pacing or permanent pacemaker placement.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q15","question":"A patient is in Torsades de Pointes (polymorphic VT associated with QT prolongation). What pacing strategy can be both therapeutic and preventive?","options":["A. Overdrive pacing at 90–110/min to suppress the triggering premature ventricular complexes","B. Pacing at 40/min to slow the heart rate","C. Defibrillation only — pacing is not used for Torsades","D. Synchronized cardioversion at 200J"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Overdrive pacing at 90–110/min suppresses the premature ventricular complexes that trigger Torsades de Pointes, providing both acute termination and prevention of recurrence.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c05_q16","question":"What type of sedation is recommended before elective synchronized cardioversion in a conscious patient?","options":["A. No sedation is needed","B. Sedation and analgesia (e.g., midazolam, propofol, etomidate, or ketamine) per protocol","C. General anesthesia in all cases","D. Only oral acetaminophen"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Synchronized cardioversion is painful in a conscious patient. Sedation and analgesia should be provided per institutional protocol before elective cardioversion.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q17","question":"During transcutaneous pacing, the patient's wide QRS complexes are visible on the monitor following each pacer spike, but the blood pressure remains 60/30 mmHg. What is the most appropriate action?","options":["A. Increase the pacer rate to 120/min","B. Verify mechanical capture by palpating a pulse — if absent, electrical capture without mechanical capture requires further intervention","C. Stop pacing immediately","D. Defibrillate the patient"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Electrical capture without adequate mechanical capture (no palpable pulse, persistent hypotension) requires further evaluation. The team must confirm mechanical capture and consider transvenous pacing or additional medical therapy.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c05_q18","question":"After an unsuccessful first-shock biphasic defibrillation of VF at 150J, what energy should the team use for the second shock?","options":["A. 150J again","B. 120J","C. The maximum available biphasic energy","D. 360J regardless of the defibrillator type"],"correct":2,"rationale":"If the first biphasic shock is unsuccessful, subsequent shocks should use the maximum available biphasic energy to maximize the chance of successful defibrillation.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","questions":[{"id":"c06_q01","question":"A patient is found in ventricular fibrillation. What is the first intervention?","options":["A. Administer epinephrine","B. Establish IV access","C. Deliver a defibrillation shock","D. Place an advanced airway"],"correct":2,"rationale":"VF and pVT are shockable rhythms. The single most important intervention is immediate defibrillation — survival declines with every minute delay.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q02","question":"What biphasic energy level is recommended for the first shock in VF/pVT?","options":["A. 50 J","B. 100 J","C. 120–200 J","D. 360 J"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The 2025 AHA guidelines recommend 120–200 J for the first biphasic shock, per manufacturer recommendations. 360 J is for monophasic waveforms.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q03","question":"What energy should be used for monophasic defibrillation in VF/pVT?","options":["A. 200 J","B. 300 J","C. 360 J","D. 400 J"],"correct":2,"rationale":"All monophasic defibrillation shocks use 360 J regardless of the number of prior shocks.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q04","question":"Immediately after delivering a shock to a patient in VF, the team should:","options":["A. Pause to check the pulse","B. Pause to check the rhythm on the monitor","C. Resume chest compressions immediately without a pulse check","D. Administer epinephrine before resuming compressions"],"correct":2,"rationale":"After defibrillation, compressions resume immediately without checking pulse or rhythm. CPR continues for approximately 2 minutes before the next rhythm check.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q05","question":"What is the minimum acceptable chest compression fraction (CCF) during VF/pVT arrest?","options":["A. 40%","B. 50%","C. 60%","D. 80%"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The target CCF is ≥60%, with ≥80% being ideal. CCF is independently associated with survival to discharge.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q06","question":"During VF/pVT arrest, when should epinephrine be administered?","options":["A. Before the first shock","B. After the first shock","C. As soon as reasonably available, typically after the second shock, then every 3–5 minutes","D. Only after ROSC is achieved"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO is given as soon as reasonably available, typically after the second shock in a persistent VF/pVT arrest, then repeated every 3–5 minutes.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q07","question":"What is the first dose of amiodarone for refractory VF/pVT?","options":["A. 150 mg IV/IO","B. 300 mg IV/IO","C. 450 mg IV/IO","D. 50 mg IV/IO"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Amiodarone is given as 300 mg IV/IO as the first dose for refractory VF/pVT. A second dose of 150 mg IV/IO may follow if VF/pVT persists.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q08","question":"A patient remains in VF after the third shock and amiodarone is unavailable. Which antiarrhythmic should be given instead, and at what dose?","options":["A. Lidocaine 0.5–0.75 mg/kg IV/IO","B. Lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO","C. Lidocaine 2–3 mg/kg IV/IO","D. Lidocaine 50 mg flat dose IV/IO"],"correct":1,"rationale":"When amiodarone is unavailable, lidocaine is an acceptable alternative antiarrhythmic for refractory VF/pVT, dosed at 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO for the first dose.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q09","question":"What is the second dose of amiodarone if VF/pVT persists after the first 300 mg dose?","options":["A. 300 mg IV/IO","B. 150 mg IV/IO","C. 50 mg IV/IO","D. 450 mg IV/IO"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The second dose of amiodarone for persistent VF/pVT is 150 mg IV/IO, which is half the first dose.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q10","question":"A pulse check during VF/pVT resuscitation should be performed:","options":["A. After every shock","B. Every minute","C. Only when a rhythm check reveals an organized (non-VF/pVT) rhythm","D. Before every drug administration"],"correct":2,"rationale":"During ongoing VF/pVT, there is no pulse to check. A pulse check is only indicated when the rhythm check shows an organized rhythm that might generate a pulse.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q11","question":"Correct CPR quality parameters during VF/pVT arrest include all of the following EXCEPT:","options":["A. Compression rate of 100–120/min","B. Compression depth of 2–2.4 inches (5–6 cm)","C. Allowing full chest recoil between compressions","D. Compression rate of 60–80/min to allow adequate filling"],"correct":3,"rationale":"The correct compression rate is 100–120/min. A rate of 60–80/min is too slow and does not generate adequate cardiac output during arrest.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q12","question":"Why is minimizing the pre-shock pause important in VF/pVT defibrillation?","options":["A. To reduce patient discomfort","B. Because prolonged pauses decrease coronary perfusion pressure, reducing the likelihood of successful defibrillation and ROSC","C. Because the defibrillator charges faster with shorter pauses","D. Because the AHA recommends exactly 10-second pauses"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Prolonged pre-shock pauses cause coronary perfusion pressure to fall, which decreases the likelihood of successful defibrillation and ROSC. Rescuers should keep hands on the chest until the last possible moment before shock delivery.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c06_q13","question":"When considering refractory VF/pVT strategies after ≥3 shocks, which of the following is a Class 2b option?","options":["A. Immediate ECPR for all patients","B. Vector-change defibrillation or dual sequential external defibrillation (DSED)","C. Routine sodium bicarbonate administration","D. Transcutaneous pacing"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Vector-change defibrillation and DSED are Class 2b (may be considered) options for refractory VF/pVT. They are not routine first-line steps but may be useful in selected cases.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c06_q14","question":"What is the correct second dose of lidocaine for persistent VF/pVT?","options":["A. 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO","B. 0.5–0.75 mg/kg IV/IO","C. 300 mg IV/IO","D. 2 mg/kg IV/IO"],"correct":1,"rationale":"After the initial lidocaine dose of 1–1.5 mg/kg, subsequent doses are 0.5–0.75 mg/kg IV/IO.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q15","question":"Which statement about epinephrine administration during VF/pVT arrest is correct?","options":["A. Epinephrine should be given during a dedicated pause in compressions","B. Epinephrine should be given as a continuous infusion throughout the arrest","C. Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO is pushed during ongoing compressions and followed by a saline flush","D. Epinephrine is only given after ROSC is achieved"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Epinephrine is pushed during ongoing compressions — it does not require a pause — and is followed by a saline flush to ensure the drug reaches the central circulation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c06_q16","question":"How often should compressors be switched during a VF/pVT resuscitation?","options":["A. Every 5 minutes","B. Approximately every 2 minutes, timed with the rhythm check","C. Every 10 minutes","D. Only when a compressor becomes fatigued"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Compressors should be switched approximately every 2 minutes to prevent fatigue-related decline in compression quality, conveniently timed with the rhythm check to minimize additional pauses.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c06_q17","question":"What does waveform capnography indicate when placed after an advanced airway during VF/pVT arrest?","options":["A. Only confirms tube placement","B. Monitors CPR quality (ETCO₂ correlates with cardiac output) and detects ROSC (sudden sustained ETCO₂ rise)","C. Measures blood oxygen saturation","D. Determines the rhythm type"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Waveform capnography serves dual roles during arrest: it monitors CPR quality because ETCO₂ correlates with cardiac output during compressions, and a sudden sustained rise in ETCO₂ may indicate ROSC.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c06_q18","question":"A second-shock energy dose for biphasic VF/pVT that persists after the first shock should be:","options":["A. The same energy as the first shock","B. Higher than or equal to the first shock energy (escalating)","C. Lower energy to reduce myocardial damage","D. Fixed at 200 J regardless of first-shock energy"],"correct":1,"rationale":"If biphasic VF/pVT persists after the first shock, the second shock energy should be equal to or higher than the first (escalating strategy) up to the maximum available. If the biphasic waveform energy is unknown, use 200 J.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c07":{"chapter":"c07","questions":[{"id":"c07_q01","question":"Asystole is identified on the cardiac monitor. What is the first intervention?","options":["A. Deliver a defibrillation shock","B. Start high-quality CPR and administer epinephrine","C. Place a transcutaneous pacemaker","D. Administer amiodarone"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Asystole is a nonshockable rhythm. Defibrillation is not indicated. The priority is high-quality CPR with ventilations, early epinephrine, and identification of reversible causes.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c07_q02","question":"Why is defibrillation NOT appropriate for PEA?","options":["A. PEA is too slow to defibrillate","B. PEA is already an organized rhythm — the problem is mechanical failure to produce a pulse, not disorganized electrical activity","C. PEA always resolves spontaneously","D. PEA only occurs in children"],"correct":1,"rationale":"PEA is an organized electrical rhythm that fails to generate a pulse. There is no chaotic or fibrillatory activity to defibrillate — the management focuses on CPR, epinephrine, and treating the underlying cause.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c07_q03","question":"What is the recommended epinephrine dose for asystole/PEA arrest?","options":["A. 0.1 mg IV every 3–5 minutes","B. 1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000) every 3–5 minutes","C. 5 mg IV every 3–5 minutes","D. 0.5 mg IV once"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000 concentration) is given every 3–5 minutes for all cardiac arrest rhythms, including asystole and PEA.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c07_q04","question":"When should epinephrine ideally be given for a nonshockable rhythm?","options":["A. After 10 minutes of CPR","B. Only after ROSC","C. As soon as feasible, ideally within 3–5 minutes of arrest onset","D. At the same time as amiodarone"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The 2025 guidelines emphasize early epinephrine for nonshockable rhythms. Evidence supports giving it as soon as IV/IO access is established, ideally within 3–5 minutes of arrest onset.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q05","question":"Which of the following is NOT one of the H's of reversible causes?","options":["A. Hypovolemia","B. Hydrogen ion (acidosis)","C. Hyperthermia","D. Hypoxia"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The H's are: Hypovolemia, Hypoxia, Hydrogen ion, Hypo-/Hyperkalemia, Hypothermia. Hyperthermia is not included — the correct term is Hypothermia (low temperature).","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c07_q06","question":"Which of the following is one of the T's of reversible causes?","options":["A. Tachycardia","B. Tension pneumothorax","C. Thyroid storm","D. Tetanus"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The T's are: Tension pneumothorax, Tamponade (cardiac), Toxins, Thrombosis (pulmonary), Thrombosis (coronary).","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c07_q07","question":"How many ECG leads should be used to confirm true asystole?","options":["A. One lead is sufficient","B. At least two leads","C. Three leads","D. A full 12-lead ECG is mandatory"],"correct":1,"rationale":"True asystole should be confirmed on at least two leads to exclude lead disconnection artifacts, fine VF, or pseudo-asystole.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q08","question":"What does an ETCO₂ <10 mmHg during CPR in a patient with an advanced airway suggest?","options":["A. Excellent CPR quality","B. ROSC is imminent","C. Very low or absent cardiac output (consistent with asystole, fine VF, or poor compressions)","D. The airway is misplaced"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Very low ETCO₂ during CPR indicates minimal cardiac output. In the context of known asystole, it confirms absent cardiac function and helps assess CPR quality.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q09","question":"During a code for asystole, the rhythm check at 2 minutes shows fine, barely visible oscillations. What should the team do?","options":["A. Continue treating asystole — the oscillations are artifact","B. Treat as VF/pVT and deliver a defibrillation shock","C. Stop resuscitation","D. Administer sodium bicarbonate"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Fine VF can mimic asystole. If any fibrillatory activity is identified, the rhythm is shockable and should be treated with defibrillation per the VF/pVT algorithm.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c07_q10","question":"Which reversible cause should you suspect first in a patient with narrow-complex PEA and distended neck veins after trauma?","options":["A. Hypovolemia","B. Tension pneumothorax","C. Cardiac tamponade","D. Massive pulmonary embolism"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Distended neck veins (JVD) with PEA post-trauma suggest obstructive shock. Cardiac tamponade (Beck's triad: JVD, muffled heart sounds, hypotension) and tension pneumothorax (JVD + absent breath sounds + tracheal deviation) are top considerations. With distended neck veins and trauma, tamponade from penetrating injury is a primary suspect.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c07_q11","question":"Narrow-complex PEA versus wide-complex PEA — which clinical distinction is most useful?","options":["A. Narrow-complex PEA never needs treatment","B. Wide-complex PEA should always be shocked","C. Narrow-complex PEA may suggest a more reversible etiology (hypovolemia, pneumothorax, tamponade) and may respond more rapidly to cause-directed therapy","D. The algorithm differs completely between narrow and wide PEA"],"correct":2,"rationale":"While the algorithm is the same for both, narrow-complex PEA often suggests a potentially more reversible cause (hypovolemia, pneumothorax, tamponade) that may respond quickly to targeted treatment. Wide-complex/slow PEA may indicate more advanced myocardial dysfunction or metabolic derangement.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c07_q12","question":"In which specific circumstance may a mechanical CPR device be considered during an asystole arrest?","options":["A. For all cardiac arrests as the first-line approach","B. During ECPR cannulation when manual compressions are impractical","C. When there are 5 or more providers available","D. In the emergency department only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Mechanical CPR devices are not routinely recommended but may be considered when high-quality manual compressions are impractical or unsafe to sustain — such as during ECPR cannulation, prolonged transport with limited personnel, or in the catheterization lab.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q13","question":"A patient with known severe hyperkalemia (K⁺ 7.8 mEq/L) develops asystole. Which H is the most likely cause and what is the first treatment?","options":["A. Hypovolemia — give fluids","B. Hyperkalemia — give calcium chloride, insulin/glucose, sodium bicarbonate","C. Hypothermia — warm the patient","D. Hydrogen ion — give sodium bicarbonate only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Hyperkalemia is a well-known reversible cause of cardiac arrest (one of the H's). Treatment includes IV calcium (membrane stabilization), insulin with glucose (intracellular shift), sodium bicarbonate, and dialysis. Recognizing and treating the cause is critical — epinephrine alone has limited benefit.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q14","question":"Why is systematic searching for reversible causes especially important in asystole/PEA compared to VF/pVT?","options":["A. It is equally important in all arrest rhythms","B. Because asystole/PEA typically results from an identifiable, treatable underlying condition, and drug therapy alone without treating the cause has limited benefit","C. Because VF/pVT never has a reversible cause","D. Because asystole/PEA always requires surgery"],"correct":1,"rationale":"While reversible causes matter in all arrests, asystole/PEA most commonly result from identifiable causes (hypovolemia, pneumothorax, PE, MI, toxins, etc.) that require specific treatment. CPR and epinephrine buy time, but ROSC depends on finding and fixing the cause.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q15","question":"A patient in asystole achieves ROSC briefly but re-arrests into asystole. Epinephrine was last given 2 minutes ago. What should be done?","options":["A. Wait another minute before giving epinephrine","B. Resume CPR, repeat epinephrine now (q3–5 min interval met), and re-search for reversible causes","C. Defibrillate immediately","D. Terminate resuscitation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"After re-arrest into asystole, CPR should resume immediately. Epinephrine should be repeated every 3–5 minutes. Since 2 minutes have passed, the next dose is due. Simultaneously, re-evaluate for reversible causes that may have caused re-arrest.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c07_q16","question":"What does the 2025 AHA guideline say about routine use of mechanical CPR devices?","options":["A. They are recommended for all cardiac arrests","B. Routine use is NOT recommended — they are reasonable only in specific circumstances where manual compressions are impractical","C. They are contraindicated in all arrests","D. They should replace manual compressions in all hospitals"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The 2025 guidelines state that routine use of mechanical CPR devices is not recommended. They may be considered only in specific situations where sustained high-quality manual compressions are impractical or unsafe.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c07_q17","question":"A patient presents with PEA arrest and has signs of acute massive pulmonary embolism (sudden dyspnea, pleuritic chest pain before arrest, right heart strain on bedside echo). Which T is the likely cause?","options":["A. Tension pneumothorax","B. Tamponade","C. Toxins","D. Thrombosis (pulmonary)"],"correct":3,"rationale":"Massive pulmonary embolism (thrombosis — pulmonary) is one of the T's. Clinical clues include sudden onset, pleuritic chest pain, right heart strain, and risk factors for PE.","difficulty":"Easy"}]},"c08":{"chapter":"c08","questions":[{"id":"c08_q01","question":"What is the correct concentration of epinephrine used in cardiac arrest?","options":["A. 1:1,000 (1 mg/mL)","B. 1:10,000 (0.1 mg/mL)","C. 1:100,000 (0.01 mg/mL)","D. 1:100 (10 mg/mL)"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Epinephrine in cardiac arrest is given as 1 mg of 1:10,000 concentration (0.1 mg/mL). Using 1:1,000 would result in a 10-fold overdose.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c08_q02","question":"What is the correct epinephrine dose and interval during cardiac arrest?","options":["A. 0.5 mg IV every 1 minute","B. 1 mg IV/IO every 3–5 minutes","C. 2 mg IV every 10 minutes","D. 5 mg IV once"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000) is given every 3–5 minutes for all cardiac arrest rhythms.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c08_q03","question":"The first dose of amiodarone for refractory VF/pVT is:","options":["A. 150 mg IV/IO","B. 300 mg IV/IO","C. 450 mg IV/IO","D. 50 mg IV/IO"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Amiodarone first dose for refractory VF/pVT is 300 mg IV/IO as a rapid bolus. The second dose is 150 mg.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c08_q04","question":"The second dose of amiodarone for persistent VF/pVT is:","options":["A. 300 mg IV/IO","B. 150 mg IV/IO","C. 50 mg IV/IO","D. 100 mg IV/IO"],"correct":1,"rationale":"After the initial 300 mg dose, the second dose of amiodarone is 150 mg IV/IO if VF/pVT persists.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c08_q05","question":"What is the first dose of lidocaine as an alternative antiarrhythmic for refractory VF/pVT?","options":["A. 0.5–0.75 mg/kg IV/IO","B. 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO","C. 2–3 mg/kg IV/IO","D. 50 mg flat dose IV/IO"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Lidocaine first dose is 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO for refractory VF/pVT, with subsequent doses of 0.5–0.75 mg/kg.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q06","question":"Sodium bicarbonate 1 mEq/kg IV is indicated during cardiac arrest for all of the following EXCEPT:","options":["A. Known hyperkalemia with cardiac arrest","B. Tricyclic antidepressant overdose","C. Routine VF arrest without specific indications","D. Known bicarbonate-responsive acidosis"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Sodium bicarbonate is NOT a routine cardiac arrest drug. It is indicated only for specific conditions: hyperkalemia, TCA OD, and known bicarbonate-responsive acidosis.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q07","question":"Which diluent must be used for standard amiodarone infusions, and why?","options":["A. Normal saline, because dextrose degrades the active drug","B. 5% Dextrose in water (D5W), because normal saline causes the drug to precipitate","C. Lactated Ringer's, to maintain electrolyte balance","D. Sterile water, to prevent volume overload"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Standard amiodarone is incompatible with sodium chloride (normal saline) and will precipitate, forming crystals. Therefore, D5W must be used as the diluent. The solvent polysorbate 80 can cause hypotension during infusion, which is a known side effect of rapid administration and not a reaction to dextrose.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q08","question":"Magnesium sulfate 1–2 g IV is specifically indicated for which cardiac arrest rhythm?","options":["A. Pulseless ventricular tachycardia","B. Asystole","C. Torsades de pointes (polymorphic VT with prolonged QT)","D. Fine ventricular fibrillation"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Magnesium 1–2 g IV is indicated specifically for torsades de pointes. It is NOT indicated for standard VF or pulseless VT.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q09","question":"What is the dose of vasopressin in cardiac arrest, and why is it no longer preferred?","options":["A. 10 IU — it was less effective than epinephrine","B. 20 IU — it offers no demonstrated survival advantage over epinephrine alone","C. 40 IU — it causes dangerous vasoconstriction","D. 5 IU — it was too weak to be useful"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Vasopressin 20 IU may replace the first or second dose of epinephrine, but epinephrine alone is preferred. Vasopressin offers no demonstrated survival advantage over epinephrine.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q10","question":"Why is adenosine contraindicated in pulseless arrest?","options":["A. It is too expensive for use in arrest","B. It has an extremely short half-life and requires a pulse to reach the heart effectively; it has no role in VF/pVT/asystole/PEA","C. It causes ventricular fibrillation","D. It can only be given intramuscularly"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Adenosine is a short-acting AV nodal blocker for SVT with a pulse. Its 6-second half-life and mechanism of action make it completely ineffective in pulseless rhythms. It should never be used in cardiac arrest.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c08_q11","question":"When epinephrine is given for VF/pVT, what is the recommended timing relative to shocks?","options":["A. Before the first shock","B. After the second shock, then every 3–5 minutes","C. After the fifth shock","D. Only after ROSC"],"correct":1,"rationale":"For VF/pVT, epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO is typically given after the second shock, then repeated every 3–5 minutes during ongoing CPR.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q12","question":"For asystole/PEA, epinephrine timing is:","options":["A. After 10 minutes of CPR","B. As soon as feasible, ideally within 3–5 minutes of arrest onset","C. After the first shock","D. Only after confirming a reversible cause"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The 2025 guidelines emphasize early epinephrine for nonshockable rhythms, ideally within 3–5 minutes of arrest onset. Do not delay for IV access — use IO if needed.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q13","question":"What is the correct saline flush after an epinephrine bolus during CPR?","options":["A. No flush is needed","B. 1–2 mL flush","C. 10–20 mL normal saline flush followed by an IV/IO fluid push","D. 50 mL dextrose flush"],"correct":2,"rationale":"After each drug bolus, a 10–20 mL normal saline flush followed by an IV/IO fluid push ensures the drug reaches the central circulation. Dextrose should not be used as a flush for most arrest drugs.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q14","question":"Which statement about IV vs IO access during cardiac arrest is correct?","options":["A. IO access is contraindicated during cardiac arrest","B. IV is preferred first-line; IO is reasonable when IV cannot be obtained quickly, with comparable drug bioavailability","C. IO access is only for pediatric patients","D. IV access is always faster than IO access"],"correct":1,"rationale":"IV access is preferred first-line. IO is reasonable when IV cannot be obtained quickly — drugs delivered via IO reach the central circulation with comparable speed and bioavailability.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c08_q15","question":"A patient in cardiac arrest has a known history of chronic renal failure. At the third rhythm check, the ECG shows very peaked T waves. Potassium returns at 8.2 mEq/L. Which drug should be given in addition to standard ACLS?","options":["A. Amiodarone 300 mg IV","B. Sodium bicarbonate 1 mEq/kg IV (along with calcium and insulin/glucose)","C. Magnesium 2 g IV","D. Adenosine 6 mg IV"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Severe hyperkalemia (K⁺ 8.2) with peaked T waves is a specific indication for sodium bicarbonate 1 mEq/kg IV, along with calcium (membrane stabilization), insulin/glucose (intracellular shift), and ultimately dialysis.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c08_q16","question":"Why should you never give amiodarone and then lidocaine (or vice versa) within the same arrest?","options":["A. The drugs interact to cause asystole","B. Using one agent consistently maintains predictable levels and avoids cumulative toxicity without clear benefit from switching","C. They are identical drugs with different names","D. It is against the law"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The ACLS guidelines recommend using one antiarrhythmic consistently rather than alternating, to maintain predictable drug levels and avoid additive toxicity without proven benefit from switching.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c08_q17","question":"Which antiarrhythmic agent is preferred when the VF/pVT arrest is clearly due to acute ischemia/MI?","options":["A. Amiodarone","B. Lidocaine","C. Magnesium sulfate","D. Sodium bicarbonate"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Lidocaine is preferred as an alternative to amiodarone when the arrest is clearly due to acute ischemia/MI, as it has particular efficacy in ischemia-related ventricular arrhythmias.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c09":{"chapter":"c09","questions":[{"id":"c09_q01","question":"Which of the following is NOT one of the H's in the H's & T's mnemonic?","options":["A. Hypovolemia","B. Hypoxia","C. Hypertension","D. Hypothermia"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The five H's are Hypovolemia, Hypoxia, Hydrogen ion (acidosis), Hypo-/Hyperkalemia, and Hypothermia. Hypertension is not a reversible cause of cardiac arrest.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c09_q02","question":"A patient in PEA arrest has muffled heart sounds, jugular venous distention, and pulsus paradoxus on the arterial line. What is the most likely reversible cause?","options":["A. Tension pneumothorax","B. Hypovolemia","C. Cardiac tamponade","D. Pulmonary embolism"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The triad of muffled heart sounds, JVD, and PEA arrest strongly suggests cardiac tamponade, which requires emergent pericardiocentesis.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c09_q03","question":"What is the first-line treatment for a hyperkalemic cardiac arrest?","options":["A. Atropine","B. Calcium chloride 1 g IV","C. Epinephrine 1 mg IV","D. Sodium bicarbonate only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Calcium chloride 1 g IV provides rapid membrane stabilization in hyperkalemic arrest, followed by bicarbonate, insulin/glucose, and albuterol to shift potassium intracellularly.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q04","question":"VF has persisted after five consecutive biphasic shocks at 200 J with ongoing high-quality CPR and epinephrine. What antiarrhythmic should be given next?","options":["A. Atropine 1 mg","B. Adenosine 6 mg","C. Amiodarone 300 mg IV bolus","D. Magnesium 2 g IV"],"correct":2,"rationale":"After ≥3 shocks, amiodarone 300 mg IV/IO bolus is the first-line antiarrhythmic for refractory VF/pVT; a repeat dose of 150 mg may be given if needed.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q05","question":"What is the AHA recommendation class for dual sequential external defibrillation (DSED) in refractory VF/pVT?","options":["A. Class 1 (recommended)","B. Class 2a (probably beneficial)","C. Class 2b (may be considered)","D. Class 3 (harmful)"],"correct":2,"rationale":"DSED is Class 2b (LOE B-R) — its usefulness is not established as routine therapy; it may be considered as a selective option.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c09_q06","question":"A patient in cardiac arrest has absent breath sounds on the right, tracheal deviation to the left, and distended neck veins. What is the immediate treatment?","options":["A. Pericardiocentesis","B. Needle decompression of the right second intercostal space","C. Thrombolysis","D. Defibrillation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Tension pneumothorax requires immediate needle decompression (large-bore needle, 2nd intercostal space midclavicular line) followed by chest tube placement.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c09_q07","question":"During ongoing CPR, the ETCO₂ suddenly drops from 18 mmHg to 6 mmHg. What should the team suspect first?","options":["A. ROSC is imminent","B. Degradation in CPR quality or a new reversible cause","C. The endotracheal tube has shifted into the esophagus","D. The patient has developed ventricular fibrillation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A sudden ETCO₂ drop during CPR indicates either a deterioration in compression quality or a new reversible cause — both should be checked immediately.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q08","question":"A hypothermic cardiac arrest patient has a core temperature of 28°C. After 30 minutes of CPR, what is the correct disposition?","options":["A. Declare futility and stop resuscitation","B. Continue resuscitation — do not declare futility until core temperature is at least 32°C","C. Transport immediately without further CPR","D. Give epinephrine and stop CPR"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Hypothermic patients may achieve neurologically intact survival after prolonged resuscitation; do not declare futility until core temperature reaches at least 32°C.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c09_q09","question":"Which of the following is a T in the H's & T's mnemonic?","options":["A. Thrombosis (pulmonary)","B. Tachycardia","C. Trauma","D. Thyroid storm"],"correct":0,"rationale":"The five T's are Tension pneumothorax, Tamponade (cardiac), Toxins, Thrombosis (pulmonary), and Thrombosis (coronary).","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c09_q10","question":"What is the alternative antiarrhythmic to amiodarone for refractory VF/pVT?","options":["A. Adenosine 6 mg","B. Lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO","C. Procainamide 100 mg","D. Digoxin 0.5 mg"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO is the acceptable alternative to amiodarone, particularly when amiodarone is unavailable.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q11","question":"A patient in PEA arrest is found to have a flat IVC on bedside ultrasound. What reversible cause should be suspected?","options":["A. Cardiac tamponade","B. Tension pneumothorax","C. Hypovolemia","D. Pulmonary embolism"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A flat (collapsed) IVC in PEA arrest is consistent with hypovolemia — treat with volume resuscitation and identify the source of fluid loss.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q12","question":"When should vector-change defibrillation be considered?","options":["A. As the first shock for any VF arrest","B. After standard pad positions have failed to terminate refractory VF","C. Only for asystole","D. Never — it is Class 3"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Vector-change defibrillation involves altering pad placement after standard positions fail; it is a Class 2b option for refractory VF.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q13","question":"Which ECG finding is most characteristic of hyperkalemia?","options":["A. Peaked T waves and widened QRS","B. Deep S waves in leads V1-V2","C. ST elevation in lateral leads","D. Shortened PR interval"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Peaked T waves progressing to a wide QRS complex are the hallmark ECG findings of hyperkalemia, which may degenerate into VF or asystole.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c09_q14","question":"During refractory VF arrest, how frequently should the compressor be rotated?","options":["A. Every 5 minutes","B. Every 2 minutes","C. Every 10 minutes","D. Only when fatigued"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Compressor rotation every 2 minutes (timed with rhythm checks) prevents fatigue-related degradation of compression quality.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c09_q15","question":"A massive pulmonary embolism causes PEA arrest. Catheter-based embolectomy is not available for at least 60 minutes. What intervention should be considered?","options":["A. Additional epinephrine only","B. Systemic thrombolysis","C. A second dose of atropine","D. Transcutaneous pacing"],"correct":1,"rationale":"In suspected massive PE arrest without immediate access to catheter-based embolectomy, systemic thrombolysis should be considered.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c09_q16","question":"What is the key mechanism by which sodium bicarbonate helps in hyperkalemic cardiac arrest?","options":["A. It directly removes potassium from the blood","B. It transiently shifts potassium intracellularly by alkalinizing the serum","C. It increases heart rate","D. It defibrillates VF"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Sodium bicarbonate alkalinizes the serum, causing a transient shift of potassium into cells; it is one part of a multimodal approach that also includes calcium, insulin/glucose, and albuterol.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c09_q17","question":"When is magnesium sulfate specifically indicated during cardiac arrest?","options":["A. For all VF arrests","B. For polymorphic VT (torsades de pointes)","C. For asystole","D. For bradycardia with a pulse"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Magnesium sulfate 1–2 g IV is specifically indicated for polymorphic VT (torsades de pointes), not for routine VF/pVT.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c09_q18","question":"In refractory arrest management, what should happen BEFORE each subsequent defibrillation attempt?","options":["A. Immediately shock again without pause","B. Reassess CPR quality, ETCO₂, compressor rotation, pad position, and consider reversible causes","C. Administer another dose of epinephrine","D. Intubate the patient"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Before each shock, the team should systematically reassess CPR quality, trending ETCO₂, compressor status, pad placement, and the H's and T's.","difficulty":"Medium"}]},"c10":{"chapter":"c10","questions":[{"id":"c10_q01","question":"A patient has a heart rate of 45/min with normal blood pressure, clear mentation, and no chest pain. What is the correct initial action?","options":["A. Give atropine 1 mg IV immediately","B. Begin transcutaneous pacing","C. Monitor and observe while investigating the cause","D. Start a dopamine infusion"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Asymptomatic bradycardia without signs of instability is observed and investigated, not immediately treated with drugs or pacing.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c10_q02","question":"What is the correct first-line drug dose for symptomatic bradycardia?","options":["A. Atropine 0.5 mg IV once","B. Atropine 1 mg IV/IO, may repeat q3-5min to max 3 mg","C. Epinephrine 1 mg IV every 3-5 min","D. Atropine 3 mg IV as a single dose"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Atropine 1 mg IV or IO is given first, repeated every 3–5 minutes to a maximum total of 3 mg.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c10_q03","question":"A patient with symptomatic bradycardia has a wide-QRS third-degree AV block. Atropine 1 mg has just been given. What is the best next step?","options":["A. Repeat atropine and wait to see if it works","B. Prepare for transcutaneous pacing and/or an infusion without delay, since infranodal block is unlikely to respond to atropine","C. Give a second 3 mg dose of atropine immediately","D. Discharge the patient"],"correct":1,"rationale":"High-grade/third-degree block with a wide QRS is infranodal and unlikely to respond to atropine; pacing or an infusion should not be delayed by repeated ineffective atropine dosing.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c10_q04","question":"What is the maximum total dose of atropine for bradycardia?","options":["A. 1 mg","B. 2 mg","C. 3 mg","D. 5 mg"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Atropine is dosed 1 mg IV/IO, repeated every 3–5 minutes, to a maximum total of 3 mg.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c10_q05","question":"Transcutaneous pacing has been started. Pacing spikes with a wide QRS are seen on the monitor, but no pulse is palpable at the paced rate. What is the correct interpretation?","options":["A. This is adequate capture; continue as is","B. Electrical capture without mechanical capture — treat as if pacing is not working (consider PEA/shock)","C. Increase the pacing rate only","D. This confirms successful pacing"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Electrical capture (spike + QRS) without a corresponding pulse means there is no effective mechanical capture; the patient's perfusion status must be reassessed.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c10_q06","question":"Which two second-line options can be used when atropine fails in symptomatic bradycardia?","options":["A. Amiodarone and lidocaine","B. Transcutaneous pacing and dopamine or epinephrine infusion","C. Adenosine and vagal maneuvers","D. Synchronized cardioversion and magnesium"],"correct":1,"rationale":"When atropine is ineffective, transcutaneous pacing and dopamine or epinephrine infusion are the recommended next-line therapies.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q07","question":"A conscious patient is undergoing transcutaneous pacing. What should be provided if hemodynamically tolerated?","options":["A. General anesthesia","B. Analgesia/sedation for the discomfort of pacing","C. Nothing is needed","D. Neuromuscular blockade only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Transcutaneous pacing is uncomfortable due to skeletal muscle contraction; analgesia/sedation should be given if the patient can tolerate it hemodynamically.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q08","question":"Which of the following is a reversible cause of bradycardia that should be actively sought?","options":["A. Beta-blocker toxicity","B. Recent tetanus vaccination","C. Seasonal allergies","D. Mild dehydration only"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Beta-blocker, calcium-channel blocker, and digoxin toxicity, hyperkalemia, hypothyroidism, inferior MI, and increased ICP are all reversible/underlying causes to investigate.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q09","question":"Why is atropine more effective for sinus node dysfunction than for a Mobitz type II block?","options":["A. Atropine works by blocking vagal tone at the SA/AV node, and Mobitz II is an infranodal block not mediated by vagal tone","B. Atropine has no mechanism relevant to bradycardia","C. Mobitz II always resolves spontaneously","D. Atropine only works on wide-QRS rhythms"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Atropine's antivagal mechanism is effective at the SA/AV node level but does not address infranodal conduction disease, which is why escalation is needed for Mobitz II/third-degree block.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c10_q10","question":"A patient becomes hypotensive and confused with a heart rate of 38/min. What is this classified as?","options":["A. Asymptomatic bradycardia","B. Symptomatic (unstable) bradycardia","C. Normal sinus rhythm","D. Tachycardia"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Hypotension and altered mental status with a slow rate meet the definition of symptomatic/unstable bradycardia requiring treatment.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c10_q11","question":"What starting pacing rate is commonly used for transcutaneous pacing?","options":["A. 20-30/min","B. 60-80/min","C. 150-180/min","D. 250/min"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A common starting target for transcutaneous pacing is 60–80/min, titrated to clinical response.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q12","question":"Which statement about dopamine and epinephrine infusions in bradycardia is correct?","options":["A. They must always follow pacing and cannot be started first","B. They are alternative second-line options that may be used instead of or alongside pacing","C. They are first-line before atropine","D. They are contraindicated in bradycardia"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Dopamine and epinephrine infusions are alternative second-line options, useful especially when pacing is unavailable or not tolerated.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q13","question":"A bradycardic patient is found to have severe hyperkalemia. What is an important part of management?","options":["A. Ignore the potassium and only give atropine","B. Treat the hyperkalemia as part of addressing the underlying/reversible cause of bradycardia","C. Withhold all bradycardia treatment until dialysis","D. Give atropine 5 mg immediately"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Bradycardia may be a manifestation of a reversible metabolic cause; treating hyperkalemia directly addresses the underlying problem.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q14","question":"What confirms successful transcutaneous pacing capture?","options":["A. A pacing spike alone on the monitor","B. A paced spike immediately followed by a wide QRS/T wave, with a palpable pulse matching the paced rate","C. Patient verbal report only","D. Any heart rate above 60/min"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Both electrical capture (spike-QRS-T) and mechanical capture (a palpable pulse at the paced rate) must be confirmed.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c10_q15","question":"A patient with symptomatic bradycardia due to suspected calcium-channel blocker overdose is not responding to standard atropine dosing. What is a reasonable next consideration?","options":["A. Continue atropine indefinitely","B. Escalate to pacing/infusion and treat the toxin-specific cause per toxicology guidance in parallel","C. Give more atropine beyond 3 mg total","D. No further action is needed"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Escalation to pacing or infusion should proceed without delay while the reversible toxic cause is addressed in parallel.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c10_q16","question":"Which of these findings would classify bradycardia as symptomatic/unstable?","options":["A. Mild fatigue only","B. Acute heart failure signs","C. Normal blood pressure and clear mentation","D. Rate of 55/min with no symptoms"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Acute heart failure is one of the defined signs of cardiopulmonary compromise that makes bradycardia symptomatic and warrants treatment.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c10_q17","question":"Why should a provider avoid repeatedly re-dosing atropine beyond the maximum in a deteriorating bradycardic patient?","options":["A. Because it has no ceiling effect and is always safe to keep giving","B. Because further doses beyond 3 mg add little benefit and delay effective escalation to pacing/infusion","C. Because atropine is contraindicated in all bradycardia","D. Because it must always be given with epinephrine"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Atropine has a defined maximum total dose of 3 mg; exceeding this without benefit only delays more effective escalation therapy.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c11":{"chapter":"c11","questions":[{"id":"c11_q01","question":"A patient has a heart rate of 180/min, blood pressure 82/50 mmHg, diaphoresis, and confusion. What is the correct immediate action?","options":["A. Give adenosine 6 mg IV","B. Start a diltiazem infusion","C. Immediate synchronized cardioversion","D. Perform a vagal maneuver"],"correct":2,"rationale":"This is unstable tachycardia (hypotension, altered mental status). Immediate synchronized cardioversion is indicated regardless of the rhythm type.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c11_q02","question":"What is the correct adenosine administration technique for stable SVT?","options":["A. 6 mg IV push slowly over 5 minutes","B. 6 mg rapid IV push via a proximal IV port followed by a rapid 20 mL saline flush","C. 12 mg as the initial dose via a distal IV port","D. 6 mg subcutaneously"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Adenosine must be given as a rapid push through a proximal (near-the-heart) IV port followed by a rapid saline flush, because its half-life is only ~6 seconds.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c11_q03","question":"A patient presents with a regular wide-complex tachycardia at 160/min. Blood pressure is 118/72 mmHg. The patient is alert and comfortable. What is the safest approach?","options":["A. Assume SVT with aberrancy and give verapamil","B. Assume VT until proven otherwise and give amiodarone 150 mg IV over 10 minutes","C. Discharge the patient","D. Perform immediate cardioversion at 200 J"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A regular wide-complex tachycardia should be assumed to be VT until proven otherwise. For a stable patient, amiodarone 150 mg IV over 10 minutes is first-line. The patient is stable, so cardioversion is not immediately indicated.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c11_q04","question":"What is the initial synchronized cardioversion energy for atrial fibrillation?","options":["A. 50 J","B. 100 J","C. ≥200 J biphasic","D. 360 J monophasic only"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Atrial fibrillation requires ≥200 J biphasic for the initial synchronized cardioversion shock.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c11_q05","question":"A patient has polymorphic ventricular tachycardia (torsades de pointes). What type of electrical therapy is indicated?","options":["A. Synchronized cardioversion at 100 J","B. Synchronized cardioversion at 200 J","C. Unsynchronized defibrillation","D. Transcutaneous pacing"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Polymorphic VT requires unsynchronized defibrillation because the irregular waveform makes reliable R-wave synchronization impossible. Synchronization is contraindicated.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c11_q06","question":"What is the maximum adenosine dose that can be given for a single SVT episode?","options":["A. 6 mg total","B. 12 mg total","C. 18 mg total (6 + 12)","D. 24 mg total"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The protocol is 6 mg initially, then 12 mg (may be repeated once), for a maximum total of 18 mg in a single episode.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c11_q07","question":"A stable patient has atrial fibrillation with a ventricular rate of 150/min. What is the appropriate initial management?","options":["A. Immediate synchronized cardioversion","B. Rate control with diltiazem, metoprolol, or amiodarone","C. Adenosine 12 mg rapid IV","D. Observation without treatment"],"correct":1,"rationale":"For stable AF with rapid ventricular response, rate control with beta-blockers, calcium-channel blockers, or amiodarone is appropriate.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c11_q08","question":"What is the procainamide dose for stable wide-complex tachycardia?","options":["A. 50 mg IV push","B. 20–50 mg/min IV, maximum cumulative dose 17 mg/kg","C. 150 mg over 10 minutes","D. 1 mg/kg IV bolus"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Procainamide is dosed at 20–50 mg/min IV with a maximum cumulative dose of 17 mg/kg, given slowly with blood pressure monitoring.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c11_q09","question":"Why should adenosine NOT be used for rate control in atrial fibrillation?","options":["A. It is too dangerous","B. Adenosine terminates AV-nodal-dependent reentrant tachycardias, but does not terminate fibrillation; it may be diagnostic to unmask flutter waves","C. It is contraindicated in all tachycardias","D. It only works for wide-complex rhythms"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Adenosine works by transiently blocking AV nodal conduction, which terminates reentrant SVTs dependent on the AV node. It does not terminate atrial fibrillation or flutter, though it can transiently slow the ventricular rate to unmask flutter waves for diagnosis.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c11_q10","question":"What is the initial synchronized cardioversion energy for regular monomorphic ventricular tachycardia with a pulse?","options":["A. 50 J","B. 100 J biphasic","C. 200 J","D. 360 J"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Regular monomorphic VT with a pulse is synchronized cardioverted starting at 100 J biphasic.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c11_q11","question":"A patient with a wide-complex tachycardia becomes hypotensive (BP 74/42) mid-evaluation. What should you do?","options":["A. Continue trying amiodarone","B. Immediately switch to synchronized cardioversion","C. Give more adenosine","D. Wait for cardiology consultation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An unstable patient with tachycardia requires immediate synchronized cardioversion — do not delay for drug therapy.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c11_q12","question":"Which of the following is a common side effect of procainamide that providers must watch for?","options":["A. Hyperkalemia","B. Hypotension","C. Bradycardia","D. Hyperglycemia"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Procainamide commonly causes hypotension, especially when given too rapidly; blood pressure should be monitored throughout infusion.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c11_q13","question":"A patient has a pre-excited atrial fibrillation (WPW with AF). Which drug should be AVOIDED?","options":["A. Procainamide","B. Amiodarone","C. Verapamil (or any AV-nodal blocker)","D. Synchronized cardioversion"],"correct":2,"rationale":"AV-nodal blockers (verapamil, diltiazem, adenosine, digoxin) should be avoided in pre-excited AF because they can increase conduction through the accessory pathway, accelerating the ventricular rate and potentially precipitating VF.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c11_q14","question":"What vagal maneuver is first recommended for stable regular narrow-complex tachycardia?","options":["A. Carotid sinus massage only","B. Modified Valsalva maneuver (or carotid sinus massage)","C. diving reflex with ice water","D. No vagal maneuvers are recommended"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Vagal maneuvers (modified Valsalva, carotid sinus massage) are first-line for stable regular narrow-complex SVT before adenosine.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c11_q15","question":"What drug is specifically indicated for torsades de pointes?","options":["A. Amiodarone","B. Lidocaine","C. Magnesium sulfate 1–2 g IV","D. Epinephrine"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Magnesium sulfate 1–2 g IV is specifically indicated for torsades de pointes (polymorphic VT associated with prolonged QT interval), in addition to unsynchronized defibrillation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c11_q16","question":"A patient with stable SVT does not respond to vagal maneuvers. What is the next step?","options":["A. Synchronized cardioversion","B. Adenosine 6 mg rapid IV push via proximal port with rapid flush","C. Amiodarone 150 mg IV","D. Atropine 1 mg IV"],"correct":1,"rationale":"After failed vagal maneuvers, adenosine 6 mg rapid IV is the next step for stable narrow-complex regular SVT.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c11_q17","question":"What is the lenient rate-control target for atrial fibrillation?","options":["A. Heart rate <60/min","B. Heart rate <80/min","C. Heart rate <110/min","D. Heart rate <130/min"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The lenient rate-control target is resting heart rate <110/min; the strict target is <80/min, applied based on clinical context and symptom control.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c11_q18","question":"A patient is undergoing elective synchronized cardioversion for atrial fibrillation but is awake and distressed. What should be done?","options":["A. Cardiovert immediately without sedation","B. Administer short-acting sedation (e.g., midazolam, etomidate, or propofol) before cardioversion","C. Give general anesthesia","D. Discharge and bring back tomorrow"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Synchronized cardioversion is painful; short-acting sedation should be given to conscious patients before elective cardioversion, provided it does not dangerously delay the procedure.","difficulty":"Medium"}]},"c12":{"chapter":"c12","questions":[{"id":"c12_q01","question":"What is the 2025 first-medical-contact-to-device (FMC2D) time goal for primary PCI in STEMI?","options":["A. ≤60 minutes","B. ≤90 minutes","C. ≤120 minutes","D. ≤180 minutes"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The 2025 ACC/AHA guideline sets the FMC2D goal at ≤90 minutes. Each 30-minute delay increases 1-year mortality by approximately 7.5%.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c12_q02","question":"When is fibrinolysis indicated for STEMI?","options":["A. Symptom onset >12 hours regardless of PCI availability","B. Symptom onset <12 hours AND anticipated PPCI delay >120 minutes","C. Symptom onset <6 hours AND PPCI available within 30 minutes","D. Only as rescue therapy after failed PCI"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Fibrinolysis is indicated when symptom onset is within 12 hours and the anticipated door-to-balloon delay exceeds 120 minutes (e.g., transfer from a non-PCI-capable facility).","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c12_q03","question":"What is the first drug to administer in any ACS presentation?","options":["A. Nitroglycerin 0.4 mg sublingual","B. Heparin 60 U/kg IV bolus","C. Aspirin 162–325 mg chewed","D. Ticagrelor 180 mg PO"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Aspirin 162–325 mg chewed immediately is the universal first drug for all ACS presentations, regardless of subtype.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c12_q04","question":"A 62-year-old man presents with inferior STEMI and hypotension (BP 78/50). What medication is contraindicated?","options":["A. Aspirin 325 mg chewed","B. Sublingual nitroglycerin","C. Heparin IV bolus","D. Ticagrelor loading dose"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Inferior STEMI with hypotension should raise suspicion for right ventricular infarction, in which nitroglycerin is contraindicated because it reduces preload and can cause catastrophic hypotension. Always check V4R before giving nitroglycerin in inferior STEMI.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c12_q05","question":"A patient with chest pain took sildenafil 12 hours ago. Which ACS medication is contraindicated?","options":["A. Aspirin","B. Nitroglycerin","C. Heparin","D. Morphine"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Nitroglycerin is contraindicated within 24 hours of sildenafil (PDE5 inhibitor) use due to risk of severe, life-threatening hypotension from synergistic vasodilation.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c12_q06","question":"When should supplemental oxygen be given to an ACS patient?","options":["A. All ACS patients routinely","B. Only if SpO₂ <90% or respiratory distress is present","C. Only for STEMI patients","D. Only if the patient requests it"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The 2025 guidelines recommend supplemental oxygen ONLY for SpO₂ <90% or respiratory distress. The DETO2X-AMI trial showed no benefit from routine oxygen in normoxic ACS patients and potential harm from coronary vasoconstriction.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c12_q07","question":"Why is morphine use cautioned in ACS management?","options":["A. It causes arrhythmias","B. It delays P2Y12 inhibitor absorption and has no demonstrated mortality benefit","C. It is contraindicated with heparin","D. It causes coronary vasoconstriction"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Morphine may delay gastrointestinal absorption of P2Y12 inhibitors (reducing antiplatelet efficacy), cause hypotension, and has no demonstrated mortality benefit in ACS. It should be reserved for refractory chest pain after nitroglycerin failure.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c12_q08","question":"What is the minimum ST elevation in V2–V3 required for STEMI in a 45-year-old man?","options":["A. ≥1.0 mm","B. ≥1.5 mm","C. ≥2.0 mm","D. ≥2.5 mm"],"correct":2,"rationale":"The threshold is ≥2 mm in precordial leads V2–V3 for men <40 years old, ≥2.5 mm for men ≥40, and ≥1.5 mm for women. For this 45-year-old man, ≥2.0 mm applies.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c12_q09","question":"What is the loading dose of heparin for ACS?","options":["A. 30 U/kg bolus, max 2,000 U","B. 60 U/kg bolus, max 4,000 U, then 12 U/kg/hr","C. 100 U/kg bolus, max 10,000 U, then 18 U/kg/hr","D. 40 U/kg bolus, max 3,000 U, then 10 U/kg/hr"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The standard unfractionated heparin dose for ACS is 60 U/kg IV bolus (max 4,000 U) followed by 12 U/kg/hr infusion.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c12_q10","question":"How much does each 30-minute delay in primary PCI increase 1-year mortality?","options":["A. ~2.5%","B. ~5.0%","C. ~7.5% (relative)","D. ~15%"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Each 30-minute delay in reperfusion increases 1-year mortality by approximately 7.5% relative increase — this is why the FMC2D ≤90-minute goal is critical.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c12_q11","question":"What leads confirm a posterior MI when ST depression is seen in V1–V3?","options":["A. Leads II, III, aVF","B. Leads I, aVL","C. Posterior leads V7–V9 (ST elevation ≥0.5 mm)","D. Right-sided lead V4R"],"correct":2,"rationale":"ST depression in V1–V3 is the reciprocal change of posterior MI; posterior leads V7–V9 should be obtained, with ST elevation ≥0.5 mm confirming the diagnosis.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c12_q12","question":"A patient receives fibrinolysis for STEMI. What indicates successful reperfusion?","options":["A. Pain resolution only","B. ≥50% ST-elevation resolution within 60–90 minutes","C. Elevation of cardiac biomarkers","D. New arrhythmias"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Successful fibrinolysis is evidenced by ≥50% resolution of ST-elevation within 60–90 minutes, accompanied by symptom relief. The patient should then be transferred for early angiography within 3–24 hours.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c12_q13","question":"Which P2Y12 inhibitor is contraindicated with prior stroke/TIA?","options":["A. Ticagrelor","B. Prasugrel","C. Clopidogrel","D. All P2Y12 inhibitors"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Prasugrel is contraindicated in patients with prior ischemic stroke or TIA due to increased risk of intracranial hemorrhage. Ticagrelor and clopidogrel do not carry this contraindication.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c12_q14","question":"When does the clock start for FMC2D time measurement?","options":["A. When the patient arrives at the ED door","B. When first medical contact occurs (prehospital or ED)","C. When the cath lab is activated","D. When the interventional cardiologist is paged"],"correct":1,"rationale":"FMC2D time starts at first medical contact — which can be in the prehospital setting when EMS acquires and transmits a 12-lead ECG. This is distinct from door-to-balloon time.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c12_q15","question":"Which ECG finding is a STEMI-equivalent in the presence of LBBB?","options":["A. Sinus tachycardia with LBBB","B. Concordant ST elevation ≥1 mm (modified Sgarbossa criterion)","C. T-wave inversion in V5–V6","D. First-degree AV block"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Concordant ST elevation ≥1 mm in the setting of LBBB is a modified Sgarbossa criterion indicating STEMI-equivalent. Other criteria include concordant ST depression ≥1 mm in V1–V3 and discordant ST/S ratio ≥0.25.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c12_q16","question":"After successful fibrinolysis for STEMI, when should angiography be performed?","options":["A. Immediately within 1 hour","B. Within 3–24 hours (routine early angiography)","C. Within 48–72 hours","D. Angiography is not needed after successful fibrinolysis"],"correct":1,"rationale":"After successful fibrinolysis, patients should be transferred to a PCI-capable center for routine early angiography within 3–24 hours. Failed fibrinolysis (no ST resolution) warrants immediate rescue PCI.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c12_q17","question":"A patient's 12-lead ECG shows ST depression in V1–V3. Which additional leads should be placed?","options":["A. Right-sided lead V4R only","B. Posterior leads V7–V9","C. Limb leads only","D. No additional leads are needed"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ST depression in V1–V3 is the reciprocal change of posterior MI. Posterior leads V7–V9 should be placed to confirm with ST elevation ≥0.5 mm. V4R is for right ventricular infarction (inferior STEMI).","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c12_q18","question":"What is the maximum dose of IV alteplase used in fibrinolysis for STEMI?","options":["A. 50 mg","B. 75 mg","C. 90 mg","D. 100 mg"],"correct":2,"rationale":"For STEMI fibrinolysis, alteplase is dosed at 1.5 mg/kg (not 0.9 mg/kg as in stroke) with a maximum of 100 mg. The 0.9 mg/kg dose with 90 mg max is the stroke tPA dose — these are different protocols.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c13":{"chapter":"c13","questions":[{"id":"c13_q01","question":"What is the time window for IV thrombolysis (alteplase) in acute ischemic stroke?","options":["A. ≤2 hours","B. ≤3 hours","C. ≤4.5 hours","D. ≤6 hours"],"correct":2,"rationale":"IV tPA (alteplase) is approved for acute ischemic stroke within 4.5 hours of symptom onset, as reaffirmed by the 2025 AHA guidelines.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c13_q02","question":"What is the correct dose and administration of IV tPA for stroke?","options":["A. 0.3 mg/kg, max 30 mg, all as a bolus","B. 0.9 mg/kg, max 90 mg, 10% bolus over 1 min then remainder over 60 min","C. 1.0 mg/kg, max 100 mg, infused over 30 min","D. 0.5 mg/kg, max 50 mg, 50% bolus then 50% over 60 min"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The stroke tPA dose is 0.9 mg/kg IV (max 90 mg), with 10% given as a bolus over 1 minute and the remaining 90% infused over 60 minutes.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c13_q03","question":"What blood pressure must be achieved BEFORE administering tPA for stroke?","options":["A. <140/90 mmHg","B. <160/100 mmHg","C. <185/110 mmHg","D. <200/120 mmHg"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Blood pressure must be <185/110 mmHg before tPA is initiated. Use IV labetalol 10–20 mg or nicardipine infusion to achieve this target.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c13_q04","question":"What blood pressure target must be maintained DURING and AFTER tPA infusion?","options":["A. <160/90 mmHg","B. <180/105 mmHg for at least 24 hours","C. <140/90 mmHg for 48 hours","D. <200/110 mmHg for 12 hours"],"correct":1,"rationale":"During and for at least 24 hours after tPA, blood pressure must be maintained <180/105 mmHg, with approximately 15% reduction in the first 24 hours.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c13_q05","question":"What is the most important stroke mimic to rule out before initiating treatment?","options":["A. Bell's palsy","B. Complex partial seizure","C. Hypoglycemia","D. Migraine with aura"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Hypoglycemia is the most critical and immediately treatable stroke mimic. Always check blood glucose in every suspected stroke presentation.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c13_q06","question":"What is the time window for mechanical thrombectomy in large-vessel occlusion with standard imaging?","options":["A. ≤3 hours","B. ≤6 hours","C. ≤12 hours","D. ≤24 hours"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The standard time window for mechanical thrombectomy is within 6 hours of symptom onset using conventional imaging. Advanced perfusion imaging can extend this to 24 hours in selected patients.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c13_q07","question":"What blood pressure threshold is allowed for a non-tPA stroke candidate in the first 24 hours?","options":["A. <160/100 mmHg","B. <185/110 mmHg","C. Up to 220/120 mmHg if no hemorrhage or cardiac ischemia","D. No permissive hypertension is allowed"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Permissive hypertension up to 220/120 mmHg is allowed in the first 24 hours for non-tPA candidates, provided there is no evidence of intracranial hemorrhage, cardiac ischemia, or aortic dissection.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c13_q08","question":"What imaging must be completed BEFORE administering tPA for stroke?","options":["A. MRI with diffusion-weighted imaging","B. CT angiography of the head and neck","C. Non-contrast CT of the head","D. CT perfusion scan"],"correct":2,"rationale":"A non-contrast CT of the head is mandatory before tPA to exclude intracranial hemorrhage. This is the single most critical imaging step in stroke.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c13_q09","question":"How does Bell's palsy differ from central facial droop seen in stroke?","options":["A. Bell's palsy involves the upper face; stroke spares it","B. Bell's palsy spares the forehead; stroke involves it","C. Bell's palsy affects both sides; stroke is unilateral","D. Bell's palsy affects the forehead and lower face; stroke affects only the upper face"],"correct":3,"rationale":"Bell's palsy (peripheral facial nerve) affects the ENTIRE ipsilateral face including the forehead. Central facial droop (stroke) spares the forehead because the upper face receives bilateral cortical innervation.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c13_q10","question":"Should tPA be withheld while evaluating a patient for mechanical thrombectomy?","options":["A. Yes — always wait for thrombectomy evaluation first","B. No — give tPA immediately if criteria are met; proceed to thrombectomy without delay","C. Yes — tPA and thrombectomy are mutually exclusive","D. Only if thrombectomy is expected within 30 minutes"],"correct":1,"rationale":"tPA should be given immediately if the patient meets criteria. Patients eligible for both tPA and thrombectomy receive tPA first and proceed to thrombectomy without delay — the two treatments are complementary.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c13_q11","question":"What is the approximate rate of neuronal loss in untreated large-vessel ischemic stroke?","options":["A. 100,000 neurons per minute","B. 500,000 neurons per minute","C. 1.9 million neurons per minute","D. 5 million neurons per minute"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Approximately 1.9 million neurons are lost per minute of untreated large-vessel ischemic stroke, underscoring the urgency of 'time is brain.'","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c13_q12","question":"Which drug lowers blood pressure before tPA in stroke?","options":["A. IV nitroglycerin","B. IV labetalol 10–20 mg over 1–2 minutes or nicardipine infusion","C. IV furosemide 40 mg","D. PO amlodipine 10 mg"],"correct":1,"rationale":"IV labetalol 10–20 mg over 1–2 minutes (repeat once) or nicardipine infusion (5 mg/hr, titrate up by 2.5 mg/hr q5–15 min, max 15 mg/hr) are used to lower BP before tPA.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c13_q13","question":"A stroke patient has a glucose of 240 mg/dL. The resident says 'hyperglycemia doesn't matter in stroke.' What is the correct response?","options":["A. The resident is correct — hyperglycemia has no effect on stroke outcomes.","B. The resident is wrong — glucose should be maintained at 70–180 mg/dL; both hypo- and hyperglycemia (>180 mg/dL) worsen stroke outcomes.","C. Only hypoglycemia matters — hyperglycemia is always harmless.","D. Glucose management is not part of acute stroke care."],"correct":1,"rationale":"Glucose should be maintained at 70–180 mg/dL. Both hypoglycemia (<60 mg/dL) and severe hyperglycemia (>180 mg/dL) are associated with worse outcomes in acute ischemic stroke. Insulin should be used for glucose >180 mg/dL.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c13_q14","question":"What should be done with fever in an acute stroke patient?","options":["A. Allow permissive hyperthermia up to 39°C","B. Treat aggressively with antipyretics and cooling — >38°C worsens ischemic brain injury","C. Only treat if temperature exceeds 40°C","D. Fever is beneficial in stroke and should not be treated"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Fever (>38°C) worsens ischemic brain injury and must be treated aggressively and immediately with antipyretics and active cooling measures.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c13_q15","question":"A patient with left MCA syndrome and symptom onset 14 hours ago has CTA showing M1 occlusion. CT perfusion shows a small infarction core with large salvageable penumbra. What is the most appropriate management?","options":["A. No intervention possible — the 4.5-hour tPA and 6-hour thrombectomy windows have closed.","B. Mechanical thrombectomy — advanced perfusion imaging extends eligibility up to 24 hours in selected patients with salvageable penumbra (DAWN/DEFUSE-3 criteria).","C. Transfer to hospice — no treatment options exist beyond 6 hours.","D. Administer tPA regardless of the time window."],"correct":1,"rationale":"CT perfusion showing salvageable penumbra with limited core extends the thrombectomy window to 24 hours per DAWN and DEFUSE-3 trials. This patient has LVO with favorable perfusion profile — thrombectomy is indicated.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c13_q16","question":"A patient has normal facial symmetry, no arm drift, but abnormal speech when repeating a phrase. How many items on the Cincinnati Prehospital Stroke Scale are abnormal, and what does this indicate?","options":["A. Zero abnormal — no stroke concern","B. One abnormal — high probability of stroke; activate stroke response","C. Two abnormal — this is a TIA, not a stroke","D. Three abnormal — the scale is normal"],"correct":1,"rationale":"One of three items (speech) is abnormal. The Cincinnati scale has high positive predictive value when ANY one of the three items is abnormal — this patient has a high probability of stroke and requires immediate stroke activation.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c14":{"chapter":"c14","questions":[{"id":"c14_q01","question":"What is the recommended temperature target after cardiac arrest if TTM is chosen?","options":["A. 28–32°C","B. 30–34°C","C. 32–37.5°C for at least 36 hours","D. 36–37°C (normothermia only)"],"correct":2,"rationale":"If TTM is chosen, the 2025 AHA guidelines recommend selecting and maintaining a constant temperature between 32–37.5°C for at least 36 hours. Maintaining ≤37.5°C is the minimum standard regardless of the TTM approach.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c14_q02","question":"When must neuroprognostication be performed after cardiac arrest?","options":["A. Immediately upon ROSC","B. At 24 hours post-ROSC","C. ≥72 hours after ROSC (or after rewarming)","D. At 7 days post-ROSC"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Neuroprognostication must be deferred to ≥72 hours after ROSC (or after rewarming if TTM was used), to allow clearance of sedation, paralysis, and metabolic derangements that confound the examination.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c14_q03","question":"What is the MAP target after ROSC?","options":["A. ≥50 mmHg","B. ≥65 mmHg (SBP >90 mmHg)","C. ≥80 mmHg","D. ≥100 mmHg"],"correct":1,"rationale":"MAP ≥65 mmHg (SBP >90 mmHg) is the hemodynamic target. Both hypotension (MAP <60) and excessive hypertension (MAP >100) worsen neurological outcomes.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c14_q04","question":"What percentage of cardiac arrest survivors may have STEMI on post-ROSC ECG?","options":["A. 5–10%","B. 25–50%","C. 75–90%","D. STEMI never occurs post-ROSC"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Approximately 25–50% of cardiac arrest survivors have acute STEMI on post-ROSC 12-lead ECG, making immediate ECG acquisition critical.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c14_q05","question":"What is the target ETCO₂ range during normothermic ventilation after ROSC?","options":["A. 25–35 mmHg","B. 35–45 mmHg","C. 45–55 mmHg","D. 50–60 mmHg"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Target ETCO₂ is 35–45 mmHg. Both hyperventilation (ETCO₂ <35) and hypoventilation (ETCO₂ >45) worsen cerebral perfusion after cardiac arrest.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c14_q06","question":"What are the indications for ECPR?","options":["A. All cardiac arrests regardless of cause","B. Selected refractory VF/pVT, low-flow time <60 minutes, reversible cause, suitable candidate","C. Only asystole/PEA arrests","D. All arrests with downtime >30 minutes"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ECPR is indicated for selected refractory cardiac arrest (persistent VF/pVT despite standard ACLS), expected low-flow time <60 minutes, potentially reversible cause, and suitable candidates.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c14_q07","question":"Why should neuroprognostication NOT be performed before 72 hours?","options":["A. Because the brain has not been injured yet","B. Because sedation, paralytics, metabolic derangements, and hypothermia confound the neurological examination","C. Because 72 hours is arbitrary and has no evidence","D. Because EEG is not available before 72 hours"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Multiple factors confound the neurological exam before 72 hours: sedation and paralytics depress consciousness, metabolic derangements alter exam findings, and hypothermia affects neurological function. Early exams are unreliable.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c14_q08","question":"What is the preferred first-line vasopressor for hemodynamic support after ROSC?","options":["A. Phenylephrine","B. Norepinephrine","C. Epinephrine","D. Dopamine"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Norepinephrine (starting 0.1–0.5 mcg/kg/min, titrated to MAP ≥65) is the preferred first-line vasopressor. Dobutamine may be added for myocardial dysfunction.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c14_q09","question":"What is the maximum recommended rewarming rate after TTM?","options":["A. ≤0.1°C per hour","B. ≤0.25°C per hour","C. ≤0.5°C per hour","D. Rapid rewarming is preferred"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Rewarming should be slow and controlled at ≤0.25°C per hour to prevent rebound intracranial hypertension, hemodynamic instability, and metabolic derangements.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c14_q10","question":"What NSE (neuron-specific enolase) level at 48–72 hours suggests poor neurological prognosis?","options":["A. >10 mcg/L","B. >20 mcg/L","C. >33 mcg/L","D. >50 mcg/L"],"correct":2,"rationale":"NSE >33 mcg/L at 48–72 hours post-ROSC is associated with poor neurological outcome, but must be interpreted within the multimodal prognostication framework — no single test is sufficient.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c14_q11","question":"Which clinical examination findings at ≥72 hours post-ROSC suggest poor neurological prognosis?","options":["A. Bilateral pupillary reflexes present, purposeful motor response","B. Bilateral absent pupillary and corneal reflexes with absent motor response to pain","C. Unilateral absent pupillary reflex only","D. Mildly sluggish but present reflexes"],"correct":1,"rationale":"At ≥72 hours, bilateral absent pupillary and corneal reflexes combined with absent motor response to painful stimuli (or extensor posturing) are indicators of poor prognosis — but must be confirmed with multimodal assessment.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c14_q12","question":"What is the minimum temperature standard after cardiac arrest if TTM is NOT chosen?","options":["A. ≤36.0°C","B. ≤37.0°C","C. ≤37.5°C","D. ≤38.0°C"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Even if TTM at 32–37.5°C is not chosen, the minimum standard is maintaining temperature ≤37.5°C with continuous monitoring and immediate treatment of any fever.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c14_q13","question":"What imaging finding on post-arrest CT suggests severe hypoxic-ischemic brain injury?","options":["A. Focal lacunar infarcts","B. Diffuse cerebral edema or loss of gray-white matter differentiation","C. Single small vessel territory infarct","D. Normal CT appearance"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Diffuse cerebral edema or loss of gray-white matter differentiation on CT indicates severe hypoxic-ischemic brain injury and is associated with poor neurological prognosis.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c14_q14","question":"ECPR involves which type of circulatory support?","options":["A. Intra-aortic balloon pump only","B. Veno-arterial ECMO (VA-ECMO) via femoral cannulation","C. Impella left ventricular assist device only","D. Peripheral cardiopulmonary bypass with cardiac cooling"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ECPR typically uses veno-arterial (VA-ECMO) with femoral venous drainage and femoral arterial return, placed percutaneously under ultrasound guidance. A distal perfusion catheter prevents limb ischemia.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c14_q15","question":"What is the ECMO weaning approach?","options":["A. Abrupt discontinuation after 24 hours","B. Gradual reduction guided by echocardiographic recovery, hemodynamic stability, and ETCO₂ trends","C. Weaning is not possible — ECMO is permanent","D. Weaned based on time only, regardless of cardiac function"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Weaning from ECMO is guided by echocardiographic recovery of native cardiac function, hemodynamic stability on decreasing support, and clinical assessment — performed in a monitored setting with resuscitation equipment available.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c14_q16","question":"What does ECPR represent in the treatment pathway — a bridge or a destination therapy?","options":["A. Destination therapy — permanent support","B. A bridge to further therapy (PCI, TTM, native cardiac recovery)","C. An alternative to standard ACLS","D. A last resort with no further treatment options"],"correct":1,"rationale":"ECPR is a bridge — it provides temporary circulatory support while the reversible cause of arrest is identified and treated. It is weaned as native cardiac function recovers.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c14_q17","question":"Which multimodal approach is used for neuroprognostication after cardiac arrest?","options":["A. Clinical exam only","B. Clinical exam + SSEPs + EEG + NSE/S-100B + neuroimaging","C. CT scan only","D. Serum lactate level alone"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Neuroprognostication requires a multimodal approach combining clinical examination, electrophysiology (SSEPs, EEG), serum biomarkers (NSE, S-100B), and neuroimaging (CT/MRI). No single modality is sufficient alone.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c14_q18","question":"When should rehabilitation planning begin for a cardiac arrest survivor?","options":["A. Only after hospital discharge","B. Only after neuroprognostication is complete","C. Early in the ICU with passive range of motion and mobilization; formal referral before discharge","D. Rehabilitation is not part of cardiac arrest care"],"correct":2,"rationale":"Rehabilitation begins early in the ICU with passive range of motion, upright positioning, and mobilization. Formal referral to cardiac rehabilitation, neurorehabilitation, and psychosocial services should be initiated before discharge.","difficulty":"Easy"}]}},"scenarios":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cases":[{"id":"c01_s01","title":"The Eager Intern","presentation":"A code is called on an inpatient ward. Compressions begin immediately and the defibrillator pads are being applied. An intern asks to attempt endotracheal intubation right away, before the first rhythm check.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the correct team-lead response?","options":["A: Allow intubation immediately, pausing compressions as needed.","B: Continue compressions and complete the first rhythm check/shock if indicated; plan the airway attempt to minimize interruption to compressions.","C: Refuse any airway management until ROSC.","D: Stop compressions until the intern is ready."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Advanced airway placement is layered onto, not substituted for, high-quality compressions and early defibrillation. The team should sequence the airway attempt so it does not create a prolonged compression pause.","clinicalPearl":"Protect compression fraction and time-to-shock first — advanced interventions fit around them, not the other way around."},{"id":"c01_s02","title":"Ward Deterioration","presentation":"A patient's early-warning score has been rising for two hours (increasing respiratory rate, new confusion, falling blood pressure) but no rapid-response call has been placed.","vitals":{"hr":118,"bp":"88/54","rr":26,"spo2":"91%","loc":"New confusion"},"question":"What systems-of-care gap does this scenario illustrate?","options":["A: A failure of post-cardiac arrest care","B: A failure to activate the rapid-response/early-warning system that could have prevented arrest","C: A failure of the recovery link","D: A failure of defibrillation timing"],"correct":1,"explanation":"In-hospital systems of care rely on early-warning scores triggering a rapid-response team before deterioration progresses to arrest. This vignette shows the surveillance/prevention system not being used as designed.","clinicalPearl":"IHCA systems win by preventing the arrest, not just responding well to one."},{"id":"c01_s03","title":"Refractory Arrest, Regional System","presentation":"EMS is treating a witnessed VF arrest with ongoing high-quality CPR after three shocks with no ROSC. The regional system includes a cardiac arrest center capable of ECPR, coronary angiography, and temperature management, 12 minutes away, versus a community hospital 4 minutes away without these capabilities.","vitals":{"hr":"Refractory VF","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"Within a systems-of-care framework, what should local protocol support?","options":["A: Automatic transport to the nearest hospital regardless of capability","B: A protocol-driven option to transport appropriate refractory-arrest patients to the regional cardiac arrest center when systems support it","C: Stopping resuscitation because transport time is longer","D: Ignoring hospital capability entirely"],"correct":1,"explanation":"Regionalized cardiac arrest centers, analogous to trauma/stroke systems, are designed to receive refractory-arrest and post-ROSC patients who may benefit from ECPR, PCI, and advanced post-arrest care, when local protocols and transport times support it.","clinicalPearl":"Where a system exists, route the right patient to the right center — capability matters, not just proximity."}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","cases":[{"id":"c02_s01","title":"The Silent Room","presentation":"Ten minutes into a code, the resuscitation room has gone quiet except for the monitor beeps. The team leader realizes no one has spoken up about the current rhythm or plan in over a minute.","vitals":{"hr":"PEA","rr":"Ventilated","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What team dynamics problem does this best illustrate?","options":["A: The team is functioning efficiently with no issues.","B: A breakdown in communication — silence often signals lost situational awareness, not smooth teamwork.","C: The patient has achieved ROSC.","D: Compression quality is guaranteed to be adequate."],"correct":1,"explanation":"A quiet resuscitation is a warning sign, not a reassurance. Active closed-loop communication, frequent reevaluation, and verbalized plans keep the whole team's mental model synchronized; silence often means the team has lost track of the plan.","clinicalPearl":"A quiet code is not a calm code — silence is a red flag for lost situational awareness."},{"id":"c02_s02","title":"Airway Just Placed","presentation":"A supraglottic airway is successfully placed and confirmed during ongoing chest compressions. The rescuer bagging the patient continues to pause compressions every 30 compressions to deliver 2 breaths.","vitals":{"hr":"VF, being treated","rr":"Ventilated via SGA","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What correction should the team leader make?","options":["A: Continue the current 30:2 pattern — it is correct with any airway.","B: Direct the team to continuous compressions with 1 breath every 6 seconds now that the airway is placed.","C: Stop ventilating entirely.","D: Increase breaths to every 2 seconds."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Once an advanced airway (supraglottic or endotracheal) is placed and confirmed, compressions become continuous and breaths are delivered every 6 seconds independent of the compression cycle — 30:2 cycling should stop.","clinicalPearl":"Airway in, cycle out — advanced airway means continuous compressions plus a breath every 6 seconds."},{"id":"c02_s03","title":"The Overlooked Error","presentation":"The team leader orders a second dose of amiodarone, apparently forgetting the first dose was given 2 minutes ago. A pharmacist on the team recognizes the mistake but hesitates, unsure whether to speak up to the attending physician leading the code.","vitals":{"hr":"Refractory VF","rr":"Ventilated","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the correct action?","options":["A: Say nothing since the physician is the team leader.","B: Respectfully and promptly speak up to clarify the dosing history (constructive intervention).","C: Quietly give the dose without comment.","D: Wait until after the code to mention it in private."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Constructive intervention means any team member — regardless of role or hierarchy — should speak up immediately and respectfully when they notice a potential error, to protect patient safety.","clinicalPearl":"Hierarchy should never silence a safety concern — speak up promptly and respectfully."}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","cases":[{"id":"c03_s01","title":"The Displaced Tube","presentation":"During a cardiac arrest resuscitation, an ET tube was placed 3 minutes ago and confirmed with waveform capnography (ETCO2 = 12 mmHg). The team is performing CPR and the capnography waveform suddenly disappears. SpO2 begins to fall from 89% to 72%.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse","rr":"None","spo2":"72%","etco2":"0 mmHg","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the most likely cause and what should the team do?","options":["A: The ET tube has likely become displaced; immediately reposition or replace it while continuing compressions.","B: The capnography sensor is faulty; ignore it and continue ventilating.","C: The patient is improving; continue as-is.","D: Stop compressions to perform a detailed airway assessment."],"correct":0,"explanation":"Sudden loss of capnography waveform with falling SpO2 after confirmed tracheal placement strongly suggests tube displacement or obstruction. The tube must be repositioned or replaced immediately while compressions continue.","clinicalPearl":"Continuous waveform capnography is your early-warning system for tube displacement — treat a lost waveform as an airway emergency."},{"id":"c03_s02","title":"Low ETCO2 Despite Good Technique","presentation":"A patient is in PEA cardiac arrest. The team has been performing high-quality CPR for 5 minutes with an advanced airway in place. The monitor shows continuous waveform capnography with ETCO2 consistently reading 6–8 mmHg. The team lead confirms compressions are at the correct rate (110/min), depth (>2 inches), and full recoil is being achieved.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse","rr":"None","etco2":"7 mmHg","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What should the team investigate next?","options":["A: The capnography is likely inaccurate; recalibrate the sensor.","B: Reassess for reversible causes of low cardiac output during arrest — hypovolemia, tension pneumothorax, massive pulmonary embolism, cardiac tamponade.","C: The ETCO2 of 7 is acceptable; continue as-is.","D: Remove the ET tube and switch to BVM ventilation."],"correct":1,"explanation":"When ETCO2 is persistently below 10 mmHg despite correct compression technique, the team must investigate reversible causes that reduce cardiac output or CO2 delivery, such as hypovolemia, tension pneumothorax, massive PE, or tamponade (the H's and T's).","clinicalPearl":"ETCO2 below 10 mmHg despite correct compressions is a signal to hunt for reversible causes, not just a measure of compression quality."},{"id":"c03_s03","title":"The First-Attempt Failure","presentation":"A code team is managing a VF arrest. Compressions have been ongoing and defibrillation has been performed. An experienced provider attempts ET intubation, but after 12 seconds the tube is not placed. The team lead calls for a pause.","vitals":{"hr":"VF","rr":"None","etco2":"N/A","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the correct next step?","options":["A: Continue the intubation attempt until successful, as the airway must be secured.","B: Return to BVM ventilation and high-quality CPR; reattempt intubation only when conditions are optimized.","C: Abandon the airway entirely and use no ventilation.","D: Insert an ET tube blindly without laryngoscopy."],"correct":1,"explanation":"An intubation attempt exceeding 10 seconds without successful placement should be aborted. The team must return to BVM ventilation and high-quality CPR, optimize conditions (positioning, suction, video laryngoscopy), and reattempt only when ready.","clinicalPearl":"Failed intubation attempts are a leading cause of prolonged compression pauses — always return to BVM and CPR between attempts."}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","cases":[{"id":"c04_s01","title":"The Organized Rhythm Without a Pulse","presentation":"During a resuscitation, the monitor shows a narrow-complex regular rhythm at 55/min with visible P waves preceding each QRS. The compressor pauses for a rhythm check and the team lead announces 'organized rhythm — check for pulse.' No pulse is palpable at the carotid.","vitals":{"hr":"55 (organized, no pulse)","rr":"None","bp":"No pulse","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the correct diagnosis and treatment?","options":["A: ROSC with bradycardia — prepare for post-arrest care.","B: PEA — resume CPR immediately, administer epinephrine, and search for reversible causes.","C: Asystole — begin transcutaneous pacing.","D: Fine VF — defibrillate."],"correct":1,"explanation":"An organized rhythm without a palpable pulse is PEA, regardless of how 'normal' the ECG appears. The treatment is CPR, epinephrine, and a systematic search for reversible causes (H's and T's). Do not assume ROSC from the rhythm alone.","clinicalPearl":"The monitor does not replace your fingers — always check a pulse before concluding ROSC. Organized electrical activity without mechanical output is the hallmark of PEA."},{"id":"c04_s02","title":"Artifact or VF?","presentation":"During transport of a patient in cardiac arrest, the defibrillator monitor suddenly shows a chaotic waveform at a rate that appears to be >300/min. The compressor is actively performing chest compressions. The previous rhythm strip showed organized PEA.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse","rr":"None","bp":"No pulse","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the safest initial approach?","options":["A: Immediately defibrillate at 200J biphasic.","B: Briefly pause compressions for 5–10 seconds to assess the rhythm while maintaining readiness to defibrillate if true VF is confirmed.","C: Ignore the rhythm change and continue the current resuscitation.","D: Obtain a 12-lead ECG before making any decisions."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Motion artifact from compressions during transport can mimic VF. Briefly pausing compressions clarifies the rhythm — true VF persists without compressions while artifact disappears. If the patient is in arrest and VF is confirmed, defibrillate.","clinicalPearl":"Artifact-checking requires only a 5–10 second pause — short enough to maintain compression fraction while preventing unnecessary defibrillation."},{"id":"c04_s03","title":"Wide-Complex Tachycardia: VT or SVT?","presentation":"A 62-year-old with a history of prior anterior MI presents with palpitations and dizziness. The monitor shows a regular wide-complex tachycardia at 190/min. Blood pressure is 84/52 mmHg. No prior ECG is available for comparison.","vitals":{"hr":190,"bp":"84/52","rr":22,"spo2":"94%","loc":"Alert but dizzy"},"question":"What is the most appropriate initial management?","options":["A: Vagal maneuvers to attempt rate control.","B: Adenosine 6 mg IV rapid push.","C: Synchronized cardioversion at 100J.","D: Amiodarone 150 mg IV over 10 minutes."],"correct":2,"explanation":"This patient has a wide-complex tachycardia with hemodynamic instability (hypotension and dizziness) and risk factors for VT (prior MI). Immediate synchronized cardioversion at 100J is indicated regardless of the underlying rhythm.","clinicalPearl":"Prior MI + wide-complex tachycardia + hemodynamic instability = treat as VT and cardiovert. Do not waste time on vagal maneuvers or adenosine when the patient is unstable."}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","cases":[{"id":"c05_s01","title":"The Unknown Defibrillator","presentation":"EMS arrives at a witnessed VF cardiac arrest. They have a biphasic defibrillator, but the specific waveform type and manufacturer-recommended energy are not immediately identifiable on the device. The team must deliver the first shock.","vitals":{"hr":"VF","rr":"None","bp":"No pulse","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the appropriate first-shock energy?","options":["A: 120J because it is the lowest recommended biphasic energy.","B: 360J because all defibrillators need that energy.","C: 200J biphasic, the recommended default when the waveform is unknown.","D: 50J to be conservative and avoid harm."],"correct":2,"explanation":"When the biphasic waveform is unknown, the AHA recommends 200J as a safe default for the first shock. Using 360J on a biphasic defibrillator is unnecessarily high, and using 120J may be insufficient if the waveform requires higher energy.","clinicalPearl":"Unknown biphasic waveform → default to 200J. The AHA explicitly provides this fallback to prevent under- or over-dosing."},{"id":"c05_s02","title":"Polymorphic VT in the ED","presentation":"A 58-year-old patient with known long QT syndrome presents to the ED with syncope. The monitor shows an irregular, wide-complex tachycardia with a 'twisting' QRS axis — polymorphic VT (Torsades de Pointes). The patient has a pulse but is hypotensive (BP 78/42 mmHg).","vitals":{"hr":"Irregular, ~220","bp":"78/42","rr":24,"spo2":"88%","loc":"Confused"},"question":"What is the correct electrical therapy for this rhythm?","options":["A: Synchronized cardioversion starting at 100J.","B: Unsynchronized high-energy defibrillation (120–200J biphasic) because polymorphic VT cannot be reliably synchronized.","C: Transcutaneous pacing at 80 mA.","D: No electrical therapy — treat with magnesium only."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Polymorphic VT has variable, irregular QRS morphology, making reliable R-wave synchronization impossible. Synchronized cardioversion is contraindicated and risks R-on-T VF induction. Unsynchronized defibrillation at standard biphasic energy is correct.","clinicalPearl":"Polymorphic VT = unsynchronized = treat like VF. Do NOT attempt synchronized cardioversion."},{"id":"c05_s03","title":"Bradycardia Resistant to Atropine","presentation":"A 72-year-old with known sick sinus syndrome develops symptomatic bradycardia in the ICU. Heart rate is 32/min, blood pressure is 74/40 mmHg, and the patient is confused and diaphoretic. Atropine 1 mg IV has been given twice without improvement.","vitals":{"hr":32,"bp":"74/40","rr":18,"spo2":"95%","loc":"Confused"},"question":"What is the most appropriate next step?","options":["A: Continue giving atropine up to the 3 mg maximum.","B: Administer epinephrine drip and wait.","C: Initiate transcutaneous pacing starting at 80 mA.","D: Defibrillate the bradycardic rhythm."],"correct":2,"explanation":"After atropine has been ineffective (two doses), transcutaneous pacing is the recommended next step for hemodynamically significant bradycardia. TCP should start at 80 mA and be titrated upward by 10 mA every 2–3 minutes until capture.","clinicalPearl":"Atropine-resistant symptomatic bradycardia → TCP as a bridge to transvenous or permanent pacing. Start at 80 mA, climb by 10, max 200."}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","cases":[{"id":"c06_s01","title":"First-Shock VF","presentation":"A 62-year-old man collapses in a hospital corridor. The code team arrives within 1 minute. BLS is started, defibrillator pads are applied, and the monitor shows coarse ventricular fibrillation. The team has not yet established IV access.","vitals":{"hr":"No pulse — VF","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the priority action?","options":["A: Establish IV access and give epinephrine before shocking","B: Place an advanced airway first","C: Deliver a biphasic defibrillation shock immediately (120–200 J), then resume compressions","D: Perform a pulse check to confirm the rhythm"],"correct":2,"explanation":"VF is a shockable rhythm and immediate defibrillation is the single most important intervention. IV access and airway management are layered in after the shock and during subsequent CPR cycles without delaying or interrupting compressions.","clinicalPearl":"Every minute of delay in defibrillating a shockable rhythm measurably lowers survival — prioritize the shock above all else at the first rhythm check."},{"id":"c06_s02","title":"Refractory VF After Five Shocks","presentation":"A 55-year-old woman with a history of ischemic cardiomyopathy is in refractory VF. She has received five shocks at escalating biphasic energy (150 J, 150 J, 200 J, 200 J, 200 J). Epinephrine 1 mg IV was given after the second shock and repeated after the fourth. Amiodarone 300 mg IV was given after the third shock. VF persists. High-quality CPR has been maintained throughout with CCF >80%.","vitals":{"hr":"Refractory VF","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What antiarrhythmic dose should be given next?","options":["A: Another 300 mg amiodarone IV","B: Lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV","C: Amiodarone 150 mg IV (second dose)","D: Magnesium 1–2 g IV"],"correct":2,"explanation":"After the initial amiodarone 300 mg dose, the second dose is 150 mg IV/IO if VF/pVT persists. You should use one antiarrhythmic consistently rather than switching agents within the same arrest. Magnesium is indicated for torsades de pointes, not standard VF.","clinicalPearl":"Use one antiarrhythmic consistently: amiodarone 300 then 150, or lidocaine 1–1.5 then 0.5–0.75. Don't switch agents mid-arrest."},{"id":"c06_s03","title":"Organized Rhythm After VF Resuscitation","presentation":"After four cycles of CPR and defibrillation for VF, the rhythm check now shows a narrow complex tachycardia at a rate of 110/min. The team pauses for a rhythm check and sees this organized rhythm on the monitor.","vitals":{"hr":110,"loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the correct next step at this rhythm check?","options":["A: Deliver another shock because the patient was previously in VF","B: Check for a pulse; if no pulse, this is PEA and should be treated accordingly","C: Immediately resume compressions without any assessment","D: Administer adenosine 6 mg IV"],"correct":1,"explanation":"When an organized rhythm appears after VF resuscitation, a pulse check is indicated. If a pulse is present, the patient has achieved ROSC and should be managed accordingly. If no pulse is felt, this is PEA, and the PEA/asystole algorithm should be followed (epinephrine, identify and treat H's & T's).","clinicalPearl":"A pulse check is only performed when an organized rhythm appears — never during ongoing VF/pVT. Organized rhythm without a pulse = PEA, not VF."}]},"c07":{"chapter":"c07","cases":[{"id":"c07_s01","title":"Asystole After Massive GI Bleed","presentation":"A 72-year-old man with a history of cirrhosis and esophageal varices is brought to the ED after a massive upper GI bleed. While being triaged, he becomes unresponsive. The monitor shows asystole. IV access is established immediately with an 18-gauge peripheral line.","vitals":{"hr":"Asystole","bp":"No measurable","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the most likely reversible cause, and what is the immediate management?","options":["A: Tension pneumothorax — needle decompression","B: Hypovolemia from massive hemorrhage — high-quality CPR, epinephrine 1 mg IV now, blood products and fluid resuscitation once ROSC achieved","C: Cardiac tamponade — emergent pericardiocentesis","D: Pulmonary embolism — systemic thrombolysis"],"correct":1,"explanation":"Massive hemorrhage in a cirrhotic patient with esophageal varices is a classic cause of hypovolemic cardiac arrest (one of the H's). Management includes high-quality CPR, early epinephrine, and aggressive volume/blood product resuscitation. The arrest is a direct result of inadequate intravascular volume.","clinicalPearl":"Hypovolemia is the most common non-cardiac cause of cardiac arrest. In the setting of active hemorrhage, the cause is obvious — treat it aggressively alongside ACLS measures."},{"id":"c07_s02","title":"PEA After Tension Pneumothorax","presentation":"A 34-year-old man arrives in the ED after a motor vehicle collision with multiple rib fractures. He suddenly decompensates — blood pressure unobtainable, heart rate 50/min on monitor, breath sounds absent on the left, trachea deviated to the right, and distended neck veins. He then arrests into PEA.","vitals":{"hr":50,"bp":"Unobtainable","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive","additional":"Absent left breath sounds, tracheal deviation right, JVD"},"question":"What is the most likely cause of this PEA arrest, and what is the definitive immediate intervention?","options":["A: Cardiac tamponade — pericardiocentesis","B: Tension pneumothorax — immediate needle decompression followed by chest tube insertion","C: Hypovolemia — IV fluid bolus","D: Massive PE — thrombolysis"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The classic triad of absent breath sounds, tracheal deviation, and JVD in a trauma patient with progressive hypotension is pathognomonic for tension pneumothorax (one of the T's). Needle decompression (second intercostal space, midclavicular line, affected side) followed by tube thoracostomy is definitive. This must be recognized and treated during CPR — it is a cause that can be fixed immediately.","clinicalPearl":"Tension pneumothorax is one of the most immediately reversible causes of cardiac arrest. Needle decompression can restore circulation — do not wait for a chest X-ray."},{"id":"c07_s03","title":"Asystole in a Poisoned Patient","presentation":"A 28-year-old woman is brought in after being found unresponsive next to an empty bottle of tricyclic antidepressants. In the ED, she arrests into asystole. She has a wide QRS on the initial ECG before arrest. IV access is established.","vitals":{"hr":"Asystole","bp":"No measurable","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"Which H or T is the most likely cause, and what specific treatment beyond standard ACLS should be prioritized?","options":["A: Hypoxia — increase ventilation","B: Toxins (tricyclic antidepressant overdose) — sodium bicarbonate 1 mEq/kg IV, consider sodium bicarbonate drip, and standard ACLS measures","C: Hypothermia — warming","D: Hyperkalemia — insulin/glucose"],"correct":1,"explanation":"Tricyclic antidepressant (TCA) overdose is a classic toxin-related cause of cardiac arrest (one of the T's). TCAs cause sodium channel blockade leading to wide QRS, bradycardia, and asystole. Sodium bicarbonate (1 mEq/kg IV bolus) is the specific antidote — it overcomes the sodium channel blockade and should be given aggressively alongside standard ACLS measures.","clinicalPearl":"In any arrest of unclear etiology in a young patient, always consider toxins. A wide QRS before arrest in the setting of drug ingestion strongly suggests TCA toxicity — sodium bicarbonate is life-saving."}]},"c08":{"chapter":"c08","cases":[{"id":"c08_s01","title":"Wrong Epinephrine Concentration","presentation":"During a VF cardiac arrest resuscitation, a nurse grabs the wrong epinephrine vial from the code cart. She draws up 1 mL from a 1:1,000 (1 mg/mL) vial instead of the 1:10,000 (0.1 mg/mL) vial, and pushes it IV during compressions. The team continues CPR.","vitals":{"hr":"Refractory VF","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the clinical concern with this error?","options":["A. The dose is too low to have any effect","B. The patient received a 10-fold overdose (10 mg instead of 1 mg) that may cause severe hypertension, tachycardia, and increased myocardial oxygen demand","C. The 1:1,000 concentration has no effect during cardiac arrest","D. There is no difference between the two concentrations"],"correct":1,"explanation":"1:1,000 epinephrine contains 1 mg/mL versus 0.1 mg/mL for 1:10,000. Drawing 1 mL from the wrong vial delivers 10 mg instead of 1 mg — a 10-fold overdose that can cause severe hypertension, increased myocardial oxygen demand, and potentially worsen outcomes. This is why concentration verification is a critical safety step in every code.","clinicalPearl":"Always verify epinephrine concentration: cardiac arrest uses 1:10,000 (0.1 mg/mL). The 1:1,000 concentration is for anaphylaxis and other indications — never for cardiac arrest."},{"id":"c08_s02","title":"Torsades de Pointes Arrest","presentation":"A 68-year-old woman with a history of chronic renal failure and baseline prolonged QT interval is admitted for elective cholecystectomy. In the pre-operative holding area, she suddenly collapses. The monitor shows a rapidly alternating wide-complex rhythm consistent with torsades de pointes, which degenerates into asystole.","vitals":{"hr":"Torsades → Asystole","bp":"Unobtainable","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What specific drug should be given for this arrhythmia?","options":["A. Amiodarone 300 mg IV","B. Sodium bicarbonate 1 mEq/kg IV","C. Magnesium sulfate 1–2 g IV over 5–20 minutes","D. Adenosine 6 mg IV rapid push"],"correct":2,"explanation":"Torsades de pointes (polymorphic VT with prolonged QT) has a specific treatment: magnesium sulfate 1–2 g IV. It stabilizes the cardiac membrane and suppresses the early afterdepolarizations that trigger torsades. Amiodarone can further prolong the QT and worsen torsades. Sodium bicarbonate and adenosine have no role here.","clinicalPearl":"Magnesium for torsades is one of the few 'one drug, one rhythm' associations in ACLS — know it cold. For pulseless torsades, give it as a bolus."},{"id":"c08_s03","title":"TCA Overdose with Arrest","presentation":"A 22-year-old is brought to the ED after being found unresponsive with an empty bottle of amitriptyline (tricyclic antidepressant). Before arresting, the ECG showed a wide QRS (>100 ms) with sinus tachycardia. The patient arrests into asystole. IV access is obtained.","vitals":{"hr":"Asystole","bp":"Unobtainable","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"In addition to standard ACLS (CPR + epinephrine), what specific drug should be given for this toxidrome?","options":["A. Amiodarone 300 mg IV","B. Sodium bicarbonate 1 mEq/kg IV bolus","C. Magnesium 2 g IV","D. Vasopressin 20 IU IV"],"correct":1,"explanation":"Tricyclic antidepressant (TCA) overdose causes sodium channel blockade, leading to wide QRS, bradycardia, and cardiac arrest. Sodium bicarbonate 1 mEq/kg IV is the specific antidote — it overcomes the sodium channel blockade by alkalinizing the serum and increasing sodium availability. Multiple boluses may be needed. This is one of the specific indications for NaHCO₃ in cardiac arrest.","clinicalPearl":"Wide QRS + drug ingestion + asystole = think TCA. Sodium bicarbonate is the life-saving antidote. Repeat boluses as needed until QRS narrows."}]},"c09":{"chapter":"c09","cases":[{"id":"c09_s01","title":"VF Storm in the ICU","presentation":"A 68-year-old man in the ICU develops sudden cardiac arrest. Initial rhythm is ventricular fibrillation. After three shocks at 200 J biphasic with high-quality CPR between each, the rhythm remains VF. Epinephrine 1 mg has been given. The team is preparing a fourth shock.","vitals":{"hr":"Refractory VF","rr":"None (intubated)","spo2":"N/A (arrest)","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the BEST next step before the fourth shock?","options":["A: Shock again at the same 200 J with the same pad placement.","B: Give amiodarone 300 mg IV bolus, reassess CPR quality and ETCO₂, consider vector-change defibrillation, and then shock.","C: Stop CPR and prepare for emergent thoracotomy.","D: Switch to asynchronous pacing."],"correct":1,"explanation":"After ≥3 failed shocks (refractory VF), the provider should give amiodarone 300 mg IV/IO, reassess CPR quality and ETCO₂, consider vector-change defibrillation or DSED, and ensure reversible causes have been addressed — all before the next shock.","clinicalPearl":"Refractory VF is an escalation trigger, not a reason to repeat the same approach faster — drugs, vector change, and quality reassessment are all part of the next step."},{"id":"c09_s02","title":"PEA Arrest with Hidden Cause","presentation":"A 45-year-old woman collapses in the emergency department. CPR is started immediately and the rhythm is PEA. After two rounds of epinephrine and continued CPR, there is no ROSC. Bedroom ultrasound shows a compressing pericardial effusion and a dilated, non-collapsing IVC. Heart sounds are muffled.","vitals":{"hr":"PEA","rr":"None","spo2":"N/A (arrest)","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the most likely reversible cause and the correct intervention?","options":["A: Tension pneumothorax — needle decompression.","B: Cardiac tamponade — emergent pericardiocentesis.","C: Hypovolemia — aggressive fluid bolus.","D: Pulmonary embolism — systemic thrombolysis."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Muffled heart sounds, PEA, compressing pericardial effusion on ultrasound, and a non-collapsing IVC all point to cardiac tamponade. Emergent pericardiocentesis (or thoracotomy) is the definitive treatment.","clinicalPearl":"Bedside ultrasound during PEA arrest is a powerful tool for identifying tamponade, tension pneumothorax, and hypovolemia — use it early when available."},{"id":"c09_s03","title":"Arrest in the Cold","presentation":"EMS brings in a 55-year-old man found unresponsive in a snowbank. Core temperature is 26°C. The rhythm is fine VF. After the first defibrillation attempt, the VF persists. CPR continues and warm IV fluids are started.","vitals":{"hr":"Fine VF","rr":"None","spo2":"N/A","loc":"Unresponsive","temp":"26°C"},"question":"What is the correct management approach for this arrest?","options":["A: Declare futility — the patient is too cold to survive.","B: Continue aggressive resuscitation with CPR, defibrillation, and active rewarming; do not declare futility until core temperature reaches at least 32°C.","C: Give atropine and transcutaneous pace.","D: Transport immediately without further CPR or rewarming."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Hypothermic cardiac arrest requires continued aggressive resuscitation including CPR, defibrillation, and active rewarming. Futility should not be declared until core temperature is at least 32°C, as neurologically intact survival is possible.","clinicalPearl":"Hypothermia is both a cause and a protector — hypothermic patients have been successfully resuscitated after prolonged downtime that would be futile in normothermic patients."}]},"c10":{"chapter":"c10","cases":[{"id":"c10_s01","title":"The Dizzy Elderly Patient","presentation":"A 78-year-old woman presents to the ED with dizziness and near-syncope. She has a history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. On examination, she is alert but pale and diaphoretic.","vitals":{"hr":38,"bp":"78/50","rr":16,"spo2":"97%","loc":"Alert"},"question":"What is the correct initial management?","options":["A: Observe and discharge with follow-up.","B: Atropine 1 mg IV, repeat q3-5 min to max 3 mg; reassess for pacing/infusion if ineffective.","C: Immediate transcutaneous pacing without trying atropine.","D: Start an amiodarone drip."],"correct":1,"explanation":"This is symptomatic bradycardia (hypotension, near-syncope). Atropine 1 mg IV is first-line, repeated every 3–5 minutes to a maximum of 3 mg. Pacing/infusion is reserved for atropine failure or unlikely-to-respond rhythms.","clinicalPearl":"Always determine whether bradycardia is symptomatic before treating — symptoms of instability (hypotension, altered mentation, syncope, chest pain) drive the treatment decision."},{"id":"c10_s02","title":"Atropine Failure in Complete Heart Block","presentation":"A 65-year-old man with a history of coronary artery disease presents with new-onset third-degree AV block. He is confused, diaphoretic, and hypotensive. Atropine 1 mg IV has been given twice (total 2 mg) with no improvement in heart rate or blood pressure.","vitals":{"hr":32,"bp":"70/40","rr":22,"spo2":"94%","loc":"Confused"},"question":"What is the best next step?","options":["A: Give a third dose of atropine 1 mg and wait.","B: Prepare transcutaneous pacing and/or start a dopamine/epinephrine infusion — atropine is unlikely to work for complete heart block.","C: Give adenosine 6 mg rapid IV.","D: Discharge the patient with a cardiology follow-up."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Complete (third-degree) AV block with a wide QRS is infranodal and unlikely to respond to atropine. After 2 mg of atropine has already failed, the priority is to escalate to transcutaneous pacing and/or dopamine/epinephrine infusion without delay.","clinicalPearl":"Atropine's antivagal mechanism works at the SA and AV nodes; infranodal blocks (Mobitz II, complete heart block with wide QRS) are not vagally mediated, making atropine ineffective."},{"id":"c10_s03","title":"Pacing Without a Pulse","presentation":"A 58-year-old woman in symptomatic bradycardia from an inferior MI has transcutaneous pacing pads applied. Pacing is initiated and electrical capture is confirmed on the monitor (paced spikes followed by wide QRS complexes). However, the team cannot feel a pulse at the paced rate.","vitals":{"hr":"Pacing at 70/min (electrical capture)","bp":"60/palp","rr":24,"spo2":"88%","loc":"Lethargic"},"question":"What is the correct interpretation and next action?","options":["A: Pacing is working — continue as is.","B: Electrical capture without mechanical capture — increase the milliamp output, reassess, and consider starting a dopamine/epinephrine infusion in parallel.","C: Turn off the pacer and give atropine.","D: Shock the patient."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Pacing spikes with a QRS but no palpable pulse means electrical capture without mechanical capture. The output should be increased, pad position reassessed, and a dopamine/epinephrine infusion started to support perfusion while pacing capture is being optimized.","clinicalPearl":"Electrical capture is not the goal — mechanical capture (a pulse at the paced rate) is. Always verify by feeling the pulse, not just watching the monitor."}]},"c11":{"chapter":"c11","cases":[{"id":"c11_s01","title":"SVT in the Parking Lot","presentation":"A 32-year-old woman presents to the ED after experiencing sudden-onset palpitations, lightheadedness, and near-syncope in the parking lot. She has no prior cardiac history. On arrival, she is diaphoretic with a rapid, regular heart rate on the monitor.","vitals":{"hr":210,"bp":"84/52","rr":20,"spo2":"98%","loc":"Alert but confused"},"question":"What is the correct initial management?","options":["A: Give adenosine 6 mg and wait for a response.","B: Start a diltiazem drip for rate control.","C: Immediate synchronized cardioversion — this is unstable tachycardia.","D: Perform a carotid sinus massage and observe."],"correct":2,"explanation":"The patient has unstable tachycardia: hypotension (BP 84/52), near-syncope, diaphoresis, and confusion all indicate hemodynamic compromise. Immediate synchronized cardioversion is indicated — do not waste time on drug therapy or vagal maneuvers.","clinicalPearl":"Unstable = shock first, ask questions later. Cardioversion takes seconds; drugs take minutes."},{"id":"c11_s02","title":"The Wide-Complex Dilemma","presentation":"A 58-year-old man with a history of coronary artery disease presents to the ED with palpitations. He is alert, conversational, and in no acute distress. The monitor shows a regular wide-complex tachycardia.","vitals":{"hr":148,"bp":"122/78","rr":18,"spo2":"97%","loc":"Alert"},"question":"What is the correct management approach?","options":["A: Give adenosine 12 mg to determine if it is SVT.","B: Assume VT until proven otherwise; give amiodarone 150 mg IV over 10 minutes since the patient is stable.","C: Immediate synchronized cardioversion at 200 J.","D: Give verapamil for rate control."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Regular wide-complex tachycardia should be assumed VT until proven otherwise, especially in a patient with structural heart disease (coronary artery disease). Since the patient is stable (normal blood pressure, no symptoms of compromise), pharmacologic therapy with amiodarone 150 mg over 10 minutes is appropriate. Verapamil is dangerous if this is VT.","clinicalPearl":"When in doubt, it is VT — treating SVT as VT is less harmful than the reverse. Never give verapamil for an assumed SVT without being certain."},{"id":"c11_s03","title":"Chaotic Rhythm in the Elderly","presentation":"An 82-year-old woman presents to the ED with shortness of breath and palpitations. The ECG shows an irregularly irregular narrow-complex tachycardia with no discernible P waves. She has a history of hypertension and prior stroke.","vitals":{"hr":164,"bp":"102/64","rr":24,"spo2":"93%","loc":"Alert, mild distress"},"question":"What is the most likely rhythm and the appropriate initial management?","options":["A: SVT — give adenosine 6 mg rapid IV.","B: Atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular response — initiate rate control with diltiazem or metoprolol.","C: Polymorphic VT — defibrillate immediately.","D: Atrial flutter — give amiodarone 150 mg over 10 minutes."],"correct":1,"explanation":"The irregularly irregular rhythm with no P waves is classic for atrial fibrillation. The patient is stable (BP 102/64), so rate control with a calcium-channel blocker (diltiazem) or beta-blocker (metoprolol) is appropriate. Adenosine is not effective for AF rate control.","clinicalPearl":"Irregularly irregular + no P waves = AF until proven otherwise. In a stable patient, rate control is the priority; cardioversion is reserved for unstable patients."}]},"c12":{"chapter":"c12","cases":[{"id":"c12_s01","title":"Inferior STEMI with a Twist","presentation":"A 58-year-old man presents to the ED with crushing substernal chest pain radiating to the right arm, diaphoresis, and nausea. 12-lead ECG shows 3 mm ST elevation in leads II, III, and aVF. Blood pressure is 82/50 mmHg, heart rate is 52 bpm. The triage nurse reaches for sublingual nitroglycerin.","vitals":{"hr":52,"bp":"82/50","rr":20,"spo2":"94%","loc":"Alert but in distress"},"question":"What is the most important next step before administering nitroglycerin?","options":["A: Administer nitroglycerin — it is always indicated for chest pain.","B: Obtain right-sided ECG lead V4R to evaluate for right ventricular infarction before giving nitroglycerin.","C: Administer morphine for pain instead.","D: Send the patient directly to the cath lab without any medications."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Inferior STEMI with hypotension is the classic presentation of right ventricular infarction. Right-sided lead V4R must be obtained — ST elevation ≥1 mm confirms RV infarction, which is an absolute contraindication to nitroglycerin because reduced preload can cause catastrophic hypotension in RV-dependent patients.","clinicalPearl":"Always suspect RV infarction in inferior STEMI with hypotension. Get V4R before reaching for nitroglycerin — it could save the patient's life."},{"id":"c12_s02","title":"The Weekend Transfer","presentation":"EMS is transporting a 67-year-old woman from a rural clinic with acute-onset chest pain. Symptom onset was 3 hours ago. The 12-lead ECG transmitted en route shows anterior STEMI. The nearest PCI-capable center is 90 minutes away by ground transport. The community hospital where the patient is currently being treated has a CT scanner but no cath lab capability.","vitals":{"hr":98,"bp":"110/68","rr":22,"spo2":"96%","loc":"Alert"},"question":"What is the most appropriate management given the anticipated PPCI delay?","options":["A: Wait for transfer to PCI center — fibrinolysis is never appropriate.","B: Administer fibrinolysis (onset <12 hours, anticipated PPCI delay >120 min), then transfer to PCI center for early angiography within 3–24 hours.","C: Administer only aspirin and nitroglycerin — no fibrinolysis.","D: Perform coronary angiography at the community hospital."],"correct":1,"explanation":"With symptom onset <12 hours and an anticipated PPCI delay exceeding 120 minutes (90 min transport + cath lab activation), fibrinolysis is indicated. After successful fibrinolysis (≥50% ST resolution at 60–90 min), the patient should be transferred for routine early angiography within 3–24 hours. Failed fibrinolysis warrants rescue PCI.","clinicalPearl":"Fibrinolysis = '12 and 120' — onset within 12 hours AND anticipated PPCI delay >120 minutes. Always follow fibrinolysis with transfer to a PCI center."},{"id":"c12_s03","title":"The Normoxic Patient","presentation":"A 72-year-old man with a history of diabetes and hypertension arrives by EMS with acute chest pain. ECG shows lateral ST depression and T-wave inversions. SpO₂ is 98% on room air. The paramedic wants to place the patient on high-flow oxygen via non-rebreather mask. Troponin is pending.","vitals":{"hr":112,"bp":"138/82","rr":20,"spo2":"98%","loc":"Alert"},"question":"What is the correct management regarding supplemental oxygen?","options":["A: High-flow oxygen is always beneficial in chest pain.","B: No supplemental oxygen — SpO₂ is 98%; routine oxygen in normoxic ACS patients provides no benefit and may cause coronary vasoconstriction.","C: Oxygen is mandatory for all cardiac patients regardless of SpO₂.","D: Only give oxygen if the patient requests it."],"correct":1,"explanation":"The 2025 guidelines recommend supplemental oxygen ONLY for SpO₂ <90% or respiratory distress. The DETO2X-AMI trial demonstrated that routine supplemental oxygen in normoxic ACS patients provides no benefit and may increase coronary vasoconstriction. This patient's SpO₂ is 98% — oxygen is not indicated.","clinicalPearl":"O₂ only <90% — routine oxygen in normoxic ACS patients is not supported by evidence and may worsen coronary perfusion."}]},"c13":{"chapter":"c13","cases":[{"id":"c13_s01","title":"Wake-Up Stroke","presentation":"A 71-year-old woman is brought to the ED by her husband. She was last seen normal at 11:00 PM last night (approximately 7 hours ago). At 6:00 AM, she was found unable to speak clearly and with right-sided weakness. Cincinnati Stroke Scale: facial droop (right), arm drift (right), slurred speech. BP is 178/102 mmHg. Blood glucose is 92 mg/dL. CT head shows no hemorrhage.","vitals":{"hr":88,"bp":"178/102","rr":18,"spo2":"97%","loc":"Alert, expressive aphasia"},"question":"What is the most appropriate next step?","options":["A: Administer IV tPA — all ischemic strokes within 4.5 hours should receive tPA.","B: The 4.5-hour tPA window has passed based on last known normal; obtain CTA to evaluate for large-vessel occlusion and consider thrombectomy if indicated.","C: Start IV labetalol to lower BP immediately regardless of tPA candidacy.","D: Discharge home since symptoms might be a TIA."],"correct":1,"explanation":"The last known normal was 7 hours ago, which exceeds the 4.5-hour tPA window. Standard IV tPA cannot be given. The next step is CT angiography to evaluate for large-vessel occlusion — if LVO is present, mechanical thrombectomy may be considered up to 24 hours with appropriate imaging. Permissive hypertension is appropriate for non-tPA candidates.","clinicalPearl":"Beyond 4.5 hours, tPA is not indicated for standard IV thrombolysis. Thrombectomy may still be an option up to 24 hours with advanced imaging and LVO."},{"id":"c13_s02","title":"The Sugar Problem","presentation":"EMS is called for a 58-year-old man with acute-onset left-sided weakness and difficulty speaking. Onset was 45 minutes ago. Cincinnati Stroke Scale is positive (left facial droop, left arm drift, slurred speech). In the field, the paramedic checks a fingerstick glucose: it reads 38 mg/dL. BP is 168/94 mmHg.","vitals":{"hr":102,"bp":"168/94","rr":20,"spo2":"96%","loc":"Confused"},"question":"What is the correct immediate management?","options":["A: Administer IV tPA — the patient clearly has a stroke.","B: Administer IV dextrose to correct hypoglycemia first; reassess — the deficit may be entirely caused by hypoglycemia (stroke mimic).","C: Lower blood pressure immediately with IV labetalol.","D: Transport without treatment — wait for CT at the hospital."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Hypoglycemia (glucose <50 mg/dL) is the most critical stroke mimic and must be corrected immediately. Severe hypoglycemia can produce lateralizing neurological deficits that closely mimic stroke. After glucose correction, reassess — the deficit may resolve entirely, confirming the diagnosis as hypoglycemic encephalopathy rather than true stroke.","clinicalPearl":"Stroke + low sugar = sugar first. Always check and correct glucose in every suspected stroke before committing to stroke-specific therapy."},{"id":"c13_s03","title":"tPA and Blood Pressure Battle","presentation":"A 65-year-old man arrives at the ED with acute-onset right-sided paralysis and expressive aphasia. Symptom onset was 2 hours ago. CT head shows no hemorrhage. IV tPA is prepared. Initial blood pressure is 192/118 mmHg. IV labetalol 20 mg is administered, and blood pressure rechecks at 188/112 mmHg. A second dose of labetalol 20 mg is given.","vitals":{"hr":96,"bp":"188/112","rr":18,"spo2":"97%","loc":"Alert, right hemiparesis"},"question":"Can tPA be administered at this blood pressure?","options":["A: Yes — tPA can be given at any blood pressure.","B: No — BP must be <185/110 before tPA; continue to lower with labetalol or start nicardipine infusion.","C: Yes — the second labetalol dose was sufficient.","D: Wait 6 hours and try again."],"correct":1,"explanation":"BP must be <185/110 mmHg BEFORE tPA initiation. At 188/112, the target has not been met. Options include additional labetalol (though repeat dosing has limits), starting nicardipine infusion (5 mg/hr, titrate by 2.5 mg/hr q5–15 min, max 15 mg/hr), or using clevidipine. tPA should not be given until BP is controlled.","clinicalPearl":"185/110 before tPA — non-negotiable. Use labetalol or nicardipine to achieve this. Do not give tPA at uncontrolled blood pressure."}]},"c14":{"chapter":"c14","cases":[{"id":"c14_s01","title":"The Post-ROSC Bundle","presentation":"A 55-year-old man is brought to the ED after an out-of-hospital witnessed VF arrest. EMS performed 3 cycles of CPR and defibrillation, achieving ROSC after the third shock. On arrival, he is sedated and intubated. Heart rate is 88 bpm sinus, blood pressure is 84/52 mmHg. Post-ROSC ECG shows ST elevation in leads II, III, and aVF with reciprocal changes.","vitals":{"hr":88,"bp":"84/52","rr":14,"spo2":"98%","loc":"Sedated, intubated"},"question":"What are the TWO most critical immediate interventions in the post-ROSC bundle for this patient?","options":["A: Start therapeutic hypothermia to 33°C and administer tPA.","B: Support hemodynamics with vasopressors (MAP ≥65) AND activate the cath lab for emergent PCI given the STEMI on the post-ROSC ECG.","C: Perform neuroprognostication now and prepare for withdrawal of care.","D: extubate and assess neurological status immediately."],"correct":1,"explanation":"The two priorities are hemodynamic support (norepinephrine to MAP ≥65) and emergent coronary angiography/PCI given STEMI on the post-ROSC ECG (present in ~25–50% of post-arrest patients). Temperature management and neuroprognostication follow but are not the immediate first steps when STEMI is identified.","clinicalPearl":"Always get a 12-lead ECG immediately after ROSC — up to 50% of patients have STEMI and need emergent PCI. Simultaneously support hemodynamics."},{"id":"c14_s02","title":"The Prognostication Timing Trap","presentation":"A 48-year-old woman is 48 hours post-ROSC from a VF arrest. She was cooled to 33°C for 36 hours and is now normothermic. She remains sedated (propofol and fentanyl) and on vecuronium for shivering control. Neurological examination shows no motor response to central and peripheral painful stimuli, no pupillary reflexes, and no corneal reflexes. The family asks: 'Should we withdraw care?'","vitals":{"hr":72,"bp":"108/64","rr":16,"spo2":"99%","loc":"Sedated, no visible response"},"question":"What is the correct response?","options":["A: Yes — the exam is clearly prognostic for poor outcome and care should be withdrawn.","B: No — neuroprognostication must be deferred to ≥72 hours post-ROSC (or after rewarming). Current exam is unreliable due to ongoing sedation and paralytic effects.","C: Yes — 48 hours is sufficient for prognostication after TTM.","D: No — neuroprognostication can never be performed and care should continue indefinitely."],"correct":1,"explanation":"The neurological exam is confounded by sedation (propofol, fentanyl) and paralytic (vecuronium). Neuroprognostication must be deferred to ≥72 hours after ROSC (or after rewarming). All sedation and paralytics should be stopped and allowed to clear before examination. An early poor exam does NOT reliably predict poor outcome.","clinicalPearl":"72 hours minimum, after sedation/paralysis clearance, multimodal assessment — never prognosticate early. Families need to understand that the current exam is not interpretable."},{"id":"c14_s03","title":"ECPR Decision","presentation":"A 42-year-old man with no significant past medical history suffers a witnessed VF arrest at home. EMS arrives in 4 minutes, initiates CPR, and delivers 5 shocks over 15 minutes with persistent refractory VF. He receives epinephrine and amiodarone without ROSC. The receiving hospital has ECPR capability. Low-flow time from CPR initiation to potential ECMO flow is estimated at 25 minutes. The arrest appears to be potentially related to an acute coronary event (witnessed, young, no other obvious cause).","vitals":{"hr":"Refractory VF","rr":"None","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"Is this patient a candidate for ECPR?","options":["A: No — ECPR is only for asystole/PEA arrests.","B: Yes — selected refractory VF/pVT, low-flow time <60 minutes, potentially reversible cause, and suitable candidate.","C: No — ECPR is only for patients >65 years old.","D: No — ECPR has no role in cardiac arrest management."],"correct":1,"explanation":"This patient meets ECPR criteria: refractory VF/pVT despite standard ACLS, expected low-flow time of 25 minutes (<60 minutes threshold), potentially reversible cause (suspected acute coronary event), and a young, previously healthy candidate. ECPR provides temporary VA-ECMO support as a bridge to further therapy (PCI, TTM, recovery).","clinicalPearl":"ECPR is a bridge, not a destination. It buys time for the reversible cause to be treated. The ideal candidate: refractory VF/pVT, low-flow <60 min, reversible cause, suitable candidacy."}]}},"algorithms":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","algorithms":[{"id":"c01_alg01","title":"Universal Chain of Survival (2025) — ACLS Provider View","description":"The six-link universal chain with the ACLS provider's role at each link.","steps":["Link 1 — Activation of emergency response: recognize arrest and activate the resuscitation team/EMS.","Link 2 — High-quality CPR: protect compression rate, depth, recoil, and fraction throughout the resuscitation.","Link 3 — Defibrillation: shock a shockable rhythm as soon as identified; resume compressions immediately.","Link 4 (ACLS provider's primary role) — Advanced resuscitation interventions: advanced airway when indicated, IV/IO access, rhythm-specific drugs and electrical therapy, identify and treat H's & T's.","Link 5 — Post-cardiac arrest care: airway/ventilation, hemodynamic support, 12-lead ECG, temperature control, consider cardiac arrest center transfer.","Link 6 — Recovery: neuroprognostication timeline, rehabilitation, survivor and family support.","System feedback loop: CQI review and Utstein-style data collection feed back into training and protocol updates."]},{"id":"c01_alg02","title":"IHCA Prevention Pathway","description":"How in-hospital systems of care aim to prevent arrest before it happens.","steps":["Continuous or periodic vital-sign monitoring generates an early-warning score.","Rising score triggers a rapid-response/medical emergency team activation.","Team assesses and treats the deteriorating patient at the bedside.","If arrest still occurs, the same team transitions directly into the Chain of Survival response."]}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","algorithms":[{"id":"c02_alg01","title":"Resuscitation Team Roles","description":"Typical defined roles around an ACLS resuscitation, adaptable to team size.","steps":["Team leader: directs the resuscitation, interprets rhythms, assigns tasks by name, maintains the overall plan.","Compressor(s): deliver high-quality compressions, rotate ~every 2 minutes.","Airway/ventilation: manages BVM or advanced airway, delivers breaths at the correct rate.","Medication/IV-IO: establishes access, prepares and administers drugs, confirms doses aloud.","CPR coach / quality monitor: watches rate, depth, recoil, and pause duration; gives real-time feedback.","Recorder/timer: documents times, rhythms, and interventions; tracks the 2-minute cycle.","All roles: use closed-loop communication and speak up via constructive intervention when needed."]},{"id":"c02_alg02","title":"Ventilation Strategy Transition","description":"How ventilation changes the moment an advanced airway is confirmed in place.","steps":["Before advanced airway: 30 compressions : 2 breaths, minimizing pause for breaths.","Advanced airway (SGA or ETT) placed and position confirmed.","Switch to continuous compressions with no pause for ventilation.","Deliver 1 breath every 6 seconds (~10/min), avoiding hyperventilation.","Reassess capnography and compression quality together every ~2 minutes."]}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","algorithms":[{"id":"c03_alg01","title":"Advanced Airway Management During Cardiac Arrest","description":"Decision pathway for securing an advanced airway during CPR, integrating BVM, supraglottic airways, and ET intubation with capnography confirmation.","steps":["Cardiac arrest recognized — begin high-quality CPR with BVM ventilation (one breath every 6 seconds, visible chest rise).","Determine if an advanced airway is indicated and which device to use based on available skill and equipment.","If ET intubation is chosen and an experienced provider is available: perform laryngoscopy (video preferred) during continuous compressions; limit attempt to ≤10 seconds.","If SGA is chosen (or intubation is not immediately feasible): insert i-gel or King LT during continuous compressions (<15 seconds typical).","After device placement, confirm position with waveform capnography.","If waveform is present (characteristic rectangular CO2 waveform): continue CPR with continuous capnography monitoring.","If waveform is absent: assume esophageal placement — remove/replace the device, return to BVM between attempts.","Once advanced airway confirmed: deliver 1 breath every 6 seconds (10 breaths/min) independently of compressions.","Monitor ETCO2 throughout CPR: target ≥10 mmHg for adequate compression quality; sudden sustained rise ≥40 mmHg suggests ROSC.","If ETCO2 drops or waveform disappears: re-check tube/device position, then reassess CPR quality and reversible causes."]},{"id":"c03_alg02","title":"ETCO2-Guided CPR Quality Monitoring","description":"Using continuous waveform capnography to assess and improve CPR quality during cardiac arrest.","image":"../../images/courses/acls/c03_g01.webp","steps":["Advanced airway placed and confirmed — continuous waveform capnography active on monitor.","Measure ETCO2 after each cycle of compressions.","If ETCO2 ≥10 mmHg: compressions are likely generating adequate cardiac output — continue current technique.","If ETCO2 persistently <10 mmHg: systematically reassess CPR quality.","Check compression rate: should be 100–120 compressions per minute.","Check compression depth: at least 2 inches (5 cm) in adults, allow full chest recoil.","Check compression fraction: should be ≥80%.","If CPR quality is adequate, evaluate for reversible causes: hypovolemia, tension pneumothorax, cardiac tamponade, massive pulmonary embolism, severe acidosis.","If ETCO2 suddenly rises to ≥40 mmHg and remains elevated: suspect ROSC — perform manual pulse check.","If pulse is confirmed: transition to post-cardiac arrest care; if no pulse, continue CPR and reassess."]}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","algorithms":[{"id":"c04_alg01","title":"ACLS Cardiac Arrest Rhythm Identification and Treatment Pathway","description":"Systematic approach to identifying and treating the four cardiac arrest rhythms during ACLS resuscitation.","image":"../../images/courses/acls/c04_g01.webp","steps":["Cardiac arrest recognized — begin high-quality CPR and apply defibrillator pads.","At the first opportunity, analyze the cardiac rhythm on the monitor.","RHYTHM IDENTIFICATION:","  → VF: chaotic, disorganized activity with no identifiable QRS complexes → SHOCKABLE","  → Pulseless VT: rapid, regular, wide-complex tachycardia (>150/min) with no pulse → SHOCKABLE","  → Asystole: flat line (no ventricular activity) in at least two leads with proper settings → NON-SHOCKABLE","  → PEA: any organized rhythm (sinus, bradycardia, junctional, etc.) without a palpable pulse → NON-SHOCKABLE","SHOCKABLE PATHWAY (VF / pVT):","  → Defibrillate (biphasic 120–200J; monophasic 360J)","  → Resume CPR immediately for 2 minutes","  → Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO after the second shock","  → Consider amiodarone 300 mg IV (first dose) or lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg for refractory VF/pVT","NON-SHOCKABLE PATHWAY (Asystole / PEA):","  → Continue CPR — do NOT defibrillate","  → Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO as soon as feasible, repeat every 3–5 minutes","  → Systematically identify and treat reversible causes (H's and T's)","After every 2-minute cycle: reanalyze rhythm → treat accordingly","If ROSC achieved (sustained ETCO2 ≥40 mmHg or pulse confirmed): transition to post-arrest care"]},{"id":"c04_alg02","title":"Wide-Complex Tachycardia Evaluation","description":"Approach to evaluating and managing a wide-complex tachycardia during ACLS.","steps":["Wide-complex tachycardia identified on monitor.","STEP 1: Is the patient pulseless?","  → YES: Treat as pulseless VT → Defibrillate (120–200J biphasic) and begin CPR.","  → NO: Patient has a pulse → proceed to STEP 2.","STEP 2: Is the patient hemodynamically unstable? (hypotension, altered mental status, acute heart failure, chest pain)","  → YES: Immediate synchronized cardioversion starting at 100J (monomorphic VT).","  → NO: Proceed to STEP 3.","STEP 3: Attempt vagal maneuvers and adenosine for possible SVT.","  → If responds to adenosine: SVT with aberrancy confirmed.","  → If no response: likely VT → consider amiodarone 150 mg IV over 10 min or procainamide 20–50 mg/min, or synchronized cardioversion.","Clinical features favoring VT: prior MI or structural heart disease, AV dissociation, fusion/capture beats, concordant precordial QRS concordance.","When uncertain: treat as VT — it is the safer assumption."]}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","algorithms":[{"id":"c05_alg01","title":"Electrical Therapy Selection in ACLS","description":"Decision pathway for selecting the appropriate electrical therapy (defibrillation, synchronized cardioversion, or pacing) based on the clinical scenario and rhythm.","steps":["Cardiac arrest or arrhythmia identified — determine clinical context.","Is the patient in cardiac arrest (no pulse, no breathing)?","  → YES: Assess rhythm:","     → VF or pulseless VT → SHOCKABLE: Defibrillate","        → Biphasic: 120–200J (manufacturer's recommendation; if unknown, 200J)","        → Monophasic: 360J","        → Resume CPR for 2 minutes; reassess","     → Asystole or PEA → NON-SHOCKABLE: CPR + epinephrine + treat causes; do NOT defibrillate or cardiovert","  → NO: Patient has a pulse — assess stability:","     → Hemodynamically UNSTABLE (hypotension, altered mental status, chest pain, acute heart failure):","        → Narrow-regular SVT → Synchronized cardioversion at 100J biphasic","        → Monomorphic VT with pulse → Synchronized cardioversion at 100J biphasic","        → Atrial fibrillation/flutter → Synchronized cardioversion at ≥200J biphasic","        → Polymorphic VT → UNSYNCHRONIZED defibrillation at 120–200J biphasic (sync unreliable)","     → Hemodynamically STABLE:","        → Attempt medical therapy first (vagal maneuvers, adenosine for SVT; amiodarone for VT)","        → Consider elective synchronized cardioversion with sedation if medications fail","     → Symptomatic bradycardia refractory to atropine → Transcutaneous pacing (start 80 mA, titrate by 10 mA q2–3 min, max 200 mA)","     → Tachyarrhythmia amenable to overdrive pacing → ATP (pace at 10–20% above tachycardia rate)"]},{"id":"c05_alg02","title":"Transcutaneous Pacing Protocol","description":"Step-by-step protocol for initiating and titrating transcutaneous pacing in adults with hemodynamically significant bradycardia.","image":"../../images/courses/acls/c05_g01.webp","steps":["Hemodynamically significant bradycardia identified (HR <50, symptomatic, hypotensive).","Administer atropine 1 mg IV; repeat q3–5 min up to 3 mg total.","If atropine ineffective → prepare for transcutaneous pacing.","Apply anterior-posterior pacing pads per manufacturer instructions.","Set device to demand (pacer) mode at 80 mA.","Observe monitor for electrical capture (wide QRS complex following each pacer spike).","If no electrical capture after 2–3 minutes → increase current by 10 mA (to 90 mA).","Repeat: increase by 10 mA every 2–3 minutes until electrical capture achieved.","When electrical capture achieved: immediately confirm mechanical capture (palpate pulse with each paced complex).","If mechanical capture confirmed: TCP effective — arrange transvenous pacing or cardiology consultation.","If electrical capture without mechanical capture: continue CPR/resuscitation efforts and escalate to transvenous pacing.","Maximum output: 200 mA — if no capture at 200 mA, TCP has failed → transvenous pacing or cardiology emergency.","Provide sedation/analgesia for conscious patients (TCP is painful).","Continuously monitor rhythm, blood pressure, and patient comfort."]}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","algorithms":[{"id":"c06_alg01","title":"VF/pVT Cardiac Arrest Algorithm","description":"Step-by-step management of ventricular fibrillation and pulseless ventricular tachycardia, from initial rhythm identification through defibrillation, epinephrine, antiarrhythmics, and refractory-arrest considerations.","image":"../../algorithms/ACLS-CA.webp","steps":["Confirm VF or pulseless VT on the cardiac monitor.","Deliver one shock immediately — biphasic 120–200 J (manufacturer-specific or escalating); monophasic 360 J.","Resume chest compressions immediately after the shock — do NOT check a pulse or rhythm first.","Continue high-quality CPR for 2 minutes (rate 100–120/min, depth 2–2.4 in, full recoil, CCF ≥60%).","Perform a rhythm check after ~2 minutes of CPR.","If VF/pVT persists: shock again (equal to or higher energy if biphasic), then immediately resume CPR.","After the second shock (or as soon as reasonably available), administer epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO during ongoing compressions; follow with a saline flush.","Continue 2-minute CPR cycles with rhythm checks, repeating epinephrine every 3–5 minutes.","If VF/pVT persists after epinephrine and continued shocks: administer amiodarone 300 mg IV/IO (first dose) OR lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO during compressions.","If VF/pVT continues: second antiarrhythmic dose — amiodarone 150 mg IV/IO or lidocaine 0.5–0.75 mg/kg IV/IO.","Continue CPR-shock-epinephrine cycles; reassess and treat reversible causes (H's & T's).","If VF/pVT persists after ≥3 shocks with standard therapy: consider refractory-arrest strategies — vector-change defibrillation or dual sequential external defibrillation (DSED), and evaluate ECPR candidacy.","If an organized rhythm appears: check for a pulse — manage as ROSC or PEA as appropriate."]},{"id":"c06_alg02","title":"CPR Quality Optimization During VF/pVT","description":"Key parameters and strategies for maintaining high-quality chest compressions throughout VF/pVT resuscitation.","steps":["Target compression rate: 100–120 compressions per minute.","Target compression depth: 2–2.4 inches (5–6 cm) for adults.","Allow complete chest recoil between compressions — avoid leaning on the chest.","Minimize all interruptions in chest compressions — pre-shock pause should be as brief as possible.","Resume compressions immediately after shock delivery without a pulse or rhythm check.","Switch compressors every ~2 minutes, ideally timed with the rhythm check to avoid adding extra pauses.","Target chest compression fraction (CCF) ≥60%, ideally ≥80%.","Use waveform capnography after advanced airway placement: ETCO₂ 10–20 mmHg during CPR suggests adequate compressions; a sudden sustained rise may indicate ROSC.","Treat reversible causes (H's & T's) concurrently — do not defer while maintaining CPR."]}]},"c07":{"chapter":"c07","algorithms":[{"id":"c07_alg01","title":"Asystole / PEA Cardiac Arrest Algorithm","description":"Step-by-step management of asystole and pulseless electrical activity (PEA), emphasizing nonshockable rhythm management, early epinephrine, and systematic identification and treatment of reversible causes (H's & T's).","image":"../../algorithms/ACLS-CA.webp","steps":["Identify asystole or PEA on the cardiac monitor — confirm on at least two ECG leads.","Immediately begin high-quality CPR: compressions at 100–120/min, depth 2–2.4 in, allow full recoil, with ventilations (bag-valve mask or advanced airway).","Establish IV or IO access as rapidly as possible.","Administer epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000) as soon as feasible — ideally within 3–5 minutes of arrest onset for nonshockable rhythms.","Continue CPR for 2 minutes, then perform a rhythm check.","If asystole or PEA persists: resume CPR, repeat epinephrine every 3–5 minutes, and systematically search for reversible causes (H's & T's).","If an organized rhythm appears: check for a pulse. If pulse present → ROSC pathway. If no pulse → continue as PEA.","If VF/pVT develops: immediately switch to the VF/pVT defibrillation algorithm.","Use waveform capnography (once advanced airway placed) to monitor CPR quality (target ETCO₂ ≥10 mmHg during compressions) and detect ROSC (sudden sustained rise).","Consider mechanical CPR only if manual compressions are impractical or unsafe (prolonged transport, limited personnel, ECPR cannulation).","Continue resuscitation with ongoing cause-directed treatment until ROSC or a decision to terminate is made."]},{"id":"c07_alg02","title":"Systematic H's & T's Reversible Cause Evaluation","description":"A structured approach to identifying and treating the reversible causes of cardiac arrest during asystole/PEA resuscitation.","steps":["H — Hypovolemia: assess for hemorrhage, dehydration. Treat with IV/IO fluid bolus and blood products if hemorrhagic.","H — Hypoxia: ensure adequate ventilation and oxygenation. Check airway patency, confirm advanced airway placement.","H — Hydrogen ion (acidosis): assess ABG. Treat with ventilation optimization; sodium bicarbonate for severe metabolic acidosis or specific indications.","H — Hypo-/Hyperkalemia: check potassium level. Treat hypokalemia with potassium replacement; treat hyperkalemia with calcium, insulin/glucose, sodium bicarbonate.","H — Hypothermia: check core temperature. Treat with warming measures if indicated.","T — Tension pneumothorax: assess breath sounds, tracheal deviation, JVD. Treat with immediate needle decompression → chest tube.","T — Tamponade (cardiac): assess for JVD, muffled heart sounds, pulsus paradoxus. Treat with emergent pericardiocentesis.","T — Toxins: consider drug overdose or poisoning. Treat with specific antidotes when available (e.g., sodium bicarbonate for TCA OD, naloxone for opioids).","T — Thrombosis (pulmonary): consider massive PE — sudden onset, right heart strain, risk factors. Treat with systemic thrombolysis or embolectomy.","T — Thrombosis (coronary): consider acute MI — ECG changes, chest pain history. Treat with emergent PCI when ROSC achieved."]}]},"c08":{"chapter":"c08","algorithms":[{"id":"c08_alg01","title":"Cardiac Arrest Drug Administration Algorithm","description":"Decision framework for selecting and administering the correct drugs based on the cardiac arrest rhythm, including dose, timing, route, and flush protocol.","image":"../../images/courses/acls/c08_g01.webp","steps":["Cardiac arrest confirmed → begin CPR and establish IV/IO access.","Determine rhythm category: Shockable (VF/pVT) or Nonshockable (Asystole/PEA).","SHOCKABLE (VF/pVT): Deliver first shock immediately → resume CPR.","After 2nd shock: Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000), push during compressions, flush with 10–20 mL NS + fluid push. Repeat q3–5 min.","If VF/pVT persists after epinephrine: Amiodarone 300 mg IV/IO (preferred) OR Lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO (alternative). Flush after administration.","If VF/pVT continues: Second antiarrhythmic dose — Amiodarone 150 mg IV/IO or Lidocaine 0.5–0.75 mg/kg IV/IO.","NONSHOCKABLE (Asystole/PEA): Begin CPR + ventilations immediately.","Give Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000) as soon as feasible — ideally within 3–5 min. Repeat q3–5 min.","SYSTEM-SPECIFIC DRUGS: Hyperkalemia → Calcium + Insulin/Glucose + NaHCO₃ 1 mEq/kg. TCA OD → NaHCO₃ 1 mEq/kg. Torsades → Magnesium 1–2 g IV.","ALWAYS: After every drug bolus → 10–20 mL NS flush → IV/IO fluid push. Position extremity if peripheral IV.","NEVER: Use adenosine in any pulseless rhythm. Never use epinephrine 1:1,000. Never dilute amiodarone in normal saline (standard amiodarone must be diluted in D5W)."]}]},"c09":{"chapter":"c09","algorithms":[{"id":"c09_alg01","title":"H's & T's Systematic Arrest Workup","description":"A structured checklist approach to identifying and treating reversible causes during cardiac arrest.","image":"../../images/courses/acls/c09_g01.webp","steps":["Cardiac arrest identified — begin CPR and deliver first defibrillation as indicated.","While CPR continues, team lead initiates H's & T's checklist with one team member assigned to investigate.","Hypovolemia: Check clinical history for hemorrhage, assess IVC on ultrasound, give IV fluids or blood products.","Hypoxia: Confirm advanced airway in place, ensure adequate ventilation with 100% FiO₂, check ETCO₂.","Hydrogen ion (acidosis): Assess ventilation adequacy; address the underlying cause rather than empiric bicarbonate.","Hypo-/Hyperkalemia: Check bedside potassium if available; for hyperkalemia, give calcium chloride, bicarbonate, insulin/glucose, albuterol.","Hypothermia: Measure core temperature; do not declare futility until ≥32°C; active rewarming.","Tension pneumothorax: Assess breath sounds, tracheal position, JVD; decompress if suspected.","Tamponade: Assess heart sounds, JVD; bedside ultrasound; pericardiocentesis if confirmed.","Toxins: Review medication list and clinical context; give specific antidotes when available.","Thrombosis (pulmonary): Consider massive PE — thrombolysis or embolectomy.","Thrombosis (coronary): Consider acute MI — early defibrillation and coronary reperfusion.","Reassess after each 2-minute CPR cycle — new or previously missed reversible causes may emerge.","Document findings and interventions for CQI review."]},{"id":"c09_alg02","title":"Refractory VF/pVT Escalation Pathway","description":"Stepwise management when VF/pVT persists despite standard defibrillation attempts.","steps":["VF/pVT identified → Deliver biphasic shock (200 J) and resume CPR immediately.","After 2 minutes of CPR → rhythm check; still VF/pVT → shock again (200 J), resume CPR.","Give epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO during CPR (as soon as feasible).","After 3rd shock → rhythm check; still VF/pVT → REFRACTORY VF/pVT.","Give amiodarone 300 mg IV/IO bolus (or lidocaine 1–1.5 mg/kg if amiodarone unavailable).","REASSESS CPR quality: rate 100–120/min, depth ≥2 in, full recoil, minimize interruptions, check ETCO₂.","REASSESS compressor: rotate if ≥2 minutes elapsed.","Consider vector-change defibrillation (reposition pads) or DSED (Class 2b).","REASSESS H's & T's: tension pneumo, tamponade, toxins, PE, hypoxia, hypothermia.","Deliver shock (200 J) with antiarrhythmic on board; resume CPR.","If still refractory: consider magnesium 1–2 g IV (polymorphic VT), additional antiarrhythmic, or consider ECPR if available.","Continue cycling: 2 min CPR → rhythm check → shock → reassess, until ROSC or futility criteria met."]}]},"c10":{"chapter":"c10","algorithms":[{"id":"c10_alg01","title":"ACLS Bradycardia With a Pulse Algorithm","description":"Stepwise assessment and management of bradycardia in the adult patient, aligned with the 2025 AHA guidelines.","image":"../../algorithms/ACLS-Bradycardia.webp","steps":["Bradycardia identified on monitor (rate typically <50/min).","Assess for signs of instability: hypotension, acutely altered mental status, signs of shock, ischemic chest discomfort, acute heart failure.","NO instability present → monitor and observe; investigate and treat the underlying cause.","INSTABILITY present → symptomatic bradycardia — begin treatment.","FIRST LINE: Atropine 1 mg IV/IO, repeat every 3–5 minutes, to maximum total dose of 3 mg.","Reassess after each dose: improved heart rate and blood pressure?","Atropine ineffective, maximum dose reached, or block pattern predicts no response (Mobitz II, third-degree block with wide QRS)?","SECOND LINE — choose one or both: Transcutaneous pacing (confirm mechanical capture) AND/OR Dopamine 5–20 mcg/kg/min or Epinephrine 2–10 mcg/min infusion, titrated to response.","Provide analgesia/sedation for conscious patients undergoing transcutaneous pacing.","CONSIDER: Expert consultation and transvenous pacing for refractory cases.","IN PARALLEL: Identify and treat the reversible cause (hypoxia, drugs/toxins, electrolyte disturbance, hypothyroidism, inferior MI, increased ICP)."]}]},"c11":{"chapter":"c11","algorithms":[{"id":"c11_alg01","title":"ACLS Tachycardia With a Pulse Algorithm","description":"Complete decision pathway for adult tachycardia with a pulse, from initial assessment through rhythm-specific treatment.","image":"../../algorithms/ACLS-Tachycardia.webp","steps":["Tachycardia identified (heart rate >100/min with a pulse) on the monitor.","Assess for hemodynamic instability: hypotension (SBP <90), acutely altered mental status, chest pain, acute heart failure, signs of shock.","UNSTABLE → Immediate synchronized cardioversion.","  Sedate if conscious and time permits (midazolam, etomidate, or propofol).","  Energy: 100 J biphasic for regular narrow-complex or regular monomorphic VT.","  Energy: ≥200 J biphasic for atrial fibrillation or atrial flutter.","  If polymorphic VT → UNSYNCHRONIZED defibrillation (synchronization contraindicated).","STABLE → Identify the rhythm category.","  NARROW-COMPLEX, REGULAR (most likely SVT):","    Step 1: Vagal maneuvers (modified Valsalva, carotid sinus massage).","    Step 2: Adenosine 6 mg rapid IV push (proximal port + rapid saline flush).","    Step 3: Adenosine 12 mg (may repeat once).","    Step 4: If still refractory: beta-blocker or calcium-channel blocker.","  NARROW-COMPLEX, IRREGULAR (AF / atrial flutter with variable block):","    Rate control: diltiazem, metoprolol, or amiodarone.","    Target resting HR <110/min (lenient) or <80/min (strict).","    Consider anticoagulation per stroke-risk guidelines.","  WIDE-COMPLEX, REGULAR (assume VT):","    Amiodarone 150 mg IV over 10 minutes (may repeat once).","    Alternative: Procainamide 20–50 mg/min IV.","    If becomes unstable → synchronized cardioversion at 100 J.","  WIDE-COMPLEX, IRREGULAR:","    If polymorphic VT → unsynchronized defibrillation + magnesium 1–2 g IV.","    If pre-excited AF (WPW) → avoid AV-nodal blockers; consider procainamide or cardioversion.","  In parallel: identify and treat reversible causes (hypoxia, electrolytes, toxins, ischemia)."]},{"id":"c11_alg02","title":"Synchronized Cardioversion Quick-Reference","description":"Energy selection and preparation checklist for synchronized cardioversion.","image":"../../algorithms/ACLS-Electrical-Cardioversion.webp","steps":["Confirm tachycardia is UNSTABLE (hypotension, altered mentation, chest pain, heart failure, shock).","Identify the rhythm: narrow vs wide, regular vs irregular.","Set defibrillator to SYNCHRONIZED mode (confirm R-wave tracking).","Select energy based on rhythm: regular narrow (SVT) = 100 J; regular monomorphic VT = 100 J; AF/AFlutter = ≥200 J (biphasic).","Sedate the patient if conscious and time permits (midazolam, etomidate, propofol).","Announce 'synchronized cardioversion — everyone clear' and deliver the shock.","Immediately reassess rhythm, blood pressure, and clinical status.","If rhythm persists: increase energy and repeat, or add antiarrhythmic (amiodarone) between shocks.","EXCEPTION: If the rhythm converts to polymorphic VT, immediately switch to UNSYNCHRONIZED defibrillation.","Post-procedure: monitor, identify and treat reversible causes, continue ACLS if needed."]}]},"c12":{"chapter":"c12","algorithms":[{"id":"c12_alg01","title":"STEMI Reperfusion Decision Pathway","description":"Decision pathway from STEMI identification to reperfusion, including primary PCI and fibrinolysis pathways.","image":"../../images/courses/acls/c12_g01.webp","steps":["Obtain and interpret 12-lead ECG within 10 minutes of first medical contact.","ST elevation or new LBBB consistent with STEMI identified.","Activate cardiac catheterization team immediately — FMC2D goal ≤90 minutes.","Administer aspirin 162–325 mg chewed.","Decision: Is primary PCI achievable within 90 minutes of FMC?","YES → Proceed to primary PCI (door-to-balloon ≤90 min).","NO → Is symptom onset <12 hours AND anticipated PPCI delay >120 minutes?","YES → Administer fibrinolysis (alteplase or tenecteplase): door-to-needle ≤30 min.","  → Assess for ≥50% ST-resolution at 60–90 minutes.","  → Successful → transfer to PCI-capable center for angiography within 3–24 hours.","  → Failed → emergent rescue PCI.","NO → Transfer to PCI-capable center as rapidly as possible; continue medical therapy.","Check right-sided leads V4R if inferior STEMI → if RV infarction, AVOID nitroglycerin.","Administer nitroglycerin for ongoing ischemic pain (CONTRAINDICATED: RV infarction, PDE5 inhibitor use within 24–48 h, SBP <90).","Add P2Y12 inhibitor (ticagrelor 180 mg or prasugrel 60 mg — prasugrel contraindicated with prior stroke/TIA or age ≥75).","Anticoagulate with unfractionated heparin (60 U/kg bolus, max 4,000 U, then 12 U/kg/hr).","Oxygen ONLY if SpO₂ <90%.","Morphine ONLY for refractory pain after nitroglycerin failure (caution: delays P2Y12 absorption)."]},{"id":"c12_alg02","title":"NSTEMI/Unstable Angina Risk-Stratified Management","description":"Risk-stratified approach to NSTEMI and unstable angina using TIMI/GRACE scores to guide timing of invasive strategy.","steps":["Patient presents with ACS symptoms (chest pain, dyspnea) without ST elevation on ECG.","Obtain 12-lead ECG within 10 minutes.","No ST elevation → NSTEMI or unstable angina.","Immediate: aspirin 162–325 mg chewed + P2Y12 inhibitor (ticagrelor/prasugrel) + anticoagulation (heparin).","Risk stratify with TIMI and/or GRACE score.","HIGH RISK (recurrent angina, hemodynamic instability, dynamic ST/T changes, elevated troponin, GRACE >140, TIMI ≥3) → early invasive strategy within 24 hours.","INTERMEDIATE RISK → invasive strategy within 24–72 hours.","LOWER RISK → delayed invasive or ischemia-guided strategy (medical therapy + stress testing if needed).","Continue medical optimization: beta-blocker (if no contraindication), statin, ACE inhibitor as indicated.","Oxygen ONLY if SpO₂ <90%.","Serial troponins and ECGs to assess for evolution."]}]},"c13":{"chapter":"c13","algorithms":[{"id":"c13_alg01","title":"Acute Ischemic Stroke — Prehospital and Emergency Department Management","description":"End-to-end pathway from stroke recognition to reperfusion decision, including IV thrombolysis and thrombectomy.","steps":["Stroke recognized (Cincinnati/FAST positive) — activate stroke alert and notify receiving stroke center.","Check blood glucose immediately.","If glucose <50 mg/dL → administer IV dextrose, reassess (may be stroke mimic).","Acquire 12-lead ECG, vital signs, SpO₂. Maintain airway if needed.","On arrival at stroke center: non-contrast CT head (MANDATORY before any reperfusion therapy).","CT shows intracranial hemorrhage → STOP: no tPA; neurosurgical consultation.","CT shows no hemorrhage, ischemic stroke confirmed or highly suspected.","Determine symptom onset (last known normal time).","Within 4.5-hour window AND no tPA contraindications?","YES → Check BP: must be <185/110 mmHg before tPA.","  → If BP >185/110: IV labetalol 10–20 mg over 1–2 min (repeat once) or nicardipine 5 mg/hr infusion (titrate up).","  → BP <185/110 achieved → Administer tPA: 0.9 mg/kg IV (max 90 mg), 10% bolus over 1 min, remainder over 60 min.","  → Maintain BP <180/105 during and for ≥24 hours after tPA (reduce by ~15% in first 24 h).","Large-vessel occlusion suspected? Obtain CTA head and neck.","LVO confirmed AND onset ≤6 hours (or ≤24 h with perfusion imaging showing penumbra) → proceed to mechanical thrombectomy (do not delay tPA).","Outside 4.5-hour window OR tPA contraindicated → permissive hypertension up to 220/120 (if no hemorrhage/cardiac ischemia); if LVO and within window, thrombectomy.","Maintain normothermia (treat fever >38°C aggressively).","Maintain glucose 70–180 mg/dL.","Admit to stroke unit for continued monitoring and care."]}]},"c14":{"chapter":"c14","algorithms":[{"id":"c14_alg01","title":"Post-ROSC Management Bundle","description":"Comprehensive post-ROSC management pathway from ROSC through neuroprognostication and recovery.","image":"../../algorithms/PCAC-Algorithm-ACLS-PCAC.webp","steps":["ROSC achieved → confirm with waveform capnography (sudden rise in ETCO₂) and pulse check.","Airway management: confirm and secure advanced airway; target ETCO₂ 35–45 mmHg (avoid hypo/hyperventilation).","Hemodynamic support: IV fluid bolus (250–500 mL) + vasopressor (norepinephrine 0.1–0.5 mcg/kg/min) to MAP ≥65 mmHg.","Obtain 12-lead ECG immediately.","  → STEMI identified → emergent coronary angiography + PCI.","  → No STEMI → continue monitoring.","Non-contrast CT head to exclude intracranial hemorrhage.","Initiate temperature management: maintain ≤37.5°C at minimum.","  → If TTM chosen → 32–37.5°C for at least 36 hours.","  → Continuous temperature monitoring (esophageal, bladder, or PA probe).","  → Treat any fever >37.5°C immediately with antipyretics and active cooling.","  → Rewarming (if TTM used): ≤0.25°C per hour.","Identify and treat reversible causes (H's and T's).","Sedation/analgesia for comfort, temperature management, and ventilation.","Continuous monitoring: arterial line, ETCO₂, temperature, telemetry.","Neuroprognostication: DEFERRED to ≥72 hours after ROSC (or after rewarming).","  → Stop sedation and paralytics; allow metabolic clearance.","  → Multimodal assessment: clinical exam + SSEPs + EEG + NSE/S-100B + CT/MRI.","  → No single test is sufficient — use the combination.","Recovery planning: neurorehabilitation, cardiac rehabilitation, psychosocial support, family communication, advance care planning."]},{"id":"c14_alg02","title":"ECPR Patient Selection and Initiation","description":"Decision pathway for extracorporeal CPR candidacy in refractory cardiac arrest.","image":"../../images/courses/acls/c14_g01.webp","steps":["Refractory cardiac arrest: persistent VF/pVT despite standard ACLS (high-quality CPR, ≥3 shocks, epinephrine, amiodarone/lidocaine).","Identify potentially reversible cause: acute MI, PE, myocarditis, drug toxicity, hypothermia, tension pneumothorax.","If no reversible cause identified → continue standard ACLS; consider cessation criteria per institutional protocol.","Reversible cause present → evaluate ECPR candidacy.","Is expected low-flow time <60 minutes? (Time from start of CPR to ECMO flow)","NO → ECPR unlikely to benefit; continue standard ACLS.","YES → Is the patient a suitable candidate? (age, comorbidities, functional status, no absolute contraindications)","NO → continue standard ACLS.","YES → Activate ECPR team.","Rapid femoral cannulation: venous drainage (femoral vein) + arterial return (femoral artery) under ultrasound guidance.","Place distal perfusion catheter to prevent limb ischemia.","Initiate VA-ECMO flow and confirm adequate perfusion.","Continue resuscitation on ECMO support.","Obtain 12-lead ECG → if STEMI → emergent PCI.","Non-contrast CT head → exclude hemorrhage.","Initiate post-ROSC management bundle (airway, hemodynamics, temperature).","Weaning: guided by echocardiographic recovery of native cardiac function, hemodynamic stability on decreasing ECMO flow, and clinical assessment."]}]}},"tables":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","tables":[{"id":"c01_t01","title":"The 2025 Universal Chain of Survival — Six Links (ACLS View)","headers":["Link","Name","Primary Owner","ACLS Provider Action"],"rows":[["1","Activation of emergency response","Bystanders / staff","Confirm activation of resuscitation team"],["2","High-quality CPR","All responders","Protect compression fraction; minimize interruptions"],["3","Defibrillation","First responders / ACLS team","Shock shockable rhythms ASAP; resume compressions immediately"],["4","Advanced resuscitation interventions","ACLS team","Airway, IV/IO, rhythm-specific drugs/electricity, treat H's & T's"],["5","Post-cardiac arrest care","ACLS / critical care / cardiology","Airway/ventilation, hemodynamics, ECG, temperature control"],["6","Recovery","Rehab / hospital / family","Support survivorship; neuroprognostication timeline"]]},{"id":"c01_t02","title":"OHCA vs IHCA Systems of Care","headers":["Feature","Out-of-Hospital (OHCA)","In-Hospital (IHCA)"],"rows":[["Front-end emphasis","Bystander recognition and CPR, public AED","Surveillance and prevention"],["Key early tools","Dispatcher-assisted CPR, EMS response time","Early-warning scores, rapid-response teams"],["Transport decision","May route to regional cardiac arrest center","Not applicable — care escalates in place"],["Goal","Fast CPR and defibrillation before EMS/ACLS arrival","Prevent arrest before it happens"]]}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","tables":[{"id":"c02_t01","title":"CPR Quality Metrics in ACLS","headers":["Metric","Target","Why It Matters"],"rows":[["Rate","100–120/min","Maintains circulation without sacrificing depth"],["Depth","≥2 in (5 cm), ≤2.4 in (6 cm)","Generates adequate blood flow; avoids injury"],["Recoil","Full recoil each compression","Allows the heart to refill between compressions"],["Pause duration","<10 s per interruption","Blood flow falls rapidly when compressions stop"],["Chest compression fraction","≥60%, ideally >80%","Reflects total time actually compressing"],["Compressor switch","~Every 2 minutes","Prevents fatigue-related quality decay"],["Ventilation (advanced airway)","1 breath / 6 s (~10/min)","Avoids over-ventilation reducing cardiac output"]]},{"id":"c02_t02","title":"Core Team Dynamics Elements","headers":["Element","What It Means","Example"],"rows":[["Defined roles","Everyone knows their job before the code starts","Compressor, airway, medications, recorder, coach"],["Closed-loop communication","Order → repeat-back → confirmation","\"Give epi 1 mg\" → \"Giving epi 1 mg\" → \"Epi 1 mg given\""],["Clear/concise messages","Direct, unambiguous language to a named person","\"Sarah, charge to 200 J\" instead of \"someone charge it\""],["Knowing your limitations","Say so before attempting a task beyond your skill","\"I haven't placed an IO before — can you take this?\""],["Constructive intervention","Speak up promptly and respectfully about an error","\"That dose was already given two minutes ago\""],["Reevaluation","Reassess rhythm, pulse, and plan frequently","Rhythm and pulse check every ~2 minutes"],["Mutual respect","Professional tone regardless of role or stress","Calm, non-punitive correction of errors"]]}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","tables":[{"id":"c03_t01","title":"Advanced Airway Options During Cardiac Arrest","headers":["Feature","BVM Ventilation","Supraglottic Airway (i-gel/King LT)","Endotracheal Intubation"],"rows":[["Speed of placement","Immediate","Fast (<15 seconds typical)","Slower (requires laryngoscopy, 10–30 seconds)"],["Skill required","Basic (BLS-level)","Moderate","Advanced (experienced provider)"],["Aspiration protection","Minimal","Partial","Complete (cuffed tube)"],["Ventilation reliability","Variable (mask seal dependent)","Good seal, consistent","Most reliable, definitive"],["Compression interruption","Minimal (continuous compressions)","Minimal","Risk of prolonged pause"],["Confirmation method","Chest rise, auscultation","Waveform capnography required","Waveform capnography (gold standard)"],["Recommended use in arrest","Initial/bridge airway","When intubation not immediately feasible","When experienced provider can do it without prolonged pause"]]},{"id":"c03_t02","title":"ETCO2 Interpretation During Cardiac Arrest","headers":["ETCO2 Value","Interpretation","Clinical Action"],"rows":[["≥10 mmHg during CPR","Adequate compression quality","Continue current CPR technique"],["<10 mmHg persistently","Inadequate cardiac output from compressions","Reassess rate, depth, recoil, fraction; evaluate for reversible causes"],["Sudden rise to ≥40 mmHg","Possible ROSC","Perform manual pulse check; if pulse present, transition to post-arrest care"],["Absent waveform after intubation","Esophageal tube placement or tube displacement","Reposition or replace tube; confirm with capnography"],["Progressive decline during CPR","Worsening compression quality or deteriorating condition","Reassess CPR technique and evaluate for new reversible cause"],["Consistently >60 mmHg during arrest","May indicate prolonged arrest with CO2 retention","Consider adequacy of ventilation; evaluate for ROSC if trending upward"]]},{"id":"c03_t03","title":"Supraglottic Airway Comparison: i-gel vs King LT","headers":["Feature","i-gel","King LT / King LTS-D"],"rows":[["Seal mechanism","Non-inflatable gel-filled cushion","Inflatable proximal and distal cuffs"],["Lumen design","Single lumen with integrated gastric channel","Dual-lumen (airway and esophageal)"],["Cuff inflation required","No","Yes (self-inflating pilot balloon)"],["Gastric access","Integrated gastric channel for decompression","Distal cuff seals esophagus; separate gastric access with LTS-D"],["Typical insertion time","<15 seconds","<15 seconds"],["Reusable / disposable","Single-use","Reusable or single-use depending on model"],["Size range","Sizes 1–5 (by patient weight)","Sizes 3–5 (by patient height)"]]}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","tables":[{"id":"c04_t01","title":"ACLS Cardiac Arrest Rhythm Comparison","headers":["Rhythm","ECG Appearance","Pulse","Shockable?","Initial Treatment"],"rows":[["Ventricular fibrillation (VF)","Chaotic, disorganized; no identifiable QRS","None","Yes","Defibrillate (120–200J biphasic) + CPR"],["Pulseless VT","Rapid, regular, wide-complex (>150/min)","None","Yes","Defibrillate (120–200J biphasic) + CPR"],["Asystole","Flat line; no ventricular activity in ≥2 leads","None","No","CPR + epinephrine q3–5 min + treat causes"],["PEA","Organized rhythm (any morphology) without pulse","None","No","CPR + epinephrine q3–5 min + treat H's & T's"]]},{"id":"c04_t02","title":"VT with Pulse vs SVT with Aberrancy: Distinguishing Features","headers":["Feature","Favors VT","Favors SVT with Aberrancy"],"rows":[["History","Prior MI, structural heart disease, cardiomyopathy","No structural heart disease"],["Hemodynamics","Often unstable","Often stable (until very fast)"],["AV dissociation","Present (independent P and QRS)","Absent (1:1 AV relationship)"],["Fusion/capture beats","May be present","Absent"],["Precordial concordance","Positive or negative concordance V1–V6","Variable"],["QRS width","Very wide (≥160 ms typical)","Wide but <160 ms typical"],["Response to adenosine","No response","May terminate or slow"]]},{"id":"c04_t03","title":"Common Reversible Causes of PEA (H's and T's)","headers":["Category","Cause","Key Finding"],"rows":[["H's","Hypovolemia","Flat neck veins, poor urine output, known bleeding"],["H's","Hypoxia","Low SpO2, cyanosis, known respiratory failure"],["H's","Hydrogen ion (acidosis)","Low pH, known DKA or renal failure"],["H's","Hypo/hyperkalemia","ECG changes, known CKD, medication history"],["H's","Hypothermia","Low core temperature, environmental exposure"],["T's","Tension pneumothorax","Absent breath sounds unilaterally, tracheal deviation, hypotension"],["T's","Tamponade (cardiac)","Beats on echo, muffled heart sounds, JVD, hypotension"],["T's","Toxins (drug overdose)","Pupillary findings, known ingestion, toxidrome"],["T's","Thrombosis (coronary)","STEMI on ECG, chest pain history"],["T's","Thrombosis (pulmonary)","S1Q3T3, right heart strain, sudden dyspnea, DVT risk factors"]]}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","tables":[{"id":"c05_t01","title":"Defibrillation and Cardioversion Energy Selection by Rhythm (Adults, Biphasic)","headers":["Rhythm","Synchronization","Initial Energy (Biphasic)","Monophasic Alternative"],"rows":[["VF","Unsynchronized (defibrillation)","120–200J (use manufacturer's recommendation; if unknown, 200J)","360J"],["Pulseless VT","Unsynchronized (defibrillation)","120–200J (use manufacturer's recommendation; if unknown, 200J)","360J"],["Polymorphic VT (with pulse)","Unsynchronized (defibrillation)","120–200J","360J"],["Monomorphic VT (with pulse)","Synchronized (cardioversion)","100J","100J"],["Atrial fibrillation","Synchronized (cardioversion)","≥200J","200J"],["Atrial flutter","Synchronized (cardioversion)","≥200J","200J"],["Narrow-regular SVT","Synchronized (cardioversion)","100J","50–100J"]]},{"id":"c05_t02","title":"Transcutaneous Pacing Parameters","headers":["Parameter","Value","Notes"],"rows":[["Starting current","80 mA","Begin at 80 mA after atropine failure"],["Titration increment","10 mA","Increase every 2–3 minutes until capture"],["Maximum output (adults)","200 mA","If no capture at 200 mA, TCP has failed"],["Pacer mode","Demand (asynchronous not preferred)","Delivers pacer spikes only when intrinsic rate falls below set rate"],["Target rate","60–80/min typical","Set slightly above intrinsic rate"],["Pad placement","Anterior-posterior","Per manufacturer instructions; anterior-left chest, posterior-left scapula"],["Confirmation","Electrical + mechanical capture","Always palpate pulse — electrical capture does not guarantee mechanical capture"],["Patient comfort","Sedation/analgesia required","TCP is painful; provide midazolam, propofol, or ketamine per protocol"]]},{"id":"c05_t03","title":"Synchronized vs Unsynchronized Electrical Therapy","headers":["Feature","Synchronized Cardioversion","Unsynchronized Defibrillation"],"rows":[["R-wave synchronization","Yes — shock delivered on R wave","No — shock delivered immediately"],["Indications","Stable/unstable tachycardias with pulse (AF, SVT, monomorphic VT)","VF, pulseless VT, polymorphic VT"],["Patient state","May be conscious (requires sedation)","Typically unconscious/arrested"],["Risk of R-on-T","Minimized by synchronization","Present — acceptable because no perfusing rhythm to lose"],["Energy selection","Rhythm-specific (100–200J biphasic)","Standard defibrillation energy (120–200J biphasic)"],["When sync fails","If R wave cannot be reliably detected, switch to unsynchronized","N/A — already unsynchronized"]]}]},"c06":{"chapter":"c06","tables":[{"id":"c06_t01","title":"Defibrillation Energy: Biphasic vs Monophasic","headers":["Waveform","First Shock","Subsequent Shocks","Notes"],"rows":[["Biphasic","120–200 J (manufacturer-specific)","Same or higher energy (escalating)","If biphasic energy unknown, use 200 J"],["Monophasic","360 J","360 J","Fixed energy for all shocks"]]},{"id":"c06_t02","title":"Antiarrhythmic Drugs for Refractory VF/pVT","headers":["Drug","First Dose","Second Dose","Route","Key Notes"],"rows":[["Amiodarone","300 mg IV/IO","150 mg IV/IO","IV/IO bolus","Preferred antiarrhythmic; use consistently"],["Lidocaine","1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO","0.5–0.75 mg/kg IV/IO","IV/IO bolus","Alternative to amiodarone; do not alternate agents within same arrest"]]},{"id":"c06_t03","title":"VF/pVT Resuscitation Drug & Procedure Timing","headers":["Intervention","Timing","Dose","Notes"],"rows":[["Defibrillation (biphasic)","Immediately on rhythm identification","120–200 J","Escalate energy if refractory"],["Defibrillation (monophasic)","Immediately on rhythm identification","360 J","Fixed energy"],["Epinephrine","After ~2nd shock (as soon as feasible), then q3–5 min","1 mg IV/IO (1:10,000)","Push during compressions; saline flush after"],["Amiodarone (first dose)","After epinephrine if VF/pVT persists","300 mg IV/IO","Push during compressions"],["Amiodarone (second dose)","If VF/pVT continues after first dose","150 mg IV/IO","Push during compressions"],["Lidocaine (first dose)","Alternative to amiodarone","1–1.5 mg/kg IV/IO","Push during compressions"],["Lidocaine (second dose)","If VF/pVT continues","0.5–0.75 mg/kg IV/IO","Push during compressions"]]}]},"c07":{"chapter":"c07","tables":[{"id":"c07_t01","title":"The H's and T's of Reversible Causes","headers":["Category","Reversible Cause","Key Clinical Clues","Specific Treatment"],"rows":[["H","Hypovolemia","Hemorrhage, dehydration, poor skin turgor, flat neck veins","IV/IO fluid bolus, blood products"],["H","Hypoxia","Cyanosis, low SpO₂, inadequate ventilation","Oxygen, ensure airway patency, advanced airway"],["H","Hydrogen ion (acidosis)","Known metabolic acidosis, pH <7.1","Ventilation optimization, sodium bicarbonate if indicated"],["H","Hypo-/Hyperkalemia","Known renal failure, ECG changes (peaked T waves or flat T/U waves)","K⁺ replacement (hypo) or calcium + insulin/glucose (hyper)"],["H","Hypothermia","Core temp <35°C, cold exposure","Passive/active rewarming"],["T","Tension pneumothorax","Absent breath sounds, tracheal deviation, JVD, hypotension","Needle decompression → chest tube"],["T","Tamponade (cardiac)","JVD, muffled heart sounds, pulsus paradoxus, hypotension","Emergent pericardiocardiocentesis"],["T","Toxins","Drug ingestion history, wide QRS (TCA), pill bottles at scene","Specific antidotes (NaHCO₃ for TCA, naloxone for opioids)"],["T","Thrombosis (pulmonary)","Sudden dyspnea, pleuritic pain, right heart strain, DVT risk factors","Systemic thrombolysis, embolectomy"],["T","Thrombosis (coronary)","Chest pain, ST changes, known CAD, ACS history","Emergent PCI after ROSC"]]},{"id":"c07_t02","title":"Asystole/PEA vs VF/pVT: Key Differences","headers":["Feature","Asystole / PEA (Nonshockable)","VF / pVT (Shockable)"],"rows":[["Defibrillation","NOT indicated","First and most important intervention"],["Epinephrine timing","As soon as feasible, ideally within 3–5 min","After ~2nd shock, then q3–5 min"],["Primary treatment focus","CPR + identify/treat H's & T's","CPR + defibrillation + antiarrhythmics"],["Antiarrhythmics","Not routinely used","Amiodarone or lidocaine for refractory cases"],["Prognosis (typical)","Lower survival rates","Higher survival if defibrillated early"],["Mechanical CPR role","May be considered if manual impractical","Same — not routine but considered in specific circumstances"]]}]},"c08":{"chapter":"c08","tables":[{"id":"c08_t01","title":"Cardiac Arrest Drug Reference — Doses, Indications, and Key Facts","headers":["Drug","Dose","Route","Indication","Key Facts"],"rows":[["Epinephrine","1 mg every 3–5 min","IV/IO","All cardiac arrest rhythms","1:10,000 concentration (0.1 mg/mL); alpha-adrenergic ↑ coronary perfusion"],["Amiodarone","300 mg first dose; 150 mg second dose","IV/IO bolus","Refractory VF/pVT","Preferred antiarrhythmic; dilute in NS (NOT D5W); Class I/III/IV properties"],["Lidocaine","1–1.5 mg/kg first dose; 0.5–0.75 mg/kg subsequent","IV/IO bolus","Refractory VF/pVT (alternative)","Preferred in acute ischemia/MI; Class Ib antiarrhythmic"],["Sodium bicarbonate","1 mEq/kg IV","IV","Hyperkalemia, TCA OD, bicarbonate-responsive acidosis only","NOT routine; risk of hypernatremia and paradoxical acidosis"],["Magnesium sulfate","1–2 g IV over 5–20 min","IV","Torsades de pointes","NOT for ordinary VF/pVT; stabilizes membrane in prolonged QT"],["Vasopressin","20 IU (single dose)","IV/IO","May replace 1st or 2nd epi dose","No advantage over epi alone; epinephrine preferred"],["Adenosine","6 mg → 12 mg","IV rapid push","SVT with a pulse ONLY","NEVER in pulseless arrest; 6-sec half-life; needs pulse to reach heart"]]},{"id":"c08_t02","title":"IV vs IO Access During Cardiac Arrest","headers":["Feature","IV Access","IO Access"],"rows":[["Preferred?","First-line","Reasonable when IV not quickly obtainable"],["Speed to establish","Dependent on patient factors (veins, edema, arrest)","Fast — can be placed in most locations within 1–2 min"],["Drug bioavailability","Gold standard","Comparable to IV — drugs reach central circulation"],["Best suited for","All patients when obtainable","Difficult IV access, obese patients, cardiac arrest"],["Catheter size","18–20 gauge peripheral","15–18 gauge intraosseous needle"],["Drug flush","10–20 mL NS + fluid push","10–20 mL NS + fluid push"]]},{"id":"c08_t03","title":"Drugs NOT Indicated in Cardiac Arrest","headers":["Drug","Why NOT Used in Arrest","Correct Indication"],"rows":[["Adenosine","Half-life of 6 seconds; requires pulse to reach heart; no effect on VF/pVT/asystole/PEA","Regular narrow-complex SVT with a pulse"],["Atropine","No longer recommended for cardiac arrest (removed from ACLS algorithms)","Symptomatic bradycardia with a pulse (1 mg IV q3–5 min, max 3 mg)"],["Epinephrine 1:1,000","Wrong concentration — 10× overdose risk","Anaphylaxis (0.3–0.5 mg IM); use 1:10,000 for arrest"],["Calcium chloride (routine)","No routine role in cardiac arrest","Hyperkalemia, calcium channel blocker OD, hypermagnesemia"]]}]},"c09":{"chapter":"c09","tables":[{"id":"c09_t01","title":"The H's and T's — Reversible Causes of Cardiac Arrest","headers":["Category","Cause","Key Finding / Test","Initial Treatment"],"rows":[["H","Hypovolemia","Flat IVC on US, hemorrhage history, dehydration","IV fluids or blood products"],["H","Hypoxia","Low SpO₂, inadequate ventilation","Ensure advanced airway, 100% O₂, confirm ETCO₂"],["H","Hydrogen ion (acidosis)","Low pH on blood gas, prolonged arrest","Improve ventilation; treat the cause; avoid empiric bicarb"],["H","Hypo-/Hyperkalemia","ECG changes (peaked T / wide QRS for hyperkalemia)","Ca²⁺, bicarb, insulin/glucose, albuterol for hyperkalemia"],["H","Hypothermia","Core temp <35°C, cold exposure","Active rewarming; do not stop until ≥32°C"],["T","Tension pneumothorax","Absent breath sounds, tracheal deviation, JVD","Needle decompression → chest tube"],["T","Tamponade","Muffled heart sounds, JVD, pulsus paradoxus, US effusion","Pericardiocentesis"],["T","Toxins","Medication history, toxidrome findings","Specific antidotes (Fab for digoxin, intralipid, etc.)"],["T","Thrombosis (pulmonary)","DVT risk factors, RV strain on US, PE history","Thrombolysis or embolectomy"],["T","Thrombosis (coronary)","Acute MI on ECG, ischemic changes","Defibrillation, emergent PCI"]]},{"id":"c09_t02","title":"Antiarrhythmic Drugs for Refractory VF/pVT","headers":["Drug","Dose","Route","Repeat Dose","Notes"],"rows":[["Amiodarone (1st dose)","300 mg","IV/IO bolus","150 mg once if needed","First-line antiarrhythmic for refractory VF/pVT"],["Lidocaine","1–1.5 mg/kg","IV/IO bolus","0.5–0.75 mg/kg up to 3 mg/kg total","Alternative if amiodarone unavailable"],["Magnesium sulfate","1–2 g","IV/IO","May repeat for torsades","Specifically for polymorphic VT (torsades de pointes)"],["Epinephrine","1 mg","IV/IO","Every 3–5 min","Give as soon as feasible for all arrest rhythms"]]},{"id":"c09_t03","title":"Defibrillation Strategies for Refractory VF/pVT","headers":["Strategy","Description","AHA Class / LOE","When to Consider"],"rows":[["Standard biphasic","200 J via standard anterolateral or anterior-posterior pads","Class 1","First-line for all VF/pVT"],["Vector-change defibrillation","Reposition pads to alter current path through myocardium","Class 2b / B-R","After ≥3 failed shocks with standard placement"],["DSED","Two defibrillators, asynchronous rapid succession, different pad positions","Class 2b / B-R","Selective; after ≥3 failed shocks when available"],["Escalating biphasic","Increase energy on successive shocks (manufacturer-dependent)","Class 2a","Follows device manufacturer protocol"]]}]},"c10":{"chapter":"c10","tables":[{"id":"c10_t01","title":"Atropine Dosing for Symptomatic Bradycardia","headers":["Parameter","Value","Notes"],"rows":[["Dose per administration","1 mg IV or IO","Single bolus injection"],["Repeat interval","Every 3–5 minutes","Reassess after each dose"],["Maximum total dose","3 mg total","Do not exceed — escalate to pacing/infusion"],["Mechanism","Anticholinergic (vagolytic)","Blocks vagal tone at SA and AV nodes"],["Most effective for","Sinus node dysfunction, low-grade AV block","Supra-Hisian / vagally-mediated bradycardia"],["Least effective for","Mobitz II, third-degree block (wide QRS)","Infranodal blocks are not vagally mediated"]]},{"id":"c10_t02","title":"Transcutaneous Pacing Parameters","headers":["Parameter","Starting Value","Titration","Maximum"],"rows":[["Rate","60–80/min","Titrate to clinical response","Per patient need"],["Output (current)","Start at 80 mA","Increase by 10 mA q2-3 min","200 mA"],["Confirmation","Paced spike → wide QRS → T wave","PLUS palpable pulse at paced rate","Mechanical capture required"],["Pad placement","Anterior-posterior or anterolateral","Reposition if no capture at max output","Ensure good skin contact"],["Patient comfort","N/A","Give analgesia/sedation if conscious","Assess hemodynamic tolerance"]]},{"id":"c10_t03","title":"Symptomatic vs Asymptomatic Bradycardia — Decision Guide","headers":["Feature","Symptomatic (Unstable)","Asymptomatic (Stable)"],"rows":[["Heart rate","Typically <50/min","Typically <50/min"],["Blood pressure","Hypotension (SBP <90 mmHg)","Normal or near-normal"],["Mental status","Acutely altered / confused","Clear, alert"],["Perfusion signs","Shock, diaphoresis, pallor","No signs of poor perfusion"],["Chest pain","Ischemic chest discomfort","None"],["Heart failure","Acute pulmonary edema / failure","None"],["Initial treatment","Atropine 1 mg IV, repeat to max 3 mg","Monitor, observe, investigate cause"],["Escalation","Pacing / dopamine / epinephrine infusion","Treat underlying cause if found"]]}]},"c11":{"chapter":"c11","tables":[{"id":"c11_t01","title":"Synchronized Cardioversion Energy by Rhythm (2025 AHA)","headers":["Rhythm","Type","Initial Energy (Biphasic)","Notes"],"rows":[["Narrow-complex regular (SVT)","Regular","100 J","After failed vagal maneuvers and adenosine"],["Atrial fibrillation","Irregular","≥200 J","May need higher energies on subsequent shocks"],["Atrial flutter","Regular or irregular","≥200 J","Same as AF"],["Monomorphic VT with pulse","Regular","100 J","Assume VT for all wide-complex regular tachycardias"],["Polymorphic VT","Irregular","UNSYNCHRONIZED defibrillation","Synchronization is CONTRAINDICATED"]]},{"id":"c11_t02","title":"Antiarrhythmic Drugs for Tachycardia With a Pulse","headers":["Drug","Indication","Dose","Key Considerations"],"rows":[["Adenosine","Stable narrow-complex regular SVT","6 mg rapid IV, then 12 mg (repeat once)","Proximal port + rapid flush; avoid in AF/flutter for rate control"],["Amiodarone","Stable wide-complex tachycardia","150 mg IV over 10 min (may repeat once)","First-line for regular wide-complex; also used for AF rate control"],["Procainamide","Stable wide-complex tachycardia (alternative)","20–50 mg/min IV (max 17 mg/kg)","Watch for hypotension; avoid in structural heart disease"],["Diltiazem","AF/AFlutter rate control","0.25 mg/kg IV over 2 min, then infusion","Calcium-channel blocker; avoid in pre-excited AF"],["Metoprolol","AF/AFlutter rate control","5 mg IV q5min (max 15 mg)","Beta-blocker; avoid in decompensated heart failure"],["Magnesium sulfate","Torsades de pointes","1–2 g IV over 5–60 min","Specific for polymorphic VT with prolonged QT"]]},{"id":"c11_t03","title":"Narrow vs Wide vs Irregular Tachycardia — Comparison","headers":["Feature","Narrow-Regular (SVT)","Narrow-Irregular (AF/Flutter)","Wide-Regular (assume VT)","Wide-Irregular (Poly VT / Pre-excited AF)"],"rows":[["QRS duration","<0.12 sec","<0.12 sec","≥0.12 sec","≥0.12 sec"],["Regularity","Regular","Irregularly irregular","Regular","Irregular"],["Most likely rhythm","AVNRT, AVRT","Atrial fibrillation","Ventricular tachycardia","Polymorphic VT or pre-excited AF"],["First-line (stable)","Vagal maneuvers → adenosine","Rate control (diltiazem, metoprolol)","Amiodarone 150 mg over 10 min","Defibrillate if poly VT; avoid AV-nodal blockers if pre-excited AF"],["First-line (unstable)","Synchronized cardioversion 100 J","Synchronized cardioversion ≥200 J","Synchronized cardioversion 100 J","Unsynchronized defibrillation (poly VT) or synchronized cardioversion"],["Key danger","Misidentifying VT as SVT","Rapid ventricular response causing ischemia","Giving verapamil if actually VT","AV-nodal blockers in pre-excited AF → VF"]]}]},"c12":{"chapter":"c12","tables":[{"id":"c12_t01","title":"ACS Initial Medication Summary","headers":["Medication","Dose","Route","Key Notes"],"rows":[["Aspirin","162–325 mg","PO (chewed)","First drug in ALL ACS — give immediately"],["Ticagrelor","180 mg loading, then 90 mg BID","PO","Preferred P2Y12 inhibitor; avoid with strong CYP3A4 inhibitors"],["Prasugrel","60 mg loading, then 10 mg daily","PO","CONTRAINDICATED with prior stroke/TIA, age ≥75, weight <60 kg"],["Clopidogrel","300–600 mg loading, then 75 mg daily","PO","Less effective than ticagrelor/prasugrel; use if P2Y12 inhibitor needed and others contraindicated"],["Unfractionated Heparin","60 U/kg bolus (max 4,000 U), then 12 U/kg/hr","IV","Titrate to aPTT; use with PCI and fibrinolysis"],["Nitroglycerin","0.4 mg SL q5min × 3 doses","SL","CONTRAINDICATED: RV infarction, PDE5 inhibitors, SBP <90"],["Morphine","2–4 mg IV","IV","CAUTION: delays P2Y12 absorption; reserve for refractory pain after NTG failure"],["Oxygen","Supplemental as needed","Nasal cannula/mask","ONLY if SpO₂ <90% or respiratory distress — not routine"]]},{"id":"c12_t02","title":"Nitroglycerin Contraindications in ACS","headers":["Contraindication","Mechanism","Clinical Clue"],"rows":[["Right ventricular infarction","RV is preload-dependent; NTG reduces preload → catastrophic hypotension","Inferior STEMI with hypotension; check V4R"],["PDE5 inhibitor use (sildenafil <24 h, tadalafil <48 h)","Synergistic vasodilation → severe hypotension","Ask about erectile dysfunction medications"],["Systolic BP <90 mmHg","Further BP reduction risks organ hypoperfusion","Check BP before each dose"],["Severe aortic stenosis","Fixed cardiac output; preload reduction causes hypotension","Known AS or systolic murmur"],["Hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy","Preload reduction worsens LVOT obstruction","Known HCM or dynamic murmur"]]},{"id":"c12_t03","title":"STEMI Reperfusion: Primary PCI vs Fibrinolysis","headers":["Parameter","Primary PCI","Fibrinolysis"],"rows":[["Time goal","FMC2D ≤90 minutes","Door-to-needle ≤30 minutes"],["Indication","First choice when achievable within 90 min","Onset <12 h AND anticipated PPCI delay >120 min"],["Drug","None (mechanical reperfusion)","Alteplase or tenecteplase"],["Post-treatment","N/A","Transfer for angiography within 3–24 h"],["If failed","N/A","Rescue PCI"],["Contraindications","None specific to PCI","Active bleeding, stroke <3 months, ICH, INR >1.7, platelets <100K, aortic dissection"],["Preferred when","PCI-capable center within 90 min","Non-PCI center with prolonged transfer time"]]}]},"c13":{"chapter":"c13","tables":[{"id":"c13_t01","title":"Blood Pressure Management in Acute Ischemic Stroke","headers":["Scenario","BP Target","Medication","Notes"],"rows":[["Pre-tPA (patient receiving tPA)","<185/110 mmHg","IV labetalol 10–20 mg over 1–2 min (repeat ×1) OR nicardipine 5 mg/hr (titrate ↑2.5 mg/hr q5–15 min, max 15 mg/hr)","Must achieve BEFORE tPA initiation"],["During and post-tPA (first 24 h)","<180/105 mmHg","Labetalol or nicardipine as above; reduce BP by ~15% in first 24 h","Continuous monitoring; avoid rebounds"],["Non-tPA candidate (first 24 h)","Permissive up to 220/120 mmHg","No treatment unless >220/120 or contraindications","Must confirm no ICH, no cardiac ischemia, no aortic dissection"],["Post-24 hours (all patients)","Treat according to underlying etiology","Per institutional protocol","Reassess goals after first 24 h"]]},{"id":"c13_t02","title":"IV tPA (Alteplase) Dosing and Administration for Stroke","headers":["Parameter","Detail"],"rows":[["Total dose","0.9 mg/kg IV (maximum 90 mg)"],["Bolus","10% of total dose IV over 1 minute"],["Infusion","Remaining 90% of total dose IV over 60 minutes"],["Time window","≤4.5 hours from symptom onset (last known normal)"],["Door-to-needle goal","≤30 minutes"],["Pre-tPA BP requirement","<185/110 mmHg"],["Post-tPA BP requirement","<180/105 mmHg for ≥24 hours"],["Mandatory imaging","Non-contrast CT head (exclude hemorrhage)"],["Key contraindications","ICH on CT, active bleeding, stroke <3 months, INR >1.7, platelets <100K, glucose <50, multilobar infarction >1/3 hemisphere"]]},{"id":"c13_t03","title":"Stroke Screening Tools Comparison","headers":["Tool","Components","Setting","Key Feature"],"rows":[["Cincinnati Prehospital Stroke Scale (CPSS)","Facial droop, arm drift, speech abnormality","Prehospital / EMS","Any 1 of 3 abnormal = high probability of stroke"],["FAST mnemonic","Face, Arms, Speech, Time","Public-facing / BLS","Emphasizes time to activate EMS"],["NIH Stroke Scale (NIHSS)","11 items (consciousness, gaze, visual fields, facial palsy, motor, ataxia, sensory, language, dysarthria, extinction)","Hospital / neurology","Quantifies stroke severity (0–42); guides treatment decisions"]]}]},"c14":{"chapter":"c14","tables":[{"id":"c14_t01","title":"Post-ROSC Management Targets","headers":["Parameter","Target","Intervention","Notes"],"rows":[["MAP","≥65 mmHg (SBP >90)","Norepinephrine 0.1–0.5 mcg/kg/min, IV fluid bolus 250–500 mL","Avoid MAP <60 or >100"],["ETCO₂","35–45 mmHg","Mechanical ventilation adjustment","Avoid hypo- and hyperventilation"],["Temperature","≤37.5°C (minimum); 32–37.5°C if TTM","Active cooling, antipyretics, cooling catheters/pads","Continuous monitoring; treat fever >37.5°C immediately"],["TTM duration","≥36 hours","Maintain target range","Rewarm at ≤0.25°C/hr"],["Glucose","70–180 mg/dL","Insulin protocol; dextrose if hypoglycemic","Avoid both hypo- and hyperglycemia"],["Oxygenation","SpO₂ ≥94%","Adjust FiO₂ as needed","Avoid hyperoxia if possible"],["12-lead ECG","Obtain immediately","Identify STEMI → emergent PCI","Present in ~25–50% of post-arrest patients"]]},{"id":"c14_t02","title":"Multimodal Neuroprognostication After Cardiac Arrest","headers":["Modality","Timing","Finding Suggesting Poor Prognosis","Notes"],"rows":[["Clinical exam","≥72 h post-ROSC (after sedation/paralysis clearance)","Bilateral absent pupillary + corneal reflexes; absent motor response or extensor posturing","Must be after sedation/paralysis/metabolic clearance"],["SSEPs","≥72 h post-ROSC","Bilateral absence of cortical N20 response","High specificity; less affected by sedation"],["Continuous EEG","Within first days, interpreted at ≥72 h","Status myoclonus, burst suppression without epileptiform discharges, malignant patterns","Requires expert interpretation"],["NSE (neuron-specific enolase)","48–72 h post-ROSC",">33 mcg/L","Must be interpreted in multimodal context; single value not sufficient"],["S-100B protein","48–72 h post-ROSC","Elevated levels","Less specific than NSE; adjunctive marker"],["CT head","First 24–48 h","Diffuse cerebral edema, loss of gray-white differentiation","Early CT may be normal; CT at 48–72 h more informative"],["MRI brain","3–5 days post-ROSC","Restricted diffusion in cortical and deep gray matter","Most sensitive imaging modality for hypoxic-ischemic injury"]]},{"id":"c14_t03","title":"ECPR: Indications, Contraindications, and Key Parameters","headers":["Category","Detail"],"rows":[["Indication","Refractory cardiac arrest (persistent VF/pVT despite standard ACLS: high-quality CPR, ≥3 shocks, epinephrine, antiarrhythmic)"],["Expected low-flow time","<60 minutes from CPR initiation to ECMO flow"],["Reversible cause","Required — acute MI, PE, myocarditis, drug toxicity, hypothermia, etc."],["Candidacy","Consider age, comorbidities, pre-arrest functional status; no absolute contraindications"],["Cannulation","Femoral: venous drainage (femoral vein) + arterial return (femoral artery), percutaneous under US guidance"],["Limb protection","Distal perfusion catheter recommended to prevent limb ischemia"],["Complications","Limb ischemia, bleeding, cannula malposition, hemolysis, infection"],["ECPR role","Bridge to further therapy (PCI, TTM, recovery) — NOT destination therapy"],["Weaning","Guided by echocardiographic recovery, hemodynamic stability on decreasing flow, clinical assessment"],["Institutional requirement","Experienced, high-volume team with dedicated ECPR infrastructure"]]}]}}};
